\id ISA Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h Isaie
\mt1 The Prophecy of Isaie.
\c 1
\p
\v 1 The vision of Isaie the son of Amos, which he saw concerning Juda and Jerusalem in the days of Ozias, Joathan, Achaz, and Ezechias, kings of Juda. \f + \fr 1:1 \ft Not Amos the third of the less prophets, for this name is written in other letters in Hebrew: but one of the royal blood as S. Ierom. testifieth.\f*
\v 2 Hear ye heavens, & give ear o earth, because our Lord hath spoken. I have brought up children, and exalted them: but they have despised me.
\v 3 The oxe hath known his owner, and the ass his master's crib: but Israel hath not known me, and my people hath not understood.
\v 4 Woe to the sinful nation, the people laden with grievous iniquity, the wicked seed, ungracious children: they have forsaken our Lord, they have blasphemed the holy one of Israel, they are revolted backwards.
\v 5 For what shall I strike you any more, which add prevarication? Every head is sick, & every heart in heaviness. \f + \fr 1:5 \ft Prince, Priest, and people are all sick of ingratitude against God, & other iniquities.\f*
\v 6 From the sole of the foot unto the top of the head, there is no health therein: wound, and wail, and swelling stroke: it is not bound up, nor cured with medicine, nor mollified with oil.
\v 7 Your land is desolate, your cities burnt with fire: your country strangers devour before your face, and it shall be made desolate as in the spoil of enemies.
\v 8 And the daughter of Sion shall be left as a vineyard, and as a cottage in a place of cucumbers, and as a city that is wasted. \f + \fr 1:8 \ft Jerusalem defaced and destroyed.\f*
\v 9 Unless the Lord of hosts had left us seed, we had been as Sodom, and we should be like to Gomorrha. \f + \fr 1:9 \ft God continually preserveth some holy seed, that his Church never faileth.\f* \x + \xo 1:9 \xt Rom. 9.\x*
\v 10 Hear the word of our Lord ye Princes of Sodom, give ear to the law of our God ye people of Gomorrha.
\v 11 To what purpose do you offer me the multitude of your victims, saith our Lord? I am full, the holocaust of rams, and the fat of fatlings, and the blood of calves, and lambs, and buck goats I have not desired.
\v 12 When you should have come before my sight, who sought for these things at your hands, that you should walk in my courts?
\v 13 Offer sacrifice no more in vain: incense is abomination to me. The New moon, and the Sabbath, and other festivities I will not abide, your assemblies are wicked.
\v 14 My soul hateth your Calends, and your solemnities: they are become tedious to me, I have laboured in sustaining.
\v 15 And when you shall stretch forth your hands, I will turn away mine eyes from you: & when you shall multiply prayer, I will not hear: for your hands are full of blood.
\v 16 Wash you, be clean, take away the evil of your cogitations from mine eyes: cease to do perversely,
\v 17 Learn to do good: seek judgement, succour the oppressed, judge for the pupil, defend the widow.
\v 18 And come, and accuse me, saith our Lord: if your sins shall be as scarlet, they shall be made white as snow: and if they be red as vermilion, they shall be white as wool.
\v 19 If you be willing, and will hear me, you shall eat the good things of the earth.
\v 20 But if you will not, and will provoke me to wrath: the sword shall devour you, because the mouth of our Lord hath spoken.
\v 21 How is the faithful city full of judgement become an harlot? Justice hath dwelled in it, but now mankillers. \f + \fr 1:21 \ft Much wickedness reigned in Jerusalem before their captivity in Babylon; but much more at Christ's passion, when they persecuted him even to the Cross: and his disciples, and all Christians, till their city was taken by the Romans, and the whole nation dispersed.\f*
\v 22 Thy silver is turned into dross: thy wine is mingled with water.
\v 23 Thy princes are unfaithful, companions of thieves: all love gifts, follow rewards. They judge not for the pupil: and the widow's cause goeth not in to them.
\v 24 For this cause saith our Lord the God of hosts the mighty one of Israel: Alas! I will comfort myself upon mine adversaries: and will be revenged of mine enemies.
\v 25 And I will turn mine hand to thee, and I will boil out thy dross till it be pure, & will take away all thy tin.
\v 26 And I will restore thy judges as they have been before, and thy counsellers as of old. After these things thou shalt be called the just, a faithful city. \f + \fr 1:26 \ft The Rabbins understand those Judges and Priests that\f*
\v 27 Sion shall be redeemed in judgement, and they shall bring her back in justice.
\v 28 And he shall destroy the wicked and the sinners together: and they that have forsaken our Lord, shall be consumed.
\v 29 For they shall be confounded for the idols, to which they have sacrificed: and you shall be ashamed of the gardens, which you chose.
\v 30 When you shall be as an oak the leaves falling off, and as a garden without water.
\v 31 And your strength shall be as the ashes of tow, and your work as a spark: and both shall be set on fire together, and there shall be none to quench it.
\c 2
\p
\v 1 The word that Isaie the son of Amos saw upon Juda and Jerusalem.
\v 2 And in the later days the mountain of the house of our Lord shall be prepared, in the top of mountains, and it shall be elevated above the little hills: and all nations shall flow unto it. \f + \fr 2:2 \ft It is not only certain, but also evident that the prophet speaketh here, and in innumerable other places, of the Church of Christ, which is the city set upon a mountain, Mat. 5. unto which all nations are gathered, and all the time of the new Testament is called the last hour, 1. Ioan. 2. because no time shall follow after this, but all eternity.\f*
\v 3 And many peoples shall go, & shall say, come and let us go up to the mount of our Lord, and to the house of the God of Jacob, and he will teach us his ways, and we shall walk in his paths: because the law shall come forth from Sion, and the word of our Lord from Jerusalem.
\v 4 And he shall judge the Gentiles, and rebuke many peoples: and they shall turn their swords into coulters, and their spears into sithes: nation shall not lift up sword against nation, neither shall they be exercised any more to battle.
\v 5 House of Jacob come ye and let us walk in the light of our Lord.
\v 6 For thou hast rejected thy people, the house of Jacob: because they are filled as in times past, and have had soothsayers as the Philisthiims, and have struck fast to strange children. \f + \fr 2:6 \ft The Jews were rejected after Christ's death: before which they were still conserved: though often severely punished. And so now the Church of Christ shall never be rejected.\f*
\v 7 The land is replenished with silver and gold: and there is no end to their treasures.
\v 8 And their land is replenished with horses: and their chariots are innumerable. And their land is full of idols: they have adored the work of their hands, which their fingers made.
\v 9 And man bowed himself, and man was humbled: therefore forgive them not.
\v 10 Enter thou into the rock, and be hid in a pit, in the ground from the face of the fear of our Lord, & from the glory of his majesty.
\v 11 The lofty eyes of man are humbled, and the height of men shall be made to stoop: & our Lord only shall be exalted in that day.
\v 12 Because the day of the Lord of hosts shall be upon all the proud and lofty, and upon every one that is arrogant, and he shall be humbled.
\v 13 And upon all the cedars of Libanus high & elevated, & upon all the oaks of Basan.
\v 14 And upon all the high mountains, and upon all little hills elevated.
\v 15 And upon every high tower, and every fenced wall.
\v 16 And upon all the ships of Tharsis, and upon all that is fair to behold.
\v 17 And the loftiness of men shall be bowed, and the height of men shall be humbled, and our Lord only shall be exalted in that day.
\v 18 And idols shall utterly be destroyed. \f + \fr 2:18 \ft It is most absurd, and contrary to this and other Scriptures, that Protestants feign of great idolatry in the Christian world, for a thousand or more years together, professing Christ's name & Religion, and yet continually committing (as these new masters imagine) gross idolatry.\f*
\v 19 And they shall enter into the caves of rocks, and into the pits of the earth from the face of the fear of our Lord, and from the glory of his majesty, when he shall rise up to strike the earth.
\v 20 In that day shall a man cast away the idols of his silver, and the idols of his gold, which he had made him to adore, moles and bats.
\v 21 And he shall go into the clefts of rocks, and into the caves of stones from the face of the fear of our Lord, and from the glory of his majesty, when he shall rise up to strike the earth.
\v 22 Cease therefore from the man, whose spirit is in his nostrils, because he is reputed high.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 For behold the dominatour the Lord of hosts shall take away from Jerusalem, and from Juda the valiant & the strong, all strength of bread, and all strength of water. \f + \fr 3:1 \ft This was fulfilled first in the captivity of Babylon, and more notoriously after Christ's passion, in the destruction of Ierusalem, and dispersion of the Jews, even to this day: and yet forward, till near the end of this world.\f*
\v 2 The strong, and the man of war, the judge, and the prophet, and soothsayer, and the ancient.
\v 3 The prince over fifty, and the honourable of countenance, and the counseller, and the wise of workmasters, and the skillful of mystical speech.
\v 4 And I will give children to be their princes, and the effeminate shall rule over them.
\v 5 And the people shall rush violently, man against man, and every one against his neighbour: the child shall make tumult against the ancient, and the base against the noble.
\v 6 For a man shall take hold of his brother, one of the house of his father: Thou hast a garment, be thou our prince, and let this ruin be under thy hand.
\v 7 He shall answer in that day, saying: I am no physician, & in my house there is no bread, nor garment: do not appoint me prince of the people.
\v 8 For Jerusalem is gone to ruin, and Juda is fallen: because their tongue & their inventions were against our Lord, to provoke the eyes of his majesty.
\v 9 The knowledge of their face hath answered them: and they have proclaimed their sin as Sodom, neither have they hid it: woe to their soul, because evils are rendered to them.
\v 10 Say to the just that it is well, because he shall eat the fruit of his inventions.
\v 11 Woe to the impious unto evil: for the reward of his hands shall be made to him.
\v 12 My people their exactors have spoiled, & women have ruled over them. My people, they that call thee blessed, the same deceive thee, & dissipate the way of thy steps. \f + \fr 3:12 \ft An Ecclesiastical preacher must not flatter the people. He must move tears (saith S. Ierom) not laughter.\f*
\v 13 Our Lord standeth to judge, & he standeth to judge peoples. \x + \xo 3:13 \xt Apoc. 1.\x*
\v 14 Our Lord shall come to judgement with the ancients of his people, and his princes: for you have devoured the vineyard, and the spoil of the poor is in your house.
\v 15 Why do you consume my people, and grind the faces of the poor, saith our Lord the God of hosts?
\v 16 And our Lord said: for that the daughters of Sion are haughty, and have walked with stretched out neck, and went with twinglings of eyes, and clapped their hands, walked on their feet, and jetted in a set pace. \f + \fr 3:16 \ft By the metaphor of women, S. Ierom. understandeth the cities of Jury, of which Jerusalem was the head, and Sion the chief place thereof, all which were defaced by the Babylonians, but more fully destroyed by Titus and Vespasian, forty years after Christ's passion.\f*
\v 17 Our Lord shall make bald the crown of the daughters of Sion, and our Lord shall discover their hair.
\v 18 In that day shall our Lord take away the ornament of shoes, and little moons.
\v 19 And chains, and ouches, and bracelets, and bonnets.
\v 20 And the shedding combs, and slops, and tablets, and sweet balls, and earlets.
\v 21 And rings, and pearls hanging on the forehead.
\v 22 And changes of apparel, and short cloaks, and the fine linen, and needles,
\v 23 and looking glasses, and lawns, and headbands, and bongraces.
\v 24 And for sweet savour there shall be stink, and for a girdle a cord, and for frizzled hair baldness, and for stomacher haircloth.
\v 25 Thy fairest men also shall fall by the sword, and thy strong ones in battle.
\v 26 And her gates shall lament and mourn, and she shall sit desolate on the ground.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 And seven women shall take hold of one man in that day, saying: We will eat our own bread, and be covered with our garments: only let thy name be called upon us, take away our reproach. \f + \fr 4:1 \ft After the reduction of heathenish or heretical people to Catholic religion, there will be great want of spiritual pastors.\f*
\v 2 In that day the bud of our Lord shall be in magnificence, and glory, and the fruit of the earth high, and exultation to them, that shall be saved of Israel.
\v 3 And it shall be: Every one that shall be left in Sion, and shall remain in Jerusalem, shall be called holy, every one that is written in life in Jerusalem. \f + \fr 4:3 \ft Not all the Jews that escaped temporal death in the destruction of Jerusalem, but those only shall be eternally saved, that believing shall be baptized and live well.\f*
\v 4 If our Lord shall cleanse the filth of the daughters of Sion, and shall wash the blood of Jerusalem out of the midst thereof in the spirit of judgement, and spirit of heat.
\v 5 And our Lord shall create upon every place of mount Sion, and where he is invocated, a cloud by day, and smoke, and the brightness of flaming fire in the night: for upon all glory protection.
\v 6 And there shall be a tabernacle for a place of shadow in the day from the heat, and for security, and covert from the whirlwind, and from rain.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 I will sing to my beloved the canticle of my cousin concerning his vineyard. A vineyard was made to my beloved in horn, the son of oil. \f + \fr 5:1 \ft Isaie of the tribe of Juda here prophesieth the doleful song which Christ uttered over Jerusalem, foreseeing & foretelling their destruction. Luc. 19. v. 41.\f* \x + \xo 5:1 \xt Mat. 21.\x*
\v 2 And he hedged it, and chose stones out of it, and planted it elect, and built a tower in the midst thereof, and set up a press therein: and looked that it should yield grapes, and it yielded wild grapes.
\v 3 Now therefore ye inhabitants of Jerusalem, and men of Juda, judge between me and my vineyard.
\v 4 What is there that I ought to do more to my vineyard, and have not done to it? Whether that I looked, it should yield grapes, and it hath yielded wild grapes?
\v 5 And now I will shew you what I will do to my vineyard. I will take away the hedge thereof, and it shall be into spoil: I will throw down the wall thereof, and it shall be to be trodden upon. \f + \fr 5:5 \ft All this sheweth that God only subtracting his protection, no man nor people is able to stand; of whose ruin God is not the author, but only permitteth that they fall into sins, and so into other miseries.\f*
\v 6 And I will lay it waste: it shall not be pruned, and it shall not be digged: and briers and thorns shall overgrow it: and I will command the clouds that they rain no shower upon it.
\v 7 For the vineyard of the Lord of hosts, is the house of Israel: and the man of Juda, his delectable bud: & I looked that it should do judgement, and behold iniquity: and justice, and behold clamour.
\v 8 Woe to you that join house to house, and lay field to field, even to the end of the place: why shall you alone dwell in the midst of the earth?
\v 9 These things are in my ears, saith the Lord of hosts: unless many great and fair houses become desolate, without an inhabiter.
\v 10 For ten acres of the vineyards shall yield one little flagon, and thirty bushels of seed shall yield three bushels.
\v 11 Woe to you that rise up early to follow drunkenness, & to drink even until evening, that you may be inflamed with wine.
\v 12 Harp, and viol, & timbrel, and shalm, & wine in your feasts: and the work of our Lord you regard not, nor consider the works of his hands. \f + \fr 5:12 \ft An admonition to celebrate festival days with holy religious exercises, and not to follow drunkenness nor other wicked or vain things.\f*
\v 13 Therefore is my people led away captive, because they had not knowledge, and their nobles died with famine, and the multitude thereof dried away with thirst.
\v 14 Therefore hath hell dilated his soul, and opened his mouth without any limit: and their strong ones, and their people, and their high and glorious ones shall descend into it.
\v 15 And man shall be bowed, and man shall be humbled, and the eyes of the lofty shall be brought low.
\v 16 And the Lord of hosts shall be exalted in judgement, and the holy God shall be sanctified in justice.
\v 17 And the lambs shall feed according to their order, and strangers shall eat the deserts turned into fruitfulness.
\v 18 Woe to you that draw iniquity in cords of vanity, & sin as the link of a wain.
\v 19 Which say: let him make haste, & let his work come quickly, that we may see it: & let the counsel of the holy one of Israel come, and we shall know it.
\v 20 Woe unto you that call evil good; & good evil: putting darkness light, and light darkness: putting bitter for sweet, & sweet for bitter.
\v 21 Woe to you that are wise in your own eyes, and prudent before yourselves. \x + \xo 5:21 \xt Rom. 12.\x*
\v 22 Woe to you that are mighty to drink wine, & stout men in drunkenness.
\v 23 Which justify the impious for gifts, and take away the justice of the just from them.
\v 24 For this, even as the tongue of fire devoureth stubble, and the heat of the flame burneth it up: so shall their root be as ashes, and their bud shall rise up as dust, for they have cast away the law of the Lord of hosts, and have blasphemed the word of the holy one of Israel.
\v 25 Therefore is the fury of our Lord wrath against his people, and he hath stretched out his hand upon them, & strucken them: and the mountains were troubled, and their carcasses were made as dung in the midst of the streets. In all these things his fury is not turned away, but yet is his hand stretched forth. \f + \fr 5:25 \ft Grievous sins must be grievously punished. Such as was the sin of the Jews persecuting Christ.\f*
\v 26 And he shall lift up a sign in the nations a far, and shall whistle to him of the ends of the earth: and behold he shall come in haste speedily.
\v 27 There is none that fainteth, nor that laboureth in them, he will not slumber, nor sleep, neither shall the girdle of his reins be loosed, neither shall the latchet of his shoe be broken.
\v 28 His arrows sharp, and all his bows bent. The hoofs of his horses as the flint, & his wheels as the violence of a tempest.
\v 29 His roaring as a lion's, he shall roar as lions' whelps: and he will gnash, and hold the prey, and clasp it, and there shall be none to pluck it away.
\v 30 And it shall sound upon him in that day, as the sound of the sea: we shall look towards the earth, and behold darkness of tribulation, and the light is darkened in the mist thereof.
\c 6
\p
destroyed, but good relics shall be conserved.
\v 1 In the year that king Ozias died, I saw our Lord sitting upon an high throne and elevated: and those things that were under him filled the temple. \x + \xo 6:1 \xt 4. Reg. 15. 2. Par. 26.\x*
\v 2 Seraphims stood upon the same: six wings to one, and six wings to the other: with two they covered his face, and with two they covered his feet, and with two they flew. \f + \fr 6:2 \ft Neither Isaie, nor Moyses, nor any other mortal man did ever see God in himself, but only shadowed. Yet the wicked calumniously accused, condemned, and put Isaie to cruel death, upon pretence of blasphemy, for saying that he saw God. Which he otherwise said not, but covered by the wings of the Seraphims. Origen in hunc locum, & S. Ierom Tradi. Hebraicis in Paral.\f*
\v 3 And they cried one to another, and said: Holy, holy, holy, the Lord God of hosts, all the earth is full of his glory. \x + \xo 6:3 \xt Apo. 4. Rom. 11.\x*
\v 4 And the lintels of the doors were moved at the voice of him that cried, & the house was filled with smoke.
\v 5 And I said: Woe is me because I have held my peace, because I am a man of polluted lips, and I dwell in the midst of a people that hath polluted lips, and the King the Lord of hosts I have seen with mine eyes.
\v 6 And one of the Seraphims flew to me, & in his hand an hot coal, which he had taken with tongs from the altar.
\v 7 And he touched my mouth, and said: Behold this hath touched thy lips, and thine iniquity shall be taken away, & thy sin shall be cleansed.
\v 8 And I heard the voice of our Lord saying: Whom shall I send? And who shall go for us? And I said: Lo I am here, send me. \f + \fr 6:8 \ft Isaie was not only an Evangelical but also an Apostolical prophet, with whom God here treateth and proceedeth, as with an Apostle, saying: Whom shall I send? and the prophet answering: Send me, God sent him, saying: Go &c. S. Ierom in Prooemio Isaie.\f*
\v 9 And he said: Go, and thou shalt say to this people: Hear ye that hear, and understand not: and see the vision, & know it not. \x + \xo 6:9 \xt Mat. 21.\x*
\v 10 Blind the heart of this people, and make their ears heavy, and shut their eyes: lest perhaps they may see with their eyes, and hear with their ears, and understand with their heart, and be converted and I heal them.
\v 11 And I said: How long Lord? And he said: Until the cities be made desolate without inhabiter, and the houses without man, and the land shall be left desert.
\v 12 And our Lord shall make men go far off, and he shall be multiplied that was left in the midst of the earth.
\v 13 And yet there shall be tithing in it, and she shall be converted, and shall be to the shew as a terebinth, and as an oak, that spreadeth his boughs: that which shall stand in it, shall be an holy seed.
\c 7
\p
\v 1 And it came to pass in the days of Achaz the son of Joathan, the son of Ozias king of Juda, there came up Rasin the king of Syria, and Phacee the son of Romelia the king of Israel, to Jerusalem to fight against it: and they could not overcome it. \f + \fr 7:1 \ft Before this the kings of Syria and of Israel had taken King Achaz in battle, and carried away great spoils, 2. Paral. 28. But presuming, to do the like again, God suffered them not to prevail. Mystically this signified that heretics of diverse sects conspire together, to impugn the Catholic Church. Which they do much afflict, and terrify, but can never overthrow it. S. Ierom in hunc locum.\f* \x + \xo 7:1 \xt 4. Reg. 16.\x*
\v 2 And they told the house of David, saying: Syria hath rested upon Ephraim, and his heart was moved, and the heart of his people, as the trees of the woods are moved at the face of the wind.
\v 3 And our Lord said to Isaie: Go forth to meet Achaz, thou, and Jasub thy son that is left, to the conduit of the upper pool, in the way of the Fuller's field.
\v 4 And thou shalt say to him: See thou be still: fear not, and let not thine heart be afraid of the two tails of these smoking firebrands, in the wrath of the fury of Rasin the king of Syria, and of the son of Romelia.
\v 5 For that Syria hath taken counsel against thee, unto the evil of Ephraim, and the son of Romelia, saying:
\v 6 Let us go up to Juda, and raise it up, and pluck it away to us, and make the son of Tabeel king in the midst thereof.
\v 7 Thus saith our Lord God: It shall not stand, & this shall not be.
\v 8 But the head of Syria Damascus, & the head of Damascus, Rasin: and yet threescore and five years, and Ephraim shall cease to be a people:
\v 9 And the head of Ephraim Samaria, and the head of Samaria the son of Romelia. If you will not believe, you shall not be permanent.
\v 10 And our Lord added to speak to Achaz, saying.
\v 11 Ask a sign for thee of the Lord thy God unto the depth of hell, or unto the height above.
\v 12 And Achaz said: I will not ask, and I will not tempt our Lord. \f + \fr 7:12 \ft Though Achaz was very wicked and committed idolatry, 4. Reg. 16. 2. Par. 28. yet he believed in God Almighty, knowing that he ought not to tempt him.\f*
\v 13 And he said: Hear ye therefore o house of David: Is it a small thing for you, to be grievous to men, that you are grievous to my God also?
\v 14 Therefore shall our Lord himself give you a sign. Behold a Virgin shall conceive, and bear a son, & his name shall be called Emmanuel. \f + \fr 7:14 \ft Upon occasion of God's mercy provised without man's desert, which King Achaz hardly believed, to confirm the same with a far greater example, God inspired the Prophet also to foreshew the greater mystery of Christ's Incarnation, his conception & birth of a virgin, for the redemption of all mankind.\f*
\v 15 He shall eat butter and honey, that he may know to refuse evil, and choose the good.
\v 16 For before the child know to refuse evil, and choose good, the land which thou doest detest shall be forsaken of the face of her two kings.
\v 17 Our Lord will bring upon thee, & upon thy people, and upon the house of thy father, days that came not since the days of the separation of Ephraim from Juda, with the king of the Assyrians.
\v 18 And it shall be in that day: our Lord shall hiss to the fly, that is in the uttermost part of the rivers of Ægypt, and to the bee, that is in the land of Assur.
\v 19 And they shall come, and shall rest all in the torrents of valleys, and in the caves of rocks, and in all shrub places, and in all holes. \x + \xo 7:19 \xt 4. Reg. 9.\x*
\v 20 In that day our Lord shall shave with a razor, hired by them, that are beyond the river, by the king of the Assyrians, the head, and the hairs of the feet, and the whole beard.
\v 21 And it shall be in that day: a man shall nourish a young cow, and two ewes.
\v 22 And for the aboundance of milk he shall eat butter: for butter and honey shall every one eat, that shall be left in the midst of the land.
\v 23 And it shall be in that day: every place where there shall be a thousand vines, for a thousand pieces of silver, they shall be into thorns and briers.
\v 24 With arrows & bow they shall go in thither: for briers and thorns shall be in all the land.
\v 25 And all mountains, that shall be weeded with a weeding hook, the terror of thorns and briers shall not come thither, and it shall be for the oxe to feed on, and cattle to tread upon.
\c 8
\p
\v 1 And our Lord said to me: Take thee a great book, & write in it with the pen of man. Take away the spoils speedily, quickly take preys. \f + \fr 8:1 \ft The mystery here prophesied is of so great importance, as would require a very great book for full explication\f*
\v 2 And I took to me faithful witnesses, Urias the Priest, & Zacharias the son of Barachias.
\v 3 And I went to the Prophetess, and she conceived, and bare a son. And our Lord said to me: Call his name, Hasten to take away the spoils: make haste to take preys. \f + \fr 8:3 \ft Christ the Son of God and a Virgin's child quickly taketh the prey from the devil, who before possessed almost all the world.\f*
\v 4 For before the child know to call his father and his mother, the strength of Damascus shall be taken away, and the spoils of Samaria before the king of the Assyrians.
\v 5 And our Lord added yet to speak unto me, saying:
\v 6 For that this people hath cast away the waters of Siloe, that run with silence, and rather taken Rasin, and the son of Romelia: \f + \fr 8:6 \ft The Prophet speaketh of the ten tribes, which joined forces with the king of Syria against Jerusalem, but themselves were first brought into captivity by the Assyrians, God protecting Jerusalem for that time, and long after.\f*
\v 7 for this cause behold our Lord will bring upon them the waters of the river strong and many, the king of the Assyrians, and all his glory: and he will ascend over all their rivers, and will flow over all their banks.
\v 8 And will go through Juda, overflowing, and passing through shall come even to the neck. And the stretching out of his wings shall fill the breadth of thy land o Emmanuel.
\v 9 Gather ye together o peoples, and be overcome, and hear all ye lands far off: Take courage, and be overcome, gird yourselves, & be overcome.
\v 10 Take counsel and it shall be defeated: speak a word, and it shall not be done: because God is with us.
\v 11 For thus saith our Lord to me: As in a strong arm he hath taught me, that I should not walk in the way of this people, saying:
\v 12 Say not, Conspiracy: for all things that this people speaketh, is conspiracy: and fear ye not their fear, neither dread ye.
\v 13 The Lord of hosts him sanctify ye: be he your dread, and he your terror.
\v 14 And he shall be a sanctification to you. But for a stone of offence, and for a rock of scandal to the two houses of Israel, for a snare & a ruin to the inhabitants of Jerusalem. \x + \xo 8:14 \xt Luc. 2. Rom. 9. 2. Pet. 2.\x*
\v 15 And very many of them shall stumble and fall, and shall be broken in pieces, and shall be snared, and taken.
\v 16 Bind the testimony, seal the law in my disciples.
\v 17 And I will expect our Lord, who hath hid his face from the house of Jacob, and I will wait for him.
\v 18 Behold I and my children, whom our Lord hath given me for a sign, and for a wonder in Israel from the Lord of hosts, which dwelleth in mount Sion.
\v 19 And when they shall say to you: Ask of Pythons, and of diviners, which whisper in their enchantments: shall not the people ask vision of their God, for the living of the dead?
\v 20 To the law rather, and to the testimony. As if they speak not according to this word, they shall not have the morning light.
\v 21 And he shall pass by it, shall fall, and be hungry: and when he shall be hungry, he will be angry, and curse his king, and his God, and will look upwards. \f + \fr 8:21 \ft Whether they seek to God in their extreme distress, not sincerely, but coacted, or seek worldly help, they shall not escape misery.\f*
\v 22 And he will look to the earth, and behold tribulation and darkness, dissolution and distress, and mist persecuting, and he cannot fly away from his distress.
\c 9
\p
\v 1 At the first time was the land of Zabulon alleviated, and the land of Nephthali: and at the last was aggravated the way of the sea beyond Jordan of Galilee of the Gentiles. \f + \fr 9:1 \ft S. Matthew expoundeth this prophecy of Christ, first preaching in Galilee. Where his disciples believed in him & followed him.\f* \f + \fr 9:1 \ft But after his passion few Jews believed in him, in comparison of the Gentiles.\f* \x + \xo 9:1 \xt Mat. 4.\x*
\v 2 The people that walked in darkness, hath seen great light: to them that dwelt in the country of the shadow of death, light is risen.
\v 3 Thou hast multiplied the nation, & not magnified the joy. They shall rejoice before thee, as they that rejoice in harvest, as conquerors rejoice after a prey is taken, when they divide the spoils.
\v 4 For the yoke of their burden, and the rod of their shoulder, and the sceptre of their exactor thou hast overcome, as in the day of Madian. \x + \xo 9:4 \xt Iudic. 7.\x*
\v 5 Because all violent taking of prey with tumult, and garment mingled with blood, shall be to be burnt, and food for the fire.
\v 6 For \sc A little Child is Born\sc* TO US, and a son is given to us, and his principality is made upon his shoulder: and his name shall be called, Marvelous, Counseller, God, Strong, Father of the world to come, the Prince of peace: \f + \fr 9:6 \ft He that is great, yea omnipotent God, is born a little one in this world, and without violence conquereth & ruleth all the world.\f* \x + \xo 9:6 \xt Luc. 2.\x*
\v 7 His empire shall be multiplied, and there shall be no end of peace: he shall sit upon the throne of David, and upon his kingdom: that he may confirm it, and strengthen it in judgement and justice, from this time & for ever: the zeal of the Lord of hosts shall do this.
\v 8 Our Lord hath sent a word into Jacob, and it is fallen in Israel.
\v 9 And all the people of Ephraim shall know, & the inhabitants of Samaria, saying in pride & greatness of heart:
\v 10 Bricks are fallen, but we will build with square stones: they have cut down sycamores, but we will change them into cedars.
\v 11 And our Lord shall lift up the enemies of Rasin over him, and shall turn his enemies into tumult.
\v 12 Syria from the East, and the Philisthims from the West: and they shall devour Israel with full mouth. In all these things his fury is not turned away, but his hand is yet stretched forth. \f + \fr 9:12 \ft God punishing sinners, and they not repenting, his just fury still increaseth: punishing eternally all those that never repent.\f*
\v 13 And the people is not returned to him, who hath strucken them, and have not sought after the Lord of hosts.
\v 14 And our Lord shall destroy from Israel the head & the tail, the perverter and restrainer in one day.
\v 15 The aged and honourable, he is the head, & the prophet that teacheth a lie, he is the tail.
\v 16 And they that call this people blessed, seducing them: and that are called blessed, shall be thrown headlong.
\v 17 For this cause our Lord shall not rejoice upon their young men: and on their pupils and widows he shall not have mercy: because every one is an hypocrite & wicked, and every mouth hath spoken folly. In all these things his fury is not turned away, but his hand is yet stretched forth.
\v 18 For impiety is kindled as a fire, it shall devour brier & thorn: & it shall be kindled in the thicket of the forest, and it shall be wrapped up together in the pride of smoke.
\v 19 In the wrath of the Lord of hosts the earth is troubled, and the people shall be food for the fire: man shall not spare his brother.
\v 20 And he shall decline to the right hand, and shall be hungry: and shall eat on the left hand, and shall not be filled: every one shall eat the flesh of his arm: Manasses Ephraim, and Ephraim Manasses, they together against Juda.
\v 21 In all these things his fury is not turned away, but his hand is yet stretched forth. \f + \fr 9:21 \ft Where is no repentance, there can be no remission. As v. 12. 17. & ch. 10. v. 4. &c.\f*
\c 10
\p
God: 21. and the Jews delivered from imminent danger: \add with diverse mysteries of Christ intermixed.\add*
\v 1 Woe to them that make wicked laws: and writing, have written injustice. \f + \fr 10:1 \ft Whereas good laws are the stability of the commonwealth, wicked are the ruin thereof. Such as Jeroboam made forbidding to go to Jerusalem and setting up golden calves in Bethel and Dan: causing the people to serve them as the gods of Israel. 3. Reg. 12. v. 16. Such also as the Scribes and Pharisees made devising wicked traditions, contrary to God's commandments. Mat. 15. v. 5.\f*
\v 2 That they might oppress the poor in judgement, & do violence to the cause of the humble of my people: that widows might be their prey, and they might spoil pupils.
\v 3 What will you do in the day, of visitation & of calamity coming from far? To whose help will ye fly? And where will ye leave your glory?
\v 4 That you be not bowed under the bond, and fall with the slain? In all these things his fury is not turned away, but his hand is yet stretched forth.
\v 5 Woe to Assur, he is the rod of my fury, & the staff: mine indignation is in their hands.
\v 6 I will send him to a deceitful nation, & will give him commandment against the people of my fury, that he take away spoils, and catch the prey, and put them to be trodden upon, as the mire of the streets. \f + \fr 10:6 \ft The Jews are called a deceitful nation because they broke their promise made to God, that they would serve him and keep his commandments. Exo. 19. v. 8.\f*
\v 7 But he shall not so think, and his heart shall not esteem it so: but his heart shall be set to destroy, and to the destruction of no few nations.
\v 8 For he shall say:
\v 9 Are not my princes with all kings? Is not as Charcamis, so Calano: and as Arphad, so Emath? Is not as Damascus, so Samaria?
\v 10 Even as my hand hath found the kingdoms of the idol, so also their idols of Jerusalem, & of Samaria.
\v 11 Shall I not as I have done to Samaria and her idols so do to Jerusalem and her idols?
\v 12 And it shall be: when the Lord shall have accomplished all his works in mount Sion, and in Jerusalem, I will visit over the fruit of the magnifical heart of the king of Assur, and over the glory of the haughtiness of his eyes. \x + \xo 10:12 \xt 4. Reg. 9.\x*
\v 13 For he hath said: In the strength of mine own hand have I done it, and in mine own wisdom have I understood: and I have taken away the borders of peoples, and have spoiled their princes, and have pulled down as a mighty man, them that sat on high.
\v 14 And my hand hath found the strength of peoples as a nest: and as eggs be gathered that are left, so have I gathered together all the earth: and there was none that moved wing, and opened mouth, and once muttered.
\v 15 Shall the axe glory against him, that cutteth with it? Or shall the saw exalt itself against him, by whom it is drawn? As if a rod should lift up itself against him, that lifteth it up, and a staff exalt itself, which is certes but wood. \f + \fr 10:15 \ft Sennacherib not by his own power, but as God's instrument & minister afflicted the Israelites. Nevertheless he persecuted them of his own free will, which God used for the punishment of his people. In general therefore evil men are like to instruments without sense, but differ in that men's actions are voluntary, & unreasonable, and senseless creatures have no will at all, but only natural aptness, and inclination.\f*
\v 16 For this cause the Dominatour the Lord of hosts shall send leanness in his fat ones: and under his glory shall burn as it were the burning of fire kindled.
\v 17 And the light of Israel shall be in fire, and the Holy one thereof in flame: and his thorn shall be kindled, and be devoured, and the briers in one day.
\v 18 And the glory of his forest, and of his carmelus shall be consumed, from the soul even to the flesh, and he shall be a fugitive for fear.
\v 19 And the remains of the wood of his forest, for the fewness shall be numbered, and a child shall write them.
\v 20 And it shall be in that day, the residue of Israel, and they that shall escape of the house of Jacob, shall not add to lean upon him, that striketh them: but they shall lean upon our Lord the holy one of Israel in truth.
\v 21 The remnant shall be converted, the remnant I say of Jacob, to the strong God.
\v 22 For if thy people o Israel shall be as the sand of the sea, the remnant thereof shall be converted, consummation abridged shall make justice overflow.
\v 23 For our Lord the God of hosts shall make consummation, and abridgment in the midst of all the earth.
\v 24 For this cause, thus saith our Lord the God of hosts: O my people inhabiter of Sion, be not afraid of Assur: he shall strike thee with his rod, and shall lift up his staff over thee in the way of Ægypt.
\v 25 For yet a little, and a very little, & mine indignation and fury upon their wickedness shall be consummate. \x + \xo 10:25 \xt Iudi. 7.\x*
\v 26 And the Lord of hosts shall raise up a scourge upon him, according to the plague of Madian in the Rock Oreb, and his rod upon the sea, and he shall lift it up in the way of Ægypt.
\v 27 And it shall be in that day: his burden shall be taken away from off thy shoulder, and his yoke from off thy neck, and the yoke shall putrefy at the face of oil.
\v 28 He shall come into Aiath, he shall pass into Magron: at Machmas he shall commend his vessels. \f + \fr 10:28 \ft By these places Sennacherib passed with his army from Ægypt to Jerusalem.\f*
\v 29 They have passed in haste, Gaba is our seat: Rama was astonished, Gabaath of Saul fled.
\v 30 Neigh with thy voice o daughter of Gallim, attend Laisa, seely poor Anathoth.
\v 31 Medemena is removed: Ye inhabitants of Gabin take courage.
\v 32 Yet there is day, to stand in Nobe: he shall shake his hand over the mountain of the daughter of Sion, the little hill of Jerusalem.
\v 33 Behold the dominatour the Lord of hosts shall break the little flagon in terror, and the high of stature shall be cut down, and the lofty shall be humbled.
\v 34 And the thick places of the forest shall be overthrown with iron, and Libanus with the high ones shall fall.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 And a rod shall come forth of the root of Jesse, and a flower shall rise up out of his root. \f + \fr 11:1 \ft The Blessed Virgin.\f* \f + \fr 11:1 \ft Christ our Saviour replenished with the seven gifts of the Holy Ghost, of whose infinite plenitude his servants participate as it pleaseth his divine spirit to impart.\f* \x + \xo 11:1 \xt Act. 13.\x*
\v 2 And the Spirit of our Lord shall rest upon him: the spirit of wisdom, and understanding, the spirit of counsel, and strength, the spirit of knowledge, and piety,
\v 3 and the spirit of the fear of our Lord shall replenish him. He shall not judge according to the sight of the eyes, nor rebuke according to the hearing of the ears.
\v 4 But he shall judge the poor in justice, & shall rebuke in equity for the mild of the earth: and he shall strike the earth with the rod of his mouth, and with the spirit of his lips he shall kill the impious. \x + \xo 11:4 \xt 2. Thes. 2.\x*
\v 5 And justice shall be the girdle of his loins: and faith the girdle of his reins.
\v 6 The wolf shall dwell with the lamb: and the leopard shall lie with the kid, the calf, and lion, and sheep shall abide together, a little child shall lead them.
\v 7 The calf, and the bear shall feed: their young ones shall rest together: and the lion shall eat straw as it were an oxe.
\v 8 And the infant from the breast shall be delighted upon the hole of the asp: and he that is weaned, shall thrust his hand into the hole of the cockatrice.
\v 9 They shall not hurt, and they shall not kill in all my holy mountain, because the earth is replenished with the knowledge of our Lord, as the covering waters of the sea.
\v 10 In that day the root of Jesse, that standeth for a sign of peoples, him the nations shall beseech, and his sepulchre shall be glorious. \f + \fr 11:10 \ft Christ after his death, which to the world was ignominious, would be gloriously buried, by very honourable persons, Ioseph and Nicodemus, with aboundance of most precious spices, wrapped in fine linen, and laid in a new monument: to shew that the glory of the just beginneth from their death: where the glory of the wicked endeth. Christ's sepulchre still also remaineth glorious, honoured even by the Turks: much more by Catholic Christians.\f* \x + \xo 11:10 \xt Rom. 15.\x*
\v 11 And it shall be in that day: our Lord shall put to his hand the second time to possess the remnant of his people, which shall be left of the Assyrians, and of Ægypt, and of Phethros, and of Æthiopia, and of Ælam, and of Sennaar, and of Emath, and of the islands of the sea.
\v 12 And he shall lift up a sign unto the nations, and shall assemble together the fugitives of Israel, and shall gather the dispersed of Juda from the four quarters of the earth.
\v 13 And the emulation of Ephraim shall be taken away, and the enemies of Juda shall perish: Ephraim shall not envy Juda, & Juda shall not fight against Ephraim.
\v 14 And they shall fly upon the shoulders of the Philisthims by the sea, they together shall spoil the children of the East: Idumea, and Moab the precept of their hand, and the children of Ammon shall be obedient.
\v 15 And our Lord shall make desolate the tongue of the sea of Ægypt, and shall lift up his hand over the river in the strength of his spirit: and he shall strike him in his seven streams, so that they may pass through it with shoes.
\v 16 And there shall be a way to the remnant of my people, which shall be left of the Assyrians: as there was to Israel in the day, that he came up out of the Land of Ægypt.
\c 12
\p
\v 1 And thou shalt say in that day: I will confess to thee o Lord, because thou wast angry with me: thy fury is turned away, and thou hast comforted me.
\v 2 Behold God is my saviour, I will do confidently, and will not fear: because our Lord is my strength, and my praise, & he is become my salvation. \f + \fr 12:2 \ft The Jews gave thanks for their delivery from captivity of Babylon; & much more the Church of Christ rendereth thanks for her delivery from all sins.\f* \x + \xo 12:2 \xt Exo. 15. Psal. 117.\x*
\v 3 You shall draw waters in joy out of the saviour's fountains.
\v 4 And you shall say in that day: Confess ye to our Lord, and invocate his name: make his inventions known among the peoples: remember that his name is high.
\v 5 Sing ye to our Lord, because he hath done magnifically: shew this forth in all the earth.
\v 6 Rejoice, and praise o habitation of Sion: because great in the midst of thee, is the holy one of Israel.
\c 13
\p
\v 1 The burden of Babylon, which Isaie the son of Amos saw. \f + \fr 13:1 \ft The 1. against Babylon. (a) Nemrod began the Kingdom of Babylon (Gen. 10.) his son Belus did much augment it: & his son Ninus brought it to be a very great Empire, & Monarchy. But at last, after 1240. years, it was overcome by Cyrus King of Persia.\f*
\v 2 Upon the dark mountain lift up a sign, exalt the voice, lift up the hand, & let the dukes enter the gates.
\v 3 I have commanded my sanctified, and have called my strong ones in my wrath, them that rejoice in my glory. \f + \fr 13:3 \ft Medes and Persians were called sanctified, in that they were the ministers of God's justice, in the ruin of Babylon: which the Prophet foretelling calleth it The burden of Babylon.\f*
\v 4 The voice of a multitude in the mountains, as it were of many peoples, a voice of the sound of kings, nations gathered together: The Lord of hosts hath commanded the host of battle.
\v 5 Coming from a country far off, from the end of heaven: our Lord, & the instruments of his fury, to destroy the whole land.
\v 6 Howl ye, because the day of our Lord is near: it shall come as destruction from our Lord.
\v 7 For this cause shall all hands be dissolved, and every heart of man shall melt;
\v 8 and be broken. Gripings and pains shall hold them, they shall be in pain as she that travaileth. Every one shall be astonied at his neighbour, their countenances as faces burnt.
\v 9 Behold the day of our Lord shall come, cruel, & full of indignation, & of wrath, & fury to bring the land to a wilderness, and to destroy the sinners thereof out of it.
\v 10 Because the stars of heaven, and their brightness shall not display their light: the sun is darkened in his rising, and the moon shall not shine in her light. \x + \xo 13:10 \xt Eze. 32. Ioel. 3. Mat. 24. Mar. 23. Luc. 21.\x*
\v 11 And I will visit over the evils of the world, and against the impious their iniquity, and I will make the pride of infidels to cease, & will humble the arrogancy of the strong.
\v 12 Aman shall be more precious than gold, & man than pure fine gold. \f + \fr 13:12 \ft After the slaughter there shall be so few Babylonians, or Chaldeans left alive, that one man shall be more rare and precious than much fine gold.\f*
\v 13 For this I shall trouble heaven: and the earth shall be moved out of her place, for the indignation of the Lord of hosts, & for the day of the wrath of his fury.
\v 14 And it shall be as a young doe flying, & as a sheep: & there shall be none to gather them together: every man shall turn to his own people, and every one shall fly to his own land.
\v 15 Every one that shall be found, shall be slain: and every one that shall come to aid, shall fall by the sword.
\v 16 Their infants shall be dashed in pieces before their eyes: their houses shall be spoiled, and their wives shall be ravished. \x + \xo 13:16 \xt Ps. 136.\x*
\v 17 Behold I will raise upon them the Medes, which shall not seek silver, nor desire gold.
\v 18 But with arrows they shall kill the little ones, and shall have no pity upon the sucklings of the womb, and upon the children their eye shall not spare.
\v 19 And that Babylon glorious in kingdoms, noble in the pride of the Chaldees, shall be even as our Lord subverted Sodom and Gomorrha. \x + \xo 13:19 \xt Gen. 19.\x*
\v 20 It shall not be inhabited for ever, & it shall not be founded unto generation & generation: neither shall the Arabian pitch his tents there, nor shepherds rest there. \f + \fr 13:20 \ft Another city was built by the same name, but much less, & in another place of Chaldea.\f*
\v 21 But beasts shall rest there, and their houses shall be filled with dragons, and ostriches shall dwell there, and Satyrs shall dance there:
\v 22 And the Syrach owls shall answer there in the houses thereof, and mermaids in the temples of pleasure.
\c 14
\p
\v 1 It is near that the time thereof shall come, and the days thereof shall not be prolonged. For our Lord will have mercy on Jacob, and will yet choose out of Israel, and will make them rest upon their own ground: the stranger shall be joined to them, & shall stick to the house of Jacob. \f + \fr 14:1 \ft Isaie prophesied the destruction of Babylon above 100. years before the Jews were carried thither captive, and their captivity endured 70. years. Which was released by Cyrus, after he had overcome the Babylonians. Yet this space of near 200. years, is counted a short time in respect of so great a Monarchy as this was, which had now continued above a thousand years, from the time of Ninus, yea was begun by Nemrod. Gen. 10.\f*
\v 2 And peoples shall hold them, and bring them into their place, and the house of Israel shall possess them upon the land of our Lord for servants and handmaids: and they shall lead captive those that had taken them, & shall subdue their exactors.
\v 3 And it shall be in that day, when God shall give thee rest from thy labour, and from thy vexation, and from the sore servitude, which thou didst serve before.
\v 4 Thou shalt take this parable against the king of Babylon, and shalt say: How hath the exactor ceased, the tribute rested:
\v 5 Our Lord hath broken the staff of the impious, the rod of the rulers,
\v 6 that did beat peoples in indignation with uncurable wound, subduing nations in fury, persecuting cruelly.
\v 7 All earth is quiet and still, is glad & hath rejoiced.
\v 8 The fir trees also have rejoiced over thee, and the cedars of Libanus: since thou hast slept, there hath none come up to hew us.
\v 9 Hell beneath is troubled to meet thy coming, it hath raised up the giants for thee. All the princes of the earth are risen up from their thrones, all the princes of nations.
\v 10 All shall answer, and say to thee: Thou also art wounded even as we, made like unto us.
\v 11 Thy pride is drawn down to hell, thy carcass is fallen: under thee shall the moth be strawed, and worms shall be thy covering.
\v 12 How art thou fallen from heaven Lucifer, which didst rise in the morning? Art thou fallen to the earth, that didst wound nations? \f + \fr 14:12 \ft As Lucifer the greatest devil, so Nabuchodonosor King of Babylon fell through pride into extreme misery.\f*
\v 13 Which didst say in thy heart: I will ascend into heaven, above the stars of God will I exalt my throne, I will sit in the mount of the testament, in the sides of the North.
\v 14 I will ascend above the height of the clouds, I will be like to the Highest.
\v 15 But yet thou shalt be drawn down to hell, into the depth of the lake.
\v 16 They that shall see thee, shall turn toward thee, & behold thee: Is this the man that troubled the earth, that shaked kingdoms,
\v 17 that made the world a desert, & destroyed the cities thereof, opened not the prison to his prisoners?
\v 18 All the kings of the nations every one have slept in glory, each man in his own house.
\v 19 But thou art cast forth out of thy sepulchre, as an unprofitable branch polluted, and wrapped up with them that were slain by the sword, and are gone down to the foundations of the lake, as a rotten carcass.
\v 20 Thou shalt not keep company with them, neither in burial, for thou hast destroyed thy land, thou hast slain thy people: the seed of the wicked shall not be named for ever.
\v 21 Prepare his children to slaughter in the iniquity of their fathers: they shall not rise up, nor inherit the land, nor fill the world with cities.
\v 22 And I will rise over them, saith the Lord of hosts: & I will destroy the name of Babylon, and the remains, and bud, and progeny: saith our Lord.
\v 23 And I will make it the possession of the hedgehog, & matrices of waters, & I will sweep it with besom wearing it, saith the Lord of hosts.
\v 24 The Lord of hosts hath sworn, saying: If it shall not be, as I have thought: and so fall out, as I have in mind consulted:
\v 25 That I destroy the Assyrian in my land, and in my mountains tread upon him: and his yoke shall be taken away from them, and his burden taken off from their shoulder. \f + \fr 14:25 \ft The miraculous destruction of the Assirians' army besieging Jerusalem is recorded 4. Reg. 19.\f*
\v 26 This is the counsel, that I have devised upon all the earth, and this is the hand stretched forth upon all nations.
\v 27 For the Lord of hosts hath decreed, and who can weaken it? And his hand is stretched out: and who shall turn it away?
\v 28 In the year, that king Achaz died, was this burden made. \f + \fr 14:28 \ft The second commination is against the Philistians.\f* \x + \xo 14:28 \xt 4. Reg. 16.\x*
\v 29 Rejoice not thou whole Philistæa, that the rod of thy striker is broken in pieces: for from the root of the serpent shall issue forth a cockatrice, and his seed swallowing the bird. \f + \fr 14:29 \ft Though Achaz was dead whom the Philistims feared, yet Ezechias a better King did afflict them more than the other had done. 4. Reg. 18. v. 8. Much more Ozias. 2. Par. 26.\f*
\v 30 And the first born of the poor shall be fed, & the poor shall rest confidently: and I will make thy root to perish in famine, & will kill thy remnant.
\v 31 Howl thou gate, cry out o city: all Philisthæa is thrown down: for a smoke shall come from the North, and there is none that shall escape his troop. \f + \fr 14:31 \ft From Jerusalem which is situated on the north of Philistæa.\f*
\v 32 And what shall be answered to the messengers of nations? That our Lord hath founded Sion, and the poor of his people shall hope in him.
\c 15
\p
\v 1 The burden of Moab. Because Ar-Moab was wasted in the night, he hath held his peace: because the wall of Moab is destroyed in the night, he hath held his peace. \f + \fr 15:1 \ft The third commination was against the Moabites.\f* \f + \fr 15:1 \ft Destruction made in the night, prevented that they feared not the imminent danger, but so much the more they were afflicted, being suddenly oppressed with extreme misery.\f*
\v 2 The house is gone up, & Dibon to the high places to mourn upon Nabo, and upon Medaba shall Moab howl: on all the heads thereof baldness, and every beard shall be shaven. \x + \xo 15:2 \xt Ier. 44. Ezech. 7.\x*
\v 3 In the high ways thereof they are girded with sackcloth: upon the roofs thereof, and in the streets thereof all howling, goeth down to weep.
\v 4 Hesebon shall cry, & Eleale, their voice is heard even to Jasa. For this shall the well appointed of Moab howl, his soul shall howl to himself.
\v 5 My heart shall cry to Moab, the bars thereof unto Segor an heifer astonishing: for by the ascent of Luith he shall go up weeping: & in the way of Oronaim they shall lift up a cry of contrition. \f + \fr 15:5 \ft Misery, even of enemies, moveth a charitable heart to compassion. So the Prophet lamenteth the Moabites' affliction.\f*
\v 6 For the waters of Nemrim shall be made desolate, because the grass is withered, the spring is faded, all greenness is perished.
\v 7 According to the greatness of the work, is also their visitation: they shall lead them to the torrent of willows.
\v 8 Because the cry shall go round about the border of Moab: unto Gallim the howling thereof, and unto the Pit-Elim the cry thereof.
\v 9 Because the waters of Dibon are replenished with blood: for I will put additions upon Dibon: the lion for them that shall fly of Moab, and for the remnant of the land.
\c 16
\p
\v 1 Send forth o Lord the lamb the dominatour of the earth, from the Rock of the desert, to the mount of the daughter of Sion. \f + \fr 16:1 \ft In the great misery of the Moabites, the Prophet saw one special cause of consolation, that Christ the lamb of God, which taketh away the sins of the world, should be born of their lineage, by one of their progeny:\f* \f + \fr 16:1 \ft Of Ruth a Moabites, who was married to Booz, and so was David's great grand mother. Ruth 4. See the argument of Ruth.\f*
\v 2 And he shall be as a bird flying, and the young flying out of the nest, so shall the daughters of Moab be in the passage of Arnon.
\v 3 Take counsel, gather a council: set thy shadow in the midday as it were night: hide them that fly, and them that wander bewray not.
\v 4 My fugitives shall dwell with thee: Moab be thou their covert from the face of the destroyer: for the dust is ended, the wretch is come to naught: he hath failed, that trod down the earth.
\v 5 And a throne shall be prepared in mercy, and there shall sit upon it, in truth in the tabernacle of David, he that judgeth & seeketh judgement, and quickly rendereth that which is just.
\v 6 We have heard the pride of Moab, he is proud exceedingly: his pride and his arrogancy, and his indignation is more than his strength.
\v 7 Therefore shall Moab howl: to Moab, all shall howl: to them that rejoice upon the walls of baked brick, tell ye their plagues.
\v 8 Because the suburbs of Hesebon are desolate, and the vineyard of Sabama the lords of the Nations have cut off: the branches thereof have reached to Jazer: they wandered in the desert, the branches thereof are left, they passed over the sea.
\v 9 For this I will lament in the weeping of Jazer the vineyard of Sabama: I will inebriate thee with my tear o Hesebon, and Eleale: because the voice of the treaders is rusht in upon thy vintage, and upon thy harvest.
\v 10 And gladness and joy shall be taken away from Carmelus, and it shall not rejoice nor make jubilation in vineyards. He shall not tread wine in the press that was wont to tread: the voice of the treaders I have taken away.
\v 11 For this my belly shall sound as an harp to Moab, & my bowels to the wall of baked brick.
\v 12 And it shall be: when it shall appear that Moab hath laboured for his excelses, he shall go into his sanctuaries to pray, & shall not prevail.
\v 13 This is the word, that our Lord spake to Moab from that time:
\v 14 and now our Lord hath spoken saying: In three years, as the years of an hired servant, the glory of Moab shall be taken away upon all the multitude of people, and it shall be left little & small, not much. \f + \fr 16:14 \ft The wars against Moab continued three years, In which it was brought into servitude.\f*
\c 17
\p
\v 1 The burden of Damascus. Behold Damascus shall cease to be a city, and shall be as an heap of stones in ruin.
\v 2 The forsaken cities of Aroer shall be for flocks, and they shall rest there, and there shall be none to terrify them.
\v 3 And aid shall cease from Ephraim, and the kingdom from Damascus: and the remnant of Syria shall be as the glory of the children of Israel: saith the Lord of hosts.
\v 4 And it shall be in that day: the glory of Jacob shall be diminished, and the fatness of his flesh shall become lean.
\v 5 And it shall be as one gathering in harvest that which remaineth, and his arm shall gather the ears of corn: and it shall be as he that seeketh ears in the vale of Raphaim.
\v 6 And the fruit thereof shall be left, as it were a cluster of grapes in it, and as the shaking of the olive tree, of two or three olives in the top of a bough, or four or five in the tops thereof, saith our Lord the God of Israel.
\v 7 In that day man shall incline himself to his maker, and his eyes shall look to the holy one of Israel.
\v 8 And he shall not incline to the altars, which his hands made: and the things that his fingers wrought he shall not regard, as groves and temples.
\v 9 In that day the cities of his strength shall be left, as the ploughs and the corn that were left before the face of the children of Israel, and thou shalt be desolate. \x + \xo 17:9 \xt Iosue 10. 11. &c.\x*
\v 10 Because thou hast forgotten God thy saviour, and hast not remembered thy strong helper: therefore shalt thou plant a faithful plant, & shalt sow a strange seed.
\v 11 In the day of thy planting shall be the wild grape, & in the morning thy seed shall flourish: the harvest is taken away in the day of inheritance, and he shall be vehemently sorry.
\v 12 Woe to the multitude of many peoples, being as the multitude of the sounding sea: & the tumult of multitudes, as the sound of many waters. \f + \fr 17:12 \ft After that the Assirians had afflicted the Israelites, and their confederates, themselves were also afflicted.\f*
\v 13 Peoples shall sound as the sound of waters overflowing, and he shall rebuke him, and shall fly far off: and he shall be violently taken away as the dust of the mountains at the face of the wind, and as a whirlwind before a tempest.
\v 14 In the eventide, and behold trouble: in the morning, and he shall not be. This is the portion of them, that have wasted us, & the lot of them that spoiled us.
\c 18
\p
\v 1 Woe to the land the cymbal of wings, which is beyond the rivers of Æthiopia, \f + \fr 18:1 \ft The fifth was against the Æthiopians and Ægyptians.\f*
\v 2 which sendeth legates into the sea, and in the vessels of bulrushes upon the waters. Go ye swift angels to a nation shaken a sunder, and torn in pieces: to a terrible people, after which there is none other: to a nation expecting and trodden under foot, whose land the floods have spoiled: \f + \fr 18:2 \ft The Ægyptians bid their messengers go swiftly, & tell the Jews that they shall have present help according as they require & expect.\f* \f + \fr 18:2 \ft Or paper boats.\f*
\v 3 All ye inhabitants of the world, which abide in the earth, where the sign shall be lifted up in the mountains, you shall see, and shall hear the sound of the trumpet: \f + \fr 18:3 \ft But the Prophet sheweth that the Ægyptians themselves shall be overthrown by the Assirians\f*
\v 4 because thus saith our Lord to me: I will rest, and consider in my place, as the noon light is clear, and as a cloud of dew in the day of harvest.
\v 5 For before harvest it hath wholly flourished, and unripe perfection shall spring forth, and the boughs thereof shall be cut off with hooks: and the things that are left, shall be cut off, and shaken out.
\v 6 And they shall be left together to the birds of the mountains, and beasts of the earth: and the fowls shall be upon it the whole summer, and all the beasts of the earth shall winter upon it.
\v 7 In that time shall a gift be brought to the Lord of hosts, of a people plucked asunder and rent in pieces: of a terrible people, after which there hath been none other, of a nation expecting and trodden under foot, whose land the floods have spoiled, to the place of the name of the Lord of hosts, mount Sion.
\c 19
\p
\v 1 The burden of Ægypt. Behold our Lord will ascend upon a swift cloud, and will enter into Ægypt, and the idols of Ægypt shall be moved at his presence, & the heart of Ægypt shall melt in the midst thereof. \f + \fr 19:1 \ft When our B. Saviour was carried in his infancy by his mother into Ægypt the idols of that country lost their power. And the inhabitants were specially blessed, & afterwards very many believed in Christ, and sincerely served him.\f*
\v 2 And I will make the Ægyptians to run together against the Ægyptians: and a man shall fight against his brother, & every man against his friend, city against city, kingdom against kingdom.
\v 3 And the spirit of Ægypt shall be broken in the bowels thereof, & I will overthrow their counsel headlong: and they shall ask their idols, & their diviners, and Pythons, and Soothsayers.
\v 4 And I will deliver Ægypt into the hand of cruel masters, and a strong king shall rule over them, saith our Lord the God of hosts.
\v 5 And the water of the sea shall be dried up, & the river shall be made desolate, and dry.
\v 6 And the rivers shall fail: the rivers of the rampiers shall be diminished, & dried up. The reed and bulrush shall wither:
\v 7 the channel of the river shall be spoiled of his fountain, & all sown corn field that is watered shall be dried up, it shall wither, and shall not be.
\v 8 And the fishers shall lament, & all that cast angle into the river shall mourn, and they that spread net upon the face of the water shall pine away.
\v 9 They shall be confounded that wrought twisting flax, combing and weaving fine things.
\v 10 And the watered places thereof shall be dry, all they that made pools to take fishes.
\v 11 The Princes of Tanis are fools, the wise counsellers of Pharao have given unwise counsel: how say ye unto Pharao: I am the son of the wise, the son of the ancient kings?
\v 12 Where are now thy wise men? Let them tell thee, & shew what the Lord of hosts hath thought concerning Ægypt.
\v 13 The Princes of Tanis are become fools, the Princes of Memphis are withered away, they have deceived Ægypt, the corner of the peoples thereof.
\v 14 Our Lord hath mingled in the midst thereof the spirit of gladness: and they have made Ægypt to err in every work thereof, as he erreth that is drunk and vomiteth.
\v 15 And Ægypt shall have no work, to make the head and the tail, the perverter and restrainer.
\v 16 In that day Ægypt shall be as women, & they shall be astonished, & shall be afraid at the face of the moving of the hand of the Lord of hosts, which he shall move over it.
\v 17 And the land of Juda shall be a fear to Ægypt: every one that shall remember it, shall quake at the face of the counsel of the Lord of hosts, which he hath thought concerning it.
\v 18 In that day there shall be five cities in the land of Ægypt, speaking the tongue of Chanaan, and swearing by the Lord of hosts: one shall be called the city of the sun.
\v 19 In that day there shall be an altar of our Lord in the midst of the land of Ægypt, and a title of our Lord by the border thereof: \f + \fr 19:19 \ft Both Jews and Christians understand this prophecy of the conversion of the Ægyptians to Christ. But the Jews expect it as yet to come, we know that it is already fulfilled, at least in part. For there were sometimes many Christians in that country, yea many most excellent Saints. S. Paul. S. Antony. S. Hilarion, and innumerable others.\f*
\v 20 it shall be for a sign, and for a testimony to the Lord of hosts in the land of Ægypt. For they shall cry to our Lord at the presence of the afflicter, and he shall send them a saviour and defender to deliver them.
\v 21 And our Lord shall be known of Ægypt, & the Ægyptians shall know our Lord in that day, and shall worship him in hosts and in gifts: and they shall vow vows to our Lord, and pay them.
\v 22 And our Lord shall smite Ægypt with a stroke, and heal it, and they shall return to our Lord, and he shall be pacified towards them, and heal them.
\v 23 In that day there shall be a way from Ægypt to the Assyrians, and the Assyrian shall enter into Ægypt, and the Ægyptians to the Assyrians, & the Ægyptians shall serve Assur.
\v 24 In that day shall Israel be a third to the Ægyptian and the Assyrian: a blessing in the midst of the earth,
\v 25 which the Lord of hosts hath blessed, saying: Blessed be my people of Ægypt, and the work of my hands to the Assyrian: but Israel is mine inheritance.
\c 20
\p
\v 1 In the year that Tharthan entered into Azotus, when Sargon the king of the Assyrians had sent him, and he had fought against Azotus, and had taken it:
\v 2 at that time our Lord spake in the hand of Isaie the son of Amos, saying: Go, and loose the sackcloth from off thy loins, and take off thy shoes from thy feet. And he did so going naked, and barefoot. \f + \fr 20:2 \ft The holy Prophet, of noble blood, was not disobedient, nor ashamed to go naked, because nothing is more honest than to obey God's commandment. S. Ierom in hunc locum.\f*
\v 3 And our Lord said: As my servant Isaie hath walked, naked and barefoot, it shall be a sign and a wonder of three years upon Ægypt, and upon Æthiopia,
\v 4 so shall the king of the Assyrians lead the captivity of Ægypt, and the transmigration of Æthiopia, young and old, naked and unshod, their buttocks uncovered to the ignominy of Ægypt.
\v 5 And they shall fear, & be ashamed of Æthiopia their hope, and of Ægypt their glory.
\v 6 And the inhabitant of this isle shall say in that day: Lo this was our hope, to whom we fled for help, that they should deliver us from the face of the king of the Assyrians: and how shall we be able to escape?
\c 21
\p
\v 1 The burden of the desert sea. As whirlwinds come from the South, it cometh from the desert, from an horrible land. \f + \fr 21:1 \ft The sixth commination was against the Assirians, and specially the Babylonians.\f*
\v 2 A sore vision was told me: he that is incredulous doth unfaithfully: & he that is a spoiler, wasteth. Come up Ælam, besiege o Mede: I have made all the mourning thereof to cease.
\v 3 Therefore are my loins filled with sorrow, anguish hath possessed me, as the anguish of a woman that travaileth: I fell down when I heard it, I was troubled when I saw it.
\v 4 Mine heart failed, darkness made me astonished: Babylon my beloved is made a miracle unto me.
\v 5 Lay the table, look about in the watch tower the eaters and drinkers: arise ye Princes, take shield.
\v 6 For thus hath our Lord said to me: Go, and set a watchman: and what soever he shall see, let him tell.
\v 7 And he saw a chariot of two horsemen, a rider upon an ass, and a rider upon a camel: and he beheld them diligently with much looking. \f + \fr 21:7 \ft Cyrus King of the Persians a people of small power, & of the Medes, of great strength.\f*
\v 8 And a lion cried: I am upon the watch tower of our Lord, standing continually by day: and I am upon my watch, standing whole nights.
\v 9 Behold this man cometh, the rider upon the chariot of two horsemen, and he answered and said: Fallen, fallen is Babylon, and all the sculptiles of the gods thereof are broken to the ground. \x + \xo 21:9 \xt Iere. 51. Apoc. 14.\x*
\v 10 O my threshing, and children of my floor, the things that I have heard of the Lord of hosts the God of Israel, I have shewed unto you.
\v 11 The burden of Duma cryeth to me out of Seir: Watchman what of the night? Watchman what of the night? \f + \fr 21:11 \ft The seventh prophetical commination was against the Idumeans.\f*
\v 12 The watchman said: morning is come and night: if you seek, seek: return, come.
\v 13 The burden in Arabia. In the forest at even you shall sleep, in the paths of Dedanim. \f + \fr 21:13 \ft The eighth against the Ismaelites.\f*
\v 14 Meeting the thirsty bring water, you that inhabit the land of the South, with bread meet him that flyeth.
\v 15 For they are fled from the face of the swords, from the face of the sword hanging over, from the face of the bow bent, from the face of a grievous battle.
\v 16 Because thus saith our Lord to me: Yet in one year, as in the year of an hired man, and all the glory of Cedar shall be taken away.
\v 17 And the remnant of the number of the strong archers of the children of Cedar shall be diminished: for our Lord the God of Israel hath spoken it.
\c 22
\p
\v 1 The burden of the vale of vision. What aileth thee, that thou art also wholly gone up into the house tops? \f + \fr 22:1 \ft The ninth against the chief rulers of Jerusalem.\f* \f + \fr 22:1 \ft Sion situated on a hill, and often called a mountain, is here called a vale, for the afflicted state wherein it was in the captivity.\f*
\v 2 full of clamour, a populous city, rejoicing: thy slain are not slain by the sword, nor dead in battle.
\v 3 All thy Princes are fled together, and are bound hard: all that were found, are bound together, they are fled far off.
\v 4 Therefore have I said: Depart from me, I will weep bitterly: labour not to comfort me, for the destruction of the daughter of my people.
\v 5 For it is a day of slaughter, and conculcation, and weepings to our Lord the God of hosts, in the vale of visitation, searching the wall, and magnifical upon the mountain.
\v 6 And Ælam took quiver, chariot of the horseman, and the shield hath made the wall naked.
\v 7 And thy principal valleys shall be full of chariots, and the horsemen shall place themselves in the gate.
\v 8 And the covering of Juda shall be discovered, and thou shalt see in that day the armoury of the house of the forest.
\v 9 And you shall see the breaches of the city of David, because they are multiplied: and you have gathered together the waters of the lower pool,
\v 10 and have numbered the houses of Jerusalem, and destroyed houses to fortify the wall.
\v 11 And you have made a lake between the two walls to the water of the old pool: & you looked not up to him that made it, and the worker thereof long before you saw not.
\v 12 And our Lord the God of hosts shall call in that day to weeping, and to mourning, to baldness, and to girdle of sackcloth:
\v 13 and behold joy and gladness, to kill calves, and to slay rams, to eat flesh, and to drink wine: Let us eat and drink: for tomorrow we shall die.
\v 14 And the voice of the Lord of hosts was revealed in mine ears: If this iniquity shall be forgiven you until you die, saith our Lord the God of hosts.
\v 15 Thus saith our Lord the God of hosts: Go, get thee in to him, that dwelleth in the tabernacle, to Sobna the provost of the temple, and thou shalt say to him: \f + \fr 22:15 \ft This Sobna had some office about the Temple, but by crafty intrusion and unjust usurpation, rather than by lawful induction, was very covetous & ambitious: & so by God's judgement fell into misery.\f*
\v 16 What doest thou here, or as if thou were somebody here? Because thou hast cut thee out a sepulchre here, thou hast cut out a memorial diligently in an high place, a tabernacle for thee in a rock.
\v 17 Behold our Lord will cause thee to be carried away, as a cock is carried, and he will lift thee up as a garment.
\v 18 Crowning he will crown thee with tribulation, he will cast thee as a ball into a broad and large country: there shalt thou die, and there shall the chariot of thy glory be, the ignominy of the house of thy Lord.
\v 19 And I will expel thee from thy standing, and depose thee from thy ministry.
\v 20 And it shall be in that day: I will call my servant Eliacim the son of Helcias,
\v 21 and will clothe him with thy coat, and will strengthen him with thy girdle, and will give thy power into his hand: and he shall be as a father to the inhabitants of Jerusalem, & to the house of Juda.
\v 22 And I will give the key of the house of David upon his shoulder: and he shall open, and there shall be none to shut: and he shall shut, and there shall be none to open.
\v 23 And I will fasten him as a pin in a sure place, and he shall be for a throne of glory to the house of his father.
\v 24 And they shall hang upon him all the glory of his father's house, diverse kinds of vessels, every little vessel, from vessels of cups even to every instrument of music.
\v 25 In that day saith the Lord of hosts, shall the pin be taken away, that was fastened in the sure place: and that which hung thereon, shall be broken, and fall, and perish, because our Lord hath spoken.
\c 23
\p
\v 1 The burden of Tyre. Howl ye ships of the sea, because the house is destroyed, from whence they were wont to come: from the land of Cethim it is revealed to them. \f + \fr 23:1 \ft The tenth commination was against the Tyrians.\f*
\v 2 Hold your peace ye that dwell in the isle: the traffickers of Sidon passing over the sea, have replenished thee. \f + \fr 23:2 \ft Tyrus was an island, as Ezechiel also describeth it (ch. 27.) in the entrance, yea situated in the heart of the sea: but not far distant, for king Alexander filled up that passage of water and made it continent.\f*
\v 3 The seed of Nilus in many waters, the harvest of the river was her fruits: & she was made the traffic of the nations.
\v 4 Be ashamed Sidon, for the sea saith, the strength of the sea, saying: I have not travailed, and I have not brought forth, and I have not nourished young men, nor brought virgins to their growth.
\v 5 When it shall be heard in Ægypt, they will be sorry when they shall hear of Tyre:
\v 6 Pass over the seas, howl ye that dwell in the isle.
\v 7 Is not this your city, which gloried from ancient days in her antiquity? Her feet shall lead her afar to sojourn.
\v 8 Who hath thought this against Tyre, that was some time crowned, whose merchants were princes, her chapmen the nobles of the earth?
\v 9 The Lord of hosts hath thought it, that he might pluck down the pride of all glory, and bring all the glorious of the earth to ignominy.
\v 10 Pass thy land as a river, o daughter of the sea, thou hast a girdle no more.
\v 11 He hath stretched forth his hand upon the sea, he hath troubled kingdoms: Our Lord hath given commandment against Chanaan, to destroy the strong thereof,
\v 12 and he said: Thou shalt add no more to glory, o Virgin daughter of Sidon sustaining calumny: rising up sail over to Cethim, there also thou shalt have no rest.
\v 13 Behold the land of the Chaldees was not such a people, Assur founded it: they led away the strong thereof into captivity, they undermined the houses thereof, they brought it to ruin.
\v 14 Howl ye ships of the sea, because your strength is destroyed.
\v 15 And it shall be in that day: thou shalt be in oblivion o Tyre, seventy years, as the days of one king: but after seventy years, there shall be to Tyre as it were the song of an harlot. \f + \fr 23:15 \ft The Tyrians rejoiced in the Jews' captivity, & therefore God punished them with like captivity of 70. years.\f*
\v 16 Take an harp, go about the city thou harlot forgotten: sing well, multiply song, that there may be remembrance of thee.
\v 17 And it shall be after seventy years: our Lord will visit Tyre, and will bring her back again to her merchandise: and she shall fornicate again with all the kingdoms of the earth, upon the face of the earth.
\v 18 And the marts, and rewards shall be sanctified to our Lord: they shall not be kept in store, nor laid up: because her merchandise shall be for them, that shall dwell before our Lord, that they may eat unto satiety, and be clothed unto continuance.
\c 24
\p
\v 1 Behold our Lord shall dissipate the earth, and make it naked, and afflict the face thereof, and disperse the inhabitants thereof. \f + \fr 24:1 \ft The third part. Prophecies pertaining to the whole world.\f* \x + \xo 24:1 \xt Osee. 4.\x*
\v 2 And as the people, so shall the priest be: & as the servant, so his master: as the handmaid, so her mistress: as the buyer, so he that selleth: as the lender, so he that borroweth: as he that asketh his due, so he that oweth. \f + \fr 24:2 \ft Diversity of states which is now in the world, shall cease at the general judgement, and all men shall receive according to their deserts.\f*
\v 3 With dissipation shall the earth be dissipated, & with spoil it shall be spoiled: for our Lord hath spoken this word.
\v 4 The earth hath mourned, & fallen away, and is weakened: the world is fallen away, the height of the people of the earth is weakened.
\v 5 And the earth is infected by the inhabitants thereof: because they have transgressed the laws, changed right, dissipated the everlasting covenant.
\v 6 For this cause shall malediction devour the earth, & the inhabitants thereof shall sin: and therefore the dwellers therein shall be mad, & few men shall be left. \f + \fr 24:6 \ft Near the end of the world, many forgetting the law of God, & nature, will rage in extreme fury against others, persecuting & murdering one another, especially the wicked afflicting the good: which our Saviour describeth (Mat. 24.) saying: Nation shall rise against nation. You shall be odious to all nations for my sake. Iniquity shall abound, &c.\f*
\v 7 The vintage hath mourned, the wine is weakened, all have sighed that rejoiced in heart.
\v 8 The joy of timbrels hath ceased, the sound of them that rejoice is left off, the sweetness of the harp is silent.
\v 9 They shall not drink wine with song: the drink shall be bitter to them that drink it.
\v 10 The city of vanity is broken down, every house is shut, no man goeth in.
\v 11 There shall be crying for the wine in the streets: all mirth is left: the joy of the earth is carried away.
\v 12 Desolation is left in the city, & calamity shall oppress the gates.
\v 13 Because these things shall be in the midst of the earth, in the midst of peoples, in like manner as if a few olives, which are remaining, should be shaken out of the olive tree; and grapes, when the vintage is ended.
\v 14 These shall lift up their voice, and praise: when our Lord shall be glorified, they shall make a joyful noise from the sea.
\v 15 For this cause in doctrines glorify our Lord: in the isles of the sea the name of our Lord the God of Israel. \f + \fr 24:15 \ft This joyful propagation of God's glory and name, is either understood to be prophesied of the Church in general, which is as an island of the whole world: or properly and particularly (amongst other gentiles) of islands converted to Christ: as great Brittany & others.\f*
\v 16 From the ends of the earth we have heard praises, the glory of the just one. And I said: My secret to me, my secret to me, woe is me: the prevaricators have prevaricated, and by the prevarication of transgressors they have prevaricated.
\v 17 Fear, and pit, and snare upon thee, that art inhabiter of the earth. \x + \xo 24:17 \xt Ier. 48.\x*
\v 18 And it shall be: He that shall fly from the voice of fear, shall fall into the pit: and he that shall rid himself out of the pit, shall be held in the snare: because the floodgates from on high are opened, and the foundations of the earth shall be shaken.
\v 19 With breaking shall the earth be broken, with bruising shall the earth be bruised, with moving shall the earth be moved,
\v 20 with shaking shall the earth be shaken as a drunken man, and shall be taken away as the tabernacle of one night: and the iniquity thereof shall be heavy upon it, and it shall fall, and not add to rise again.
\v 21 And it shall be: In that day our Lord will visit upon the host of heaven on high, and upon the kings of the earth, that are upon the earth.
\v 22 And they shall be gathered together as the gathering of a bundle into the lake, and shall be shut there in prison: and after many days they shall be visited.
\v 23 And the moon shall be confounded, when the Lord of hosts shall reign in mount Sion, and in Jerusalem, & shall be glorified in the sight of his ancients.
\c 25
\p
\v 1 O Lord thou art my God. I will exalt thee, and confess to thy name: because thou hast done marvelous things, the old cogitations faithful, Amen. \f + \fr 25:1 \ft The Prophet and faithful people confessing God's benefits, and perfect performance of whatsoever he promiseth, or determineth, conforming their desires to his pleasure, say Amen, as well in prosperity, when he delivereth and blesseth them, as in adversity, when he punisheth: by the destruction of Jerusalem, which is here prophesied, and the like.\f*
\v 2 Because thou hast brought the city into a heap, the strong city into ruin, the house of strangers: that it be no city, & that it be not built for ever.
\v 3 For this shall strong people praise thee, the city of strong nations shall fear thee.
\v 4 Because thou art become a strength to the poor, a strength to the needy in his tribulation: an hope against the whirlwind, a shadow against the heat. For the spirit of the strong is as a whirlwind beating against a wall.
\v 5 As heat in thirst, shalt thou humble the tumult of strangers: and as with heat under a burning cloud thou shalt make the branch of the strong to wither.
\v 6 And the Lord of hosts shall make to all peoples in this mount, a feast of fat things, a feast of vintage, of fat things full of marrow, of vintage purified from the dregs. \f + \fr 25:6 \ft After the rejection of the Jews all Gentiles shall be converted to Christ.\f*
\v 7 And he shall in this mount throw down headlong the face of the bond, tied together upon all peoples, and the web that he hath begun upon all nations.
\v 8 He shall cast death down headlong for ever: and our Lord God shall take away tear from all face, and the reproach of his people he shall take away out of the whole earth: because our Lord hath spoken it. \x + \xo 25:8 \xt Apo. 7. & 21.\x*
\v 9 And he shall say in that day: Lo this is our God, we have expected him, and he will save us: this is our Lord, we have patiently waited for him, we shall rejoice and be joyful in his salvation.
\v 10 Because the hand of our Lord shall rest in this mount: and Moab shall be threshed under him, as straw is broken with the wain.
\v 11 And he shall stretch forth his hands under him, as he that swimmeth stretcheth forth to swim: and he shall humble his glory with dashing of his hands.
\v 12 And the munitions of thy high walls shall fall, and be humbled, & shall be plucked down to the ground even to the dust.
\c 26
\p
\v 1 In that day shall this song be sung in the land of Juda. Sion the city of our strength, a Saviour therein shall be put a wall and bulwark. \f + \fr 26:1 \ft In the time of grace given by Christ his whole Church singeth this and other like canticles of praises.\f* \f + \fr 26:1 \ft Other peoples have their peculiar proper cities: Babylon, Damascus, Tyrus, Sidon, &c. but all Christians have one city, the Catholic Church, signified by Sion.\f* \f + \fr 26:1 \ft Fenced with wall and bulwark, or faith & good works. S. Jerom here noteth that the sense of this Canticle is hard, by reason of often and sudden interlocutions of diverse persons consisting in questions and answers. To whose learned commentaries we remit the studious readers.\f*
\v 2 Open ye the gates, and let the just nation enter in, that keepeth truth.
\v 3 The old error is gone: thou wilt keep peace: peace, because we have hoped in thee.
\v 4 You have hoped in our Lord in worlds everlasting, in our Lord God strong for ever.
\v 5 Because he will bow down them that dwell on high, the high city he will abase. He will abase it even to the ground, he will pluck it down even to the dust.
\v 6 The foot shall tread it down, the feet of the poor, the steps of the needy.
\v 7 The path of the just is right, the path of the just is right to walk in.
\v 8 And in the path of thy judgements, o Lord, we have patiently expected thee: thy name, and thy memorial are in the desire of the soul.
\v 9 My soul hath desired thee in the night: yea and with my spirit in my heart I will watch to thee in the morning. When thou shalt do thy judgements in the earth, the inhabitants of the world shall learn justice.
\v 10 Let us have mercy on the impious, and he will not learn justice: in the land of the holy he hath done wicked things, and he shall not see the glory of our Lord.
\v 11 Lord thy hand be exalted, and let them not see: let the envious people see, and be confounded: and let fire devour thine enemies.
\v 12 Lord thou wilt give peace to us: for all our works thou hast wrought to us.
\v 13 O Lord our God, there have lords besides thee possessed us, only in thee let us remember thy name.
\v 14 Let not the dead live, let not the giants rise again: therefore hast thou visited and destroyed them, & hast destroyed all their memory.
\v 15 Thou hast been favourable to the nation, o Lord, thou hast been favourable to the nation: wast thou glorified? Thou hast made all the ends of the earth far off.
\v 16 Lord in distress they have sought after thee, in tribulation of murmur thy doctrine was to them.
\v 17 As she that conceiveth, when she draweth near to be delivered, being sorrowful cryeth in her pains: so are we become at thy presence, o Lord.
\v 18 We have conceived, and as it were travailed, and brought forth the spirit: salvations we have not done in the earth, therefore the inhabitants of the earth have not fallen.
\v 19 Thy dead shall live, my slain shall rise again: awake, and praise ye that dwell in the dust: because the dew of the light is thy dew, & the land of the giants thou shalt pluck down into ruin. \f + \fr 26:19 \ft Aprophecy of the general resurrection of all men.\f* \f + \fr 26:19 \ft Some in glory\f* \f + \fr 26:19 \ft Some in misery.\f*
\v 20 Go my people, enter into thy chambers, shut thy doors upon thee, be hid a little for a moment, till the indignation pass.
\v 21 For behold our Lord will come out of his place, to visit the iniquity of the inhabitant of the earth against him: and the earth shall reveal her blood, and shall cover her slain no more. \x + \xo 26:21 \xt Mich. 1.\x*
\c 27
\p
\v 1 In that day our Lord will visit with his sore, and great, and strong sword upon Leviathan the serpent, the bar, & upon Leviathan the crooked serpent, and shall kill the whale that is in the sea. \f + \fr 27:1 \ft Tyrants are called serpents for their subtle poisonful malice, and bars, because they hold men fast inclosed in bondage. And for the same reasons the devil is called a serpent, and a bar.\f* \x + \xo 27:1 \xt Iob. 40.\x*
\v 2 In that day the vineyard of pure wine shall sing to it.
\v 3 I the Lord that keep it, I will suddenly drink to it: lest perhaps there be visitation against it, night and day I keep it.
\v 4 There is no indignation in me: who will give me to be thorn and brier in battle: to go upon it, to set it on fire together?
\v 5 Or rather shall he hold my strength, shall he make peace with me, shall he make peace with me?
\v 6 They that go in with violence to Jacob, Israel shall flourish and spring, and they shall fill the face of the world with seed.
\v 7 Hath he striken him according to his stroke that struck him? Or as he killed his slain, is he killed?
\v 8 In measure against measure, when it shall be cast off, thou shalt judge it. He hath meditated in his hard spirit during the day of heat.
\v 9 Therefore upon this shall the iniquity be forgiven to the house of Jacob: and this is all the fruit, that the sin thereof be taken away, when he shall have laid all the stones of the altar, as stones of ashes broken, the groves & temples shall not stand.
\v 10 For the defensed city shall be desolate, the beautiful city shall be forsaken, and shall be left as a desert, there shall the calf feed, and there he shall lie, and shall consume the tops thereof.
\v 11 The harvests thereof shall be destroyed in drought, women coming and teaching it: for it is not a wise people, therefore shall not he that made it, have mercy on it: and he that formed it, shall not spare it.
\v 12 And it shall be, in that day our Lord will strike from the channel of the river, even to the torrent of Ægypt, and you shall be gathered together one and one o children of Israel.
\v 13 And it shall be: In that day a sound shall be made with a great trumpet, and they that were lost, shall come from the land of the Assyrians, and that were cast out, from the land of Ægypt, and shall adore our Lord in the holy mount in Jerusalem.
\c 28
\p
\v 1 Woe to the crown of pride, to the drunkards of Ephraim, and to the flower falling down from the glory of his exultation, which were in the top of the most fat valley, erring by wine. \f + \fr 28:1 \ft By Ephraim is understood the Kingdom of Israel, whose first King Jeroboam was of that tribe.\f* \f + \fr 28:1 \ft The fourth part. Prophetical admonitions to both the Kingdoms of Israel & Juda.\f*
\v 2 Behold our Lord is valiant and strong, as the violence of hail: a whirlwind breaking, the violence of many waters overflowing, & sent forth upon a large ground.
\v 3 The crown of pride of the drunkards of Ephraim shall be trodden under feet.
\v 4 And the flower of the glory of his exultation, which is upon the top of the valley of fat ones, shall be falling as a timely fruit before the ripeness of autumn: which when he that seeth it shall behold, as soon as he taketh it in his hand, he will devour it.
\v 5 In that day the Lord of hosts shall be a crown of glory, and a garland of exultation to the residue of his people: \f + \fr 28:5 \ft After that the ten tribes were carried captives (4. Reg. 17.) God delivered the two tribes out of imminent danger. (4. Reg. 18. 19.)\f* \f + \fr 28:5 \ft giving peace to their people:\f*
\v 6 and a spirit of judgement to him that sitteth in judgement, and strength to them that return out of battle to the gate. \f + \fr 28:6 \ft spirit of judgement to King Ezechias:\f* \f + \fr 28:6 \ft and victory to the soldiers.\f*
\v 7 But these also have been ignorant, because of wine, and by drunkenness have erred: the priest and the prophet have been ignorant because of drunkenness, they are swallowed up with wine, they have erred in drunkenness, they have not known him that seeth, they have been ignorant of judgement.
\v 8 For all tables were filled with vomiting and filth, so that there was no more place.
\v 9 Whom shall he teach knowledge? And whom shall he make to understand the thing heard? Them that are weaned from the milk, that are plucked away from the breasts.
\v 10 For command recommand, command recommand; expect reexpect, expect reexpect; a little there, a little there.
\v 11 For in the speech of lip, & in another tongue he will speak to his people.
\v 12 To whom he said: This is my rest, refresh the weary, and this is my refreshing: & they would not hear.
\v 13 And the word of our Lord shall be to them, command recommand, command, recommand; expect reexpect, expect, reexpect, a little there, a little there: that they may go, and fall backward, and be destroyed, and snared, and taken. \f + \fr 28:13 \ft Because Isaias & other holy Prophets often & much urged, not only the people, but also priests (which had rule over the people) to keep God's commandments, and to\f*
\v 14 For this cause hear the word of our Lord ye scornful men, which rule over my people that is in Jerusalem.
\v 15 For you have said: We have strucken a league with death, & with hell we have made a covenant. The scourge overflowing when it shall pass, shall not come upon us: because we have made lying our hope, & with lying we are protected.
\v 16 Therefore thus saith our Lord God: Behold I will send in the foundations of Sion a stone, an approved stone, a corner stone, precious, founded in the foundation. He that believeth, let him not make haste. \x + \xo 28:16 \xt Mat. 21. v. 42. Act. 4. 1. Pet. 2. Rom. 9.\x*
\v 17 And I will put judgement in weight, and justice in measure: and hail shall overthrow the hope of lying: and waters shall overflow the protection.
\v 18 And your league with death shall be abolished, & your covenant with hell shall not stand: when the scourge overflowing shall pass, you shall be trodden down of it.
\v 19 Whensoever it shall pass through, it shall take you away: because in the morning early it shall pass through in the day and in the night, and vexation alone shall give understanding in the hearing.
\v 20 For the bed is straitened, so that one must fall out, & a short mantle cannot cover both.
\v 21 For our Lord shall stand as in the mount of divisions: as in the valley, which is in Gabaon, shall he be angry: that he may do his work, his strange work: that he may work, his work is strange from him. \x + \xo 28:21 \xt 2. Reg. 5. 1. Par. 14.\x*
\v 22 And now mock not, lest perhaps your bonds be tied strait. For I have heard of our Lord the God of hosts consummation and abridgment upon all the earth.
\v 23 Harken with your ears, and hear my voice, attend, & hear my speech.
\v 24 Will the ploughman plow all the day to sow, will he cut & harrow his ground? \f + \fr 28:24 \ft As husbandmen dispose their works in order: so God sometimes worketh miracles, sometimes giveth benefits, sometimes sendeth afflictions:\f*
\v 25 Will he not when he hath made even the face thereof, sprinkle cummin, and place the wheat by order, and the barley, and millet, and vetch, in their bonds?
\v 26 And his God will instruct him in judgement: he will teach him.
\v 27 For gith shall not be threshed with instruments that have teeth, neither shall the wain wheel turn about upon cummin: but gith shall be beaten out with a rod, and cummin with a staff. \f + \fr 28:27 \ft and greater to some than to others.\f*
\v 28 But bread corn shall be broken small: but the thresher shall not thresh it for ever, neither shall the wain wheel vex it, nor break it with the teeth thereof. \f + \fr 28:28 \ft But none are continually afflicted without intermission.\f*
\v 29 And this is come forth from our Lord the God of hosts, that he might make his counsel marvelous, and magnify justice.
\c 29
\p
\v 1 Woe to Ariel, Ariel the city, which David overcame: year is added to year: the solemnities are at an end. \f + \fr 29:1 \ft Ari signifieth a lion, El, God: So Jerusalem called the lion of God, to wit a strong city, is threatened with destruction, which happened first by the Babylonians, 4. Reg. 25. again more miserable by Titus & Vespasian, 40. years after Christ's death.\f* \x + \xo 29:1 \xt 2. Reg. 5. 1. Par. 11.\x*
\v 2 And I will make a trench about Ariel, and it shall be sorrowful and mourning, and it shall be to me as Ariel. \x + \xo 29:2 \xt Luc. 19.\x*
\v 3 And I will compass as a sphere round about thee, and will cast a rampier against thee, and place munitions to besiege thee.
\v 4 Thou shalt be humbled, thou shalt speak out of the earth, and out of the ground thy speech shall be heard: and thy voice shall be out of the earth as the Python's, and out of the ground thy speech shall mutter.
\v 5 And the multitude of them that fan thee shall be as small dust: and as isles passing away, the multitude of them, that have prevailed against thee.
\v 6 And it shall be suddenly forthwith. It shall be visited of the Lord of hosts in thunder, and earth quake, and with great voice of whirlwind and tempest, and with flame of devouring fire.
\v 7 And the multitude of all nations, that have fought against Ariel, shall be as the dream of a vision in the night, and all that have warred, and besieged, and prevailed against it.
\v 8 And as he that is hungry dreameth, and eateth, but when he is awake, his soul is empty: and as he that is thirsty dreameth, & drinketh, and after he is awake, faint as yet thirsteth, & his soul is empty: so shall the multitude be of all the Gentiles, that have fought against mount Sion.
\v 9 Be astonied, and marvel, waver, & stagger: be ye drunk, & not of wine: be moved, & not of drunkenness.
\v 10 Because our Lord hath mingled unto you the spirit of drowsiness, he will shut your eyes, he will cover your prophets & princes, that see visions.
\v 11 And the vision of all shall be unto you as the words of a book sealed: which when they shall give to him that knoweth letters, they shall say: Read this; and he shall answer: I cannot, for it is sealed. \f + \fr 29:11 \ft Scribes and Pharisees pretending knowledge of Scriptures, cannot read Christ in the Prophets, because these Books are sealed (or locked) & they have not the key. Apoc. 3.\f*
\v 12 And the book shall be given to one that knoweth not letters, and it shall be said to him: Read; and he shall answer: I know not letters. \f + \fr 29:12 \ft The Gentiles could not read Christ in these books, because they knew not letters of the holy Scriptures. S. Ierom Prooemio. in Isaiam.\f*
\v 13 And our Lord said: Because this people approacheth with their mouth, and with their lips glorifieth me, but their heart is far from me, and they have feared me by the commandment and doctrines of men: \x + \xo 29:13 \xt Mat. 15. Mar. 7.\x*
\v 14 therefore behold I will add to make admiration to this people, by a great and wonderful miracle: for wisdom shall perish from their wise men, and the understanding of their prudent shall be hid.
\v 15 Woe unto you that are deep of heart, to hide your counsel from our Lord: whose works are in darkness, and they say: Who seeth us, and who knoweth us? \x + \xo 29:15 \xt 1. Cor. 1.\x*
\v 16 This your cogitation is perverse: as if the clay should think against the potter, and the work should say to the maker thereof: Thou madest me not: or the thing formed should say to the fashioner thereof: Thou understandest not. \x + \xo 29:16 \xt Eccli. 29.\x*
\v 17 Shall not yet within a little while, and in a short time, Libanus be turned into Charmel: and Charmel reputed for a forest?
\v 18 And in that day the deaf shall hear the words of the book, and out of the darkness and mist the eyes of the blind shall see.
\v 19 And the meek shall add joyfulness in our Lord, and the poor men shall rejoice in the holy one of Israel.
\v 20 Because he hath failed that did prevail, the scorner is consumed, and they are all cut down that watched upon iniquity:
\v 21 that made men sin in word, and supplanted him that reproved them in the gate, and declined in vain from the just.
\v 22 For this cause, thus saith our Lord to the house of Jacob, he that redeemed Abraham: Jacob shall not now be confounded, neither shall now his countenance be ashamed:
\v 23 but when he shall see his children, the works of mine hands, in the midst of him sanctifying my name, and they shall sanctify the holy one of Jacob, and shall preach the God of Israel,
\v 24 and they that err in spirit, shall know understanding, and the mutterers shall learn the law.
\c 30
\p
\v 1 Woe unto renegade children, saith our Lord, that you would take counsel, and not of me: and would begin a web, and not by my spirit, that you might add sin upon sin: \f + \fr 30:1 \ft You that trust in your own counsels and forces, or in other men's, and not in God, shall find the miserable event of your folly, as is before noted. chap. 20.\f* \f + \fr 30:1 \ft Apostatæ. or, deniers.\f*
\v 2 which walk to go down into Ægypt, and have not asked my mouth, hoping for help in the strength of Pharao, and having confidence in the shadow of Ægypt.
\v 3 And the strength of Pharao shall be a confusion to you, and the confidence in the shadow of Ægypt an ignominy.
\v 4 For thy Princes were in Tanis, & thy messengers came even to Hanes.
\v 5 All were confounded upon the people, that could not profit them: they were no help, nor to any profit, but to confusion & to reproach.
\v 6 The burden of the beasts of the South. In a land of tribulation & distress, the lioness, & the lion of them, the viper & the flying basiliscus carrying their riches upon the shoulders of beasts, & their treasures upon the bunch of camels, to a people that cannot be able to profit them.
\v 7 For Ægypt shall help in vain, and to no purpose: therefore have I cried upon this: It is pride only, cease.
\v 8 Now therefore going in write to her upon box, and draw it diligently in a book, and it shall be in the latter day for a testimony for ever. \f + \fr 30:8 \ft Either Isaias was commanded to write this which should be fulfilled many years after; or else he speaketh prophetically to Jeremy, near 200. years before he prophesied; signifying that he should then write it, as indeed he did. Iere. 41. &c.\f*
\v 9 For it is a people provoking to wrath, & lying children, children that will not hear the law of God.
\v 10 Which say to the seers: See not: & to them that behold: Behold us not those things that are right: Speak unto us pleasant things, see errors unto us.
\v 11 Take from me the way, turn away the path from me, let the holy one of Israel cease from our face.
\v 12 Therefore thus saith the holy one of Israel: For that you have rejected this word, and have hoped in calumny and tumult, and have leaned thereupon:
\v 13 therefore shall this iniquity be unto you as a breach that falleth, and is found lacking in an high wall, because suddenly, whilst it is not hoped, shall come the destruction thereof.
\v 14 And it shall be broken small, as the potter's vessel is broken with mighty breaking: and there shall not a shred be found of the fragments thereof, wherein a little fire may be carried from the burning, or a little water be drawn out of the pit.
\v 15 Because thus saith our Lord the God of Israel: If you return and be quiet, you shall be saved: in silence and in hope shall your strength be. And you would not:
\v 16 and you have said: No, but we will fly to horses: therefore shall you fly. And we will mount upon swift ones: therefore shall they be swifter, that shall persecute you.
\v 17 Athousand men at the face of the terror of one, and at the face of the terror of five shall you fly, till you be left as the mast of a ship in the top of a mountain, and as a sign upon a little hill.
\v 18 Therefore our Lord expecteth that he may have mercy on you: and therefore shall he be exalted sparing you: because our Lord is the God of judgement: blessed are all they that expect him.
\v 19 For the people of Sion shall dwell in Jerusalem: weeping thou shalt not weep, pitying he will pity thee: at the voice of thy cry as soon as he shall hear, he will answer thee. \x + \xo 30:19 \xt Ps. 51.\x*
\v 20 And our Lord will give you strait bread, & short water: and will not make thy doctor to fly away from thee any more: and thine eyes shall see thy master.
\v 21 And thine ears shall hear the word of him, that behind thy back admonisheth thee: This is the way, walk in it: and decline ye not neither to the right hand, nor to the left.
\v 22 And thou shalt contaminate the plates of the sculptiles of thy silver, & the garment of the molten of thy gold, and shalt scatter them as the uncleanness of a menstruous woman. Thou shalt say to it: Get thee hence.
\v 23 And rain shall be given to thy seed, wheresoever thou shalt sow in the land: and the bread of the corn of the land shall be most plentiful, and fat. The lamb in that day shall feed at large in thy possession:
\v 24 and thine oxen, as the ass colts, that till the ground, shall eat mingled provender as it was fanned in the floor.
\v 25 And there shall be upon every high mountain, and upon every little hill elevated, rivers of running waters in the day of the killing of many when the towers shall fall.
\v 26 And the light of the moon shall be as the light of the sun, and the light of the sun shall be sevenfold, as the light of seven days, in the day when our Lord shall bind up the wound of his people, and shall heal the stroke of their wound. \f + \fr 30:26 \ft This clarity in sun and moon shall be after the general resurrection.\f*
\v 27 Behold the name of our Lord cometh from far, his burning fury, and heavy to bear: his lips are filled with indignation, and his tongue as a devouring fire. \f + \fr 30:27 \ft Christ will exercise his severe justice in the general judgement, when he shall bid the damned go into everlasting fire. Mat. 25.\f*
\v 28 His spirit as a torrent overflowing even to the midst of the neck, to destroy the nations to nothing, and the bridle of error, that was in the jaws of peoples.
\v 29 There shall be a song unto you as the night of a sanctified solemnity, and joy of heart as he that goeth with a shalm, to enter into the mount of our Lord to the strong one of Israel.
\v 30 And our Lord shall make the glory of his voice to be heard, and shall shew the terror of his arm, in threatening of fury, and flame of devouring fire: he shall dash to pieces in whirlwind, and in hail stone.
\v 31 For at the voice of our Lord shall Assur fear being strucken with the rod.
\v 32 And the passage of the rod shall never cease, which our Lord shall make to rest upon him in timbrels and harps, and in principal battles he shall overthrow them. \f + \fr 30:32 \ft It often appeareth that when evil men seem most secure, they fall into sudden calamities.\f*
\v 33 For Topheth is prepared since yesterday, prepared of the king, deep, and wide. The nourishments thereof, fire and much wood: the breath of our Lord as a torrent of brimstone kindling it. \f + \fr 30:33 \ft Hell.\f*
\c 31
\p
\v 1 Woe to them that go down into Ægypt for help, hoping in horses, and having confidence upon chariots, because they be many: and upon horsemen, because they be very strong: and have not trusted upon the holy one of Israel, & have not sought after our Lord. \f + \fr 31:1 \ft Both this Prophet, and afterwards Jeremy admonished the Jews not to trust in the Ægyptians, but they contemning this admonition shewed in their deeds that they distrusted God, not believing nor obeying his Prophets: and for the same were at last punished.\f* \x + \xo 31:1 \xt Iere. 42.\x*
\v 2 But he that is the wise one hath brought evil, and hath not taken away his words: & he will rise up against the house of the wicked, and against the aid of them that work iniquity.
\v 3 Ægypt, a man, and not God: and their horses, flesh, and not spirit: and our Lord shall bow down his hand, and the helper shall fall, and he that is holpen shall fall, and they shall all be confounded together.
\v 4 Because thus saith our Lord to me: As if a lion should roar, and the lion's whelp upon his prey, and when a multitude of shepherds shall come against him, he will not fear at their voice, and of their multitude he will not be afraid: so shall the Lord of hosts descend to fight upon mount Sion, and upon the little hill thereof. \f + \fr 31:4 \ft In the mean time God destroyed the army of Sennacherib besieging Jerusalem. 4. Reg. 19. But they forgot this and many other examples of God's power and love.\f*
\v 5 As birds that fly, so will the Lord of hosts protect Jerusalem, protecting and delivering, passing and saving.
\v 6 Return as you revolted deeply, o children of Israel.
\v 7 For in that day man shall cast away the idols of his silver, and the idols of his gold, which your hands have made you into sin. \x + \xo 31:7 \xt Isai. 2.\x*
\v 8 And Assur shall fall by the sword not of man, and the sword not of man shall devour him, and he shall fly not at the face of the sword: & his young men shall be tributaries:
\v 9 and his strength shall pass away at the terror, & his princes flying shall be afraid: our Lord hath said it: whose fire is in Sion, & his furnace in Jerusalem.
\c 32
\p
\v 1 Behold the king shall reign in justice, & the princes shall rule in judgement. \f + \fr 32:1 \ft The fifth part. Of the captivity, and relaxation of the Kingdom of Juda: with other afflictions and comforts; but especially of Christ and his Church.\f*
\v 2 And a man shall be as he that is hid from the wind, and hideth himself from a tempest, as rivers of waters in drought, and the shadow of a rock that standeth out in a desert ground.
\v 3 The eyes of them that see, shall not be dim, and the ears of them that hear, shall harken diligently.
\v 4 And the heart of fools shall understand knowledge, and the tongue of mafflers shall speak readily and plain. \f + \fr 32:4 \ft Albeit many things in this and other places pertain first and literally to the old testament: yet all are in figure, & some things have no other literal sense but of the new testament. As this Prophecy of maffling, or unperfect tongues, to speak readily, is fulfilled in the Church of Christ; plainly and distinctly confessing all Mysteries of Catholic faith & religion: and the like, which cannot be verified in the Jewish people.\f*
\v 5 He that is unwise shall no more be called prince: neither shall the deceitful be called the greater man:
\v 6 for the fool shall speak foolish things, & his heart shall do iniquity, that he may work simulation, and speak to our Lord deceitfully, & make empty the soul of the hungry, and take away drink from the thirsty.
\v 7 The vessels of the deceitful are most wicked: for he hath framed devices to undo the meek, with the word of lying, when the poor man spake judgement.
\v 8 But the prince will think these things, that are worthy of a prince, & he shall stand above the dukes.
\v 9 Ye rich women arise, and hear my voice: ye confident daughters give ear to my speech. \f + \fr 32:9 \ft * Noble cities of Juda.\f*
\v 10 For after days & a year you shall be troubled that have confidence: for the vintage is at the end, the gathering will no more come.
\v 11 Be astonied ye rich women, be troubled ye confident: strip you, and be confounded, gird your loins.
\v 12 Mourn upon your breasts, upon the country worthy to be destroyed, upon the fruitful vineyard.
\v 13 Upon the ground of my people shall thorns & briers come up: how much more upon all the houses of joy, of the city rejoicing?
\v 14 For the house is forsaken, the multitude of the city is left, darkness and palpableness are made upon the dens for ever.
\v 15 The joy of wild asses the pastures of flocks, until the spirit be poured out upon us from on high: and the desert shall be as charmel, and charmel shall be reputed for a forest.
\v 16 And judgement shall dwell in the wilderness, and justice shall sit in charmel.
\v 17 And the work of justice shall be peace, and the service of justice silence, and security for ever.
\v 18 And my people shall sit in the beauty of peace, & in the tabernacles of confidence, and in wealthy rest.
\v 19 But hail in falling upon the forest, and the city shall be humbled with lowness.
\v 20 Blessed are ye, that sow upon all waters, sending in the foot of the oxe and the ass.
\c 33
\p
\v 1 Woe to thee that spoilest, shalt not thyself also be spoiled? And that despisest shall not thyself also be despised? When thou shalt have ended spoiling, thou shalt be spoiled: when being wearied thou shalt cease to contemn, thou shalt be contemned. \f + \fr 33:1 \ft Sennacherib spoiled all the kingdom of Israel, and all Juda saving Jerusalem, which he also besieged, reproaching and despising God: but himself was therefore spoiled, and despised.\f*
\v 2 Lord have mercy upon us: for we have expected thee: be our arm in the morning, and our salvation in the time of our tribulation.
\v 3 At the voice of the Angel the peoples fled, and at thy exaltation the nations are dispersed.
\v 4 And your spoils shall be gathered together as the locust is gathered, as when the ditches shall be full thereof.
\v 5 Our Lord is magnified, because he hath dwelt on high: he hath filled Sion with judgement, & justice.
\v 6 And there shall be saith in thy times: riches of salvation, wisdom & knowledge: the fear of our Lord, that is his treasure. \f + \fr 33:6 \ft Fidelity in performing promises of good things temporal and spiritual.\f*
\v 7 Behold they that see shall cry without: the angels of peace shall weep bitterly. \f + \fr 33:7 \ft Messengers sent to procure peace shall mourn, because they cannot obtain it.\f*
\v 8 The ways are dissipated, the passenger by the path hath ceased, the covenant is made frustrate, he hath rejected the cities, he hath not esteemed the men.
\v 9 The land hath mourned, & languished: Libanus is confounded, & become foul, and Saron is made as a desert: and Basan is shaken, & Carmel.
\v 10 Now will I rise up, saith our Lord: now will I be exalted, now will I be lifted up.
\v 11 You shall conceive heat, you shall bring forth stubble: your spirit as fire shall devour you.
\v 12 And the peoples shall be as ashes of a great fire, thorns gathered together shall be burned with fire.
\v 13 Hear ye that are far off, what things I have done, and ye that are near, know my strength.
\v 14 The sinners are terrified in Sion, trembling hath possessed the hypocrites. Which of you can dwell with devouring fire? Which of you shall dwell with everlasting heats?
\v 15 He that walketh in justices, and speaketh truth, that casteth away avarice of oppression, and shaketh his hands from all gift, that stoppeth his ears lest he hear blood, and shutteth his eyes that he may see no evil. \x + \xo 33:15 \xt Psa. 15.\x*
\v 16 This man shall dwell on high, the munitions of rocks shall be his highness: bread is given to him, his waters are faithful.
\v 17 His eyes shall see the king in his beauty, they shall see the land far off.
\v 18 Thy heart shall meditate fear: where is the learned? Where is he that pondereth the words of the law? Where the teacher of little ones? \x + \xo 33:18 \xt 1. Cor. 1.\x*
\v 19 The unwise people thou shalt not see, the people of profound speech: so that thou canst not understand the eloquence of his tongue, in whom there is no wisdom.
\v 20 Look upon Sion the city of our solemnity: thine eyes shall see Jerusalem, a rich habitation, a tabernacle that cannot be transferred: neither shall the nails thereof be taken away for ever, and all the cords thereof shall not be broken: \f + \fr 33:20 \ft Both prophecies & histories testify that terrene Jerusalem was subject to destruction, and was destroyed, and therefore this is necessarily to be understood of the Church of Christ, against which hell gates shall never prevail.\f*
\v 21 because only there our Lord is magnifical: a place of floods, rivers most broad and wide: no ship of rowers shall pass by it, neither shall the great galley pass thereby.
\v 22 For the Lord is our judge, the Lord is our law maker, the Lord is our King: he will save us.
\v 23 Thy cords are loosed, and they shall not prevail: thy mast shall be so, that thou canst not spread the sign. Then shall the spoils of many preys be divided: the lame shall take the spoil.
\v 24 Neither shall the neighbour say: I am feeble. The people that dwelleth therein, iniquity shall be taken away from them.
\c 34
\p
\v 1 Come near ye Gentiles, and hear, and ye peoples attend: let the earth hear, & the fullness thereof, the round world, and every spring thereof. \f + \fr 34:1 \ft God willeth as well gentiles that were far off, to come near,\f* \f + \fr 34:1 \ft as also the Jews that were his peculiar people, all to attend, that he will destroy this whole world, before the general Judgement.\f*
\v 2 Because the indignation of our Lord is upon all Gentiles, and fury upon all their hosts: he hath killed them, & given them into slaughter.
\v 3 Their slain shall be cast forth, and out of their carcasses shall rise a stink: the mountains shall melt with their blood.
\v 4 And all the host of the heavens shall melt away, and the heavens shall be folded together as a book: and all their host shall fall away as the leaf falleth from the vine, & from the fig tree.
\v 5 Because my sword is inebriated in heaven: behold it shall descend upon Idumæa, and upon the peoples of my slaughter to judgement.
\v 6 The sword of our Lord is filled with blood, it is fatted of the blood of lambs and buckgoats, of the blood of rams full of marrow: for the victim of our Lord is in Bosra, & a great slaughter in the land of Edom. \f + \fr 34:6 \ft No defence of strong places (signified by Bosra) shall save any men from destruction in the day of Judgement.\f*
\v 7 And the unicorns shall come down with them, & the bulls with the mighty: their land shall be drunk with blood, & their ground with the fatness of fat ones.
\v 8 Because it is the day of the revenge of our Lord, the year of retributions of the judgement of Sion. \f + \fr 34:8 \ft In the mean time, as a figure thereof, Sion shall be destroyed: and therefore the metaphorical destruction following, rather pertaineth to the state of the damned in the next world than to the afflicted in this life.\f*
\v 9 And the torrents thereof shall be turned into pitch, and the ground thereof into brimstone: and the land thereof shall be into burning pitch.
\v 10 Night and day it shall not be quenched, the smoke thereof shall go up for ever: from generation unto generation it shall be desolate, there shall none pass by it world without end.
\v 11 The onocrotalus, and hedgehog shall possess it: & the ibis, and the raven shall dwell in it: & a measure shall be stretched out upon it, to bring it to nothing, and a plum line unto desolation.
\v 12 The nobles thereof shall not be there: they shall call rather upon the king, and all the princes thereof shall be as nothing.
\v 13 And thorns and nettles shall grow up in the houses thereof, & the thistles in the munitions thereof: and it shall be the couch of dragons, and the pasture of ostriches.
\v 14 And spirits shall meet the onocentaurus, and the satyr shall cry one to the other, there hath the lamia lien, and found herself rest.
\v 15 There hath the hedgehog had an hole, and brought up whelps, and digged round about, and cherished them in the shadow thereof: thither are the kites gathered together, one to another.
\v 16 Search ye diligently in the book of our Lord, and read: one of them hath not wanted, one hath not sought for the other, because that which proceedeth out of my mouth, he hath commanded, and his spirit the same hath gathered them.
\v 17 And he hath cast them a lot, and his hand hath divided it unto them by measure: they shall possess it for ever, in generation and generation they shall dwell therein.
\c 35
\p
\v 1 The desert and the land without passage shall be glad, and the wilderness shall rejoice, & shall flourish as the lily. \f + \fr 35:1 \ft An evident prophecy of the conversion of Gentiles. In whom the Church shall continually spring & flourish.\f*
\v 2 Springing it shall spring, & shall rejoice joyful and praising: the glory of Libanus is given to it, the beauty of Carmel, & Saron, they shall see the glory of our Lord, and the beauty of our God.
\v 3 Encourage ye the loose hands, and strengthen the weak knees.
\v 4 Say to the faint hearted: Take courage, and fear not: behold your God shall bring revenge of retribution: God himself will come and will save you.
\v 5 Then shall the eyes of the blind be opened, and the ears of the deaf shall be open. \f + \fr 35:5 \ft Christ leaving all logical arguments, proved himself to be Messias by his works: If ye believe not me (saith our B. Saviour) believe my works. Ioan. 10. v. 38.\f* \x + \xo 35:5 \xt Mat. 15. Mar. 7. Luc. 7.\x*
\v 6 Then shall the lame leap as an hart, and the tongue of the dumb shall be opened: because waters are cut out in the desert, and torrents in the wilderness.
\v 7 And that which was dry land, shall be as a pool, and the thirsty ground as fountains of waters. In the dens wherein dragons dwelt before, shall spring up the greenness of reed and bulrush.
\v 8 And a path and a way shall be there, and it shall be called the holy way: the polluted shall not pass by it, and this shall be unto you a direct way, so that fools cannot err by it.
\v 9 The lion shall not be there, and the naughty beast shall not go up by it, nor be found there: and they shall walk that shall be delivered.
\v 10 And the redeemed of our Lord shall be converted, and shall come into Sion with praise, and everlasting joy shall be upon their head: they shall obtain joy and gladness, and sorrow and mourning shall fly away.
\c 36
\p
\v 1 And it came to pass in the fourteenth year of king Ezechias, Sennacherib king of the Assyrians came up against all the fenced cities of Juda, and took them. \f + \fr 36:1 \ft That which the Prophet had foretold by way of prophecy, now he recordeth by way of history, & therefore these four next chapters are inserted in the fourth book of kings. ch. 18. 19. and 20. almost in the same words, & an abridgement thereof 2. Paral. 32.\f* \x + \xo 36:1 \xt 4. Reg. 18. 2. Par. 31.\x*
\v 2 And the king of the Assyrians sent Rabsaces from Lachis to Jerusalem, to king Ezechias with a great army, and he stood by the water conduit of the upper pool in the way of the fuller's field.
\v 3 And there came out to him Eliacim the son of Helcias, who was over the house, and Sobna the scribe, and Joahe the son of Asaph the commenter.
\v 4 And Rabsaces said to them: Tell Ezechias: Thus saith the great king, the king of the Assyrians: What is this confidence, whereupon thou dost trust?
\v 5 or by what counsel or force art thou disposed to rebel? Upon whom hast thou confidence, that thou art revolted from me?
\v 6 Lo thou dost trust upon this broken staff of reed, upon Ægypt: upon which if a man lean, it will enter into his hand, and pierce it: so is Pharao the king of Ægypt to all that trust in him.
\v 7 But if thou wilt answer me: We trust in our Lord God: is it not he whose excelses and altars Ezechias hath taken away, and he said to Juda and Jerusalem: Before this altar shall you adore? \f + \fr 36:7 \ft Such is the blindness, and malice of infidels, that they confound things done to destroy idolatry, as if the same were against God.\f*
\v 8 And now deliver thyself to my lord the king of the Assyrians, and I will give thee two thousand horses, neither shall thou be able of thyself to give riders for them.
\v 9 And how wilt thou abide the face of the judge of one place, of the lesser servants of my lord? But if thou trust in Ægypt, in chariots and in horsemen:
\v 10 and now am I come up without the Lord unto this land to destroy it? The Lord saith to me: Go up against this land, and destroy it.
\v 11 And Eliacim, and Sobna, and Joahe said to Rabsaces: Speak to thy servants in the Syrian tongue: for we understand it: speak not to us in the Jews' language in the ears of the people, that is upon the wall.
\v 12 And Rabsaces said to them: Why, did my lord send me to thy lord and to thee, to speak all these words; and not rather to the men, that sit on the wall; that they may eat their own dung, and drink the urine of their feet with you?
\v 13 And Rabsaces stood, and cried with a loud voice in the Jews' language, and said: Hear ye the words of the great king, the king of Assyrians.
\v 14 Thus saith the king: Let not Ezechias seduce you, for he shall not be able to deliver you.
\v 15 And let not Ezechias give you confidence upon the Lord, saying: Our Lord delivering will deliver us, this city shall not be given into the hand of the king of Assyrians.
\v 16 Hear not Ezechias: for thus saith the king of Assyrians, do a blessing with me, and come forth to me, and eat ye every man of his own vineyard, and every man of his own figtree, and drink ye every man the water of his own cistern, \f + \fr 36:16 \ft Do that is profitable for you. 4. Reg. 18. v. 31.\f*
\v 17 till I come and take you away to a land, that is as your own, a land of corn and of wine, a land of bread and vineyards.
\v 18 Neither let Ezechias trouble you, saying: Our Lord will deliver us. Why, have the gods of the nations delivered every one their land out of the hand of the king of Assyrians?
\v 19 Where is the god of Emath, and Arphad? Where is the god of Sepharvaim? Have they delivered Samaria out of my hand? \f + \fr 36:19 \ft Many in Samaria served false gods which could not defend them: others served God almighty who for their good suffered them to be afflicted.\f*
\v 20 Who is there of all the gods of these lands, which hath delivered their land out of my hand, that the Lord can deliver Jerusalem out of my hand?
\v 21 And they held their peace, and answered him not a word. For the king had commanded, saying: Answer him not.
\v 22 And Eliacim the son of Helcias, that was over the house, and Sobna the scribe, and Joahe the son of Asaph the commenter, went in to Ezechias their garments rent, and told him the words of Rabsaces.
\c 37
\p
\v 1 And it came to pass, when king Ezechias had heard it, he rent his garments, and was wrapped in sack cloth, and entered into the house of our Lord. \f + \fr 37:1 \ft Renting or cutting of garments was a ceremony, to shew internal sorrow.\f* \f + \fr 37:1 \ft And sackcloth was an habit of penitents for sins.\f* \x + \xo 37:1 \xt 4. Reg. 19. 2. Par. 32.\x*
\v 2 And he sent Eliacim which was over the house, and Sobna the scribe and the ancients of the priests covered with sackcloths to Isaie, the son of Amos the Prophet.
\v 3 and they said to him: Thus saith Ezechias: This day is a day of tribulation and of rebuke, and of blasphemy: because the children are come even to the birth, and there is not strength to bring forth.
\v 4 If by any means our Lord thy God will hear the words of Rabsaces, whom the king of Assyrians his lord hath sent to blaspheme the living God, and to upbraid with words which our Lord thy God hath heard: lift up prayer therefore for the remnant that are left.
\v 5 And the servants of Ezechias came to Isaie.
\v 6 And Isaie said to them: Thus shall you say to your master: Thus saith our Lord: Fear not at the face of the words, which thou hast heard, wherewith the servants of the king of the Assyrians have blasphemed me.
\v 7 Behold, I will give him a spirit, and he shall hear a message, and shall return to his country, and I will make him fall by the sword in his own country.
\v 8 And Rabsaces returned, and found the king of Assyrians fighting against Lobna. For he heard that he was departed from Lachis,
\v 9 and he heard of Tharaca the king of Æthiopia, them that said: He is come forth to fight against thee. Which when he had heard, he sent messengers to Ezechias, saying:
\v 10 Thus shall you say to Ezechias the king of Juda, speaking: Let not thy God deceive thee, in whom thou hast confidence, saying: Jerusalem shall not be given into the hand of the king of the Assyrians.
\v 11 Lo thou hast heard all things the kings of the Assyrians have done to all countries, which they have subverted, & canst thou be delivered?
\v 12 Why, have the gods of the nations delivered them, whom my fathers have subverted, Gozam, and Haram, and Reseph, and the children of Eden, that were in Thalassar?
\v 13 Where is the king of Emath, and the king of Arphad, and the king of the city of Sepharvaim, of Ana, & Ava? \f + \fr 37:13 \ft That which happened to all these infidel Kings, fell also upon Sennacherib King of Assyrians shortly after he had thus bragged, or rather greater ruin and misery. v. 36. & 38.\f*
\v 14 And Ezechias took the letters of the hand of the messengers, & read them, and went up into the house of our Lord, and Ezechias laid them open before our Lord.
\v 15 And Ezechias prayed to our Lord, saying:
\v 16 O Lord of hosts God of Israel, which sittest upon the Cherubs, thou art the only God of all the kingdoms of the earth, thou hast made heaven and earth.
\v 17 Incline o Lord thine ear, & hear: open o Lord thine eyes, and see, and hear all the words of Sennacherib, which he hath sent to blaspheme the living God.
\v 18 For in very deed, o Lord, the kings of the Assyrians have made lands desolate, and the countries of the same.
\v 19 And they have given their gods to fire: for they were not gods, but the works of men's hands, wood and stone: & they brake them in pieces.
\v 20 And now, o Lord our God, save us out of his hand: and let all the kingdoms of the earth know, that thou only art the Lord.
\v 21 And Isaie the son of Amos sent to Ezechias, saying: Thus saith our Lord the God of Israel: For the things that thou prayed me concerning Sennacherib the king of Assyrians:
\v 22 this is the word which our Lord hath spoken upon him: The virgin daughter of Sion hath despised thee, and scorned thee: the daughter of Jerusalem hath wagged the head after thee.
\v 23 Whom hast thou upbraided, and whom hast thou blasphemed, and upon whom hast thou exalted voice, and lifted up the height of thine eyes? To the holy one of Israel.
\v 24 By the hand of thy servants thou hast upbraided our Lord, & hast said: In the multitude of my chariots have I climbed the height of mountains, the tops of Libanus: & I will cut down the high cedars thereof, & the chosen fir trees thereof, and will enter to the top of the height thereof, to the forest of his Carmel.
\v 25 I have digged, and drunken the water, and have dried up with the step of my foot all the rivers of the rampiers.
\v 26 Why, hast thou not heard, what I have done to him of old? From ancient days have I formed it: and now I have brought it to effect: and it is made to the rooting out of little hills bickering together, and of fenced cities.
\v 27 The inhabitants of them with shortened hand have trembled, and are confounded: they are become as hay of the field, and grass of the pasture ground, and herb of the housetops which hath withered before it was ripe.
\v 28 I have known thy habitation, and thy going out, and thy coming in, and thy madness against me.
\v 29 When thou didst rage against me, thy pride ascended into mine ears: therefore I will put a ring in thy nostrils, and a bit in thy lips, and will bring thee back into the way, by which thou camest.
\v 30 But to thee this shall be a sign: eat this year the things that grow to themselves, and in the second year eat fruits: but in the third year sow & reap, & plant vineyards, and eat the fruit of them. \f + \fr 37:30 \ft He turneth his speech to Ezechias.\f*
\v 31 And that which shall be saved of the house of Juda, and which is left, shall take root downward, and shall bear fruit upward:
\v 32 because out of Jerusalem there shall a remnant go forth, and salvation from mount Sion: the zeal of the Lord of hosts shall do this.
\v 33 Therefore thus saith our Lord concerning the king of the Assyrians: He shall not enter this city, and he shall not shoot arrow there, and shield shall not occupy it, and he shall not cast rampier about it:
\v 34 In the way that he came, by the same he shall return, and into this city he shall not enter, saith our Lord.
\v 35 And I will protect this city, that I may save it for mine own sake, and for David's sake my servant.
\v 36 And the Angel of our Lord came forth, and struck in the camp of the Assyrians an hundred eighty five thousand. And they arose in the morning, and behold, all were carcasses of dead men. \x + \xo 37:36 \xt Tob. 1. Eccl. 48. 1. Mac. 7. 2. Mac. 8.\x*
\v 37 And he went out, and departed, and Sennacherib the king of the Assyrians returned, and dwelt in Ninive.
\v 38 And it came to pass, when he adored in the temple of Nesroch his god, Adramelech & Sarasar his sons struck him with the sword: and they fled into the land of Ararat, & Asarhaddon his son reigned for him.
\c 38
\p
\v 1 In those days Ezechias was sick even to death: and Isaie the son of Amos the Prophet, went in unto him, and said to him: Thus saith our Lord: Take order with thy house, for thou shalt die, and shalt not live. \f + \fr 38:1 \ft After the Assyrians were slain, King Ezechias was visited with a dangerous sickness, to keep him in the fear of God, lest much joy should bring him into oblivion of his duty.\f* \f + \fr 38:1 \ft It was first revealed to the Prophet that the King's sickness was deadly.\f* \x + \xo 38:1 \xt 4. Reg. 20. 2. Par. 32.\x*
\v 2 And Ezechias turned his face to the wall, & prayed to our Lord,
\v 3 and said: I beseech thee Lord, remember I pray thee how I have walked before thee in truth, and in a perfect heart, and have done that which is good in thine eyes. And Ezechias wept with great weeping.
\v 4 And the word of our Lord was made to Isaie, saying:
\v 5 Go, & tell Ezechias: Thus saith our Lord the God of David thy father: I have heard thy prayer, and seen thy tears: Lo I will add upon thy days fifteen years: \f + \fr 38:5 \ft Secondly that God would add 15. years to his life: which could not be said, to be added, except his life according to natural causes had been at an end. S. Aug. li. 6. c. 17. de Gen. ad lit.\f*
\v 6 and out of the hand of the king of the Assyrians will I deliver thee, and this city, & will protect it.
\v 7 And this shall be a sign to thee from our Lord that our Lord will do this word, which he hath spoken:
\v 8 Behold I will make the shadow of the lines return, by the which it is now gone down in the dial of Achaz in the sun, back-ward ten lines. And the sun returned ten lines by the degrees whereby it was gone down.
\v 9 The scripture of Ezechias the king of Juda, when he had been sick, & was recovered of his infirmity.
\v 10 I have said: In the midst of my days shall I go to the gates of hell. I have sought the residue of my years. \f + \fr 38:10 \ft In this Canticle the King reciteth his afflictions of mind, for that he should part out of this world, in the flower of his age.\f*
\v 11 I have said: I shall not see our Lord God in the land of the living. I shall behold man no more, and the inhabiter of rest.
\v 12 My generation is taken away; and is wrapped together from me, as the tent of shepherds: My life is cut off, as by a weaver; whilst I yet began he cut me off: from morning until night thou wilt make an end of me. \f + \fr 38:12 \ft And without children for Manasses was born three years after being 12. years old when he began to reign. 4. Reg. 21.\f*
\v 13 I hoped until morning, as a lion so hath he broken all my bones: From morning until evening thou wilt make an end of me.
\v 14 As a young swallow so will I cry. I will meditate as a dove: Mine eyes are weakened, looking on high: Lord I suffer violence, answer for me.
\v 15 What shall I say, or what shall he answer me, whereas himself hath done it?
\v 16 I will recount to thee all my years in the bitterness of my soul. Lord if man's life be such, and the life of my spirit in such things, thou shalt chasten me, and shalt quicken me.
\v 17 Behold in peace is my bitterness most bitter: But thou hast delivered my soul that it should not perish, thou hast cast all my sins behind thy back.
\v 18 Because hell shall not confess to thee, neither shall death praise thee: they that go down into the lake, shall not expect thy truth.
\v 19 The living the living he shall confess to thee, as I also this day: the father shall make thy truth known to the children.
\v 20 O Lord save me, and we shall sing our Psalms, all the days of our life in the house of our Lord.
\v 21 And Isaie commanded that they should take a lump of figs, & plaster it upon the wound, and he should be healed. \f + \fr 38:21 \ft The Prophet ordained this medicine:\f*
\v 22 And Ezechias said: What shall be the sign that I shall go up into the house of our Lord? \f + \fr 38:22 \ft and the King also demanded a sign before he sang the Canticle.\f*
\c 39
\p
\v 1 At that time Merodach Baladan the son of Baladan, king of Babylon, sent letters & gifts to Ezechias: for he had heard that he had been sick, and was recovered, \x + \xo 39:1 \xt 4. Reg. 20.\x*
\v 2 And Ezechias rejoiced upon them, and he shewed them the storehouse of aromatical spices, & of silver, and of gold, and of sweet-odours and of the best ointment, and all the store houses of his furniture, and all things that were found in his treasures. There was not any thing, which Ezechias shewed them not in his house, and in all his dominion. \f + \fr 39:2 \ft In this honorable embassage Ezechias rejoiced immoderately and unwisely shewed his treasures, which therefore the Prophet reprehended. And upon this occasion prophesied that the Babylonians should carry away all that treasure, and his children into captivity.\f*
\v 3 But Isaie the Prophet went in to Ezechias the king, and said to him: What said these men, and from whence came they to thee? And Ezechias said: from a far country they came to me, from Babylon.
\v 4 And he said: What saw they in thy house? And Ezechias said: All things that are in my house have they seen, there was not any thing, which I have not shewed them in my treasures.
\v 5 And Isaie said to Ezechias: Hear the word of the Lord of hosts.
\v 6 Behold the days shall come: and all things that are in thy house, and that thy fathers have laid up for treasure until this day, shall be taken away into Babylon: there shall not any thing be left, saith our Lord.
\v 7 And of thy children, which shall come forth of thee, whom thou shalt beget, they shall take away, and they shall be eunuchs in the palace of the king of Babylon.
\v 8 And Ezechias said to Isaie: The word of our Lord which he hath spoken is good. And he said: Only be there peace and truth in my days. \f + \fr 39:8 \ft Not for want of affection towards his posterity, but seeing he durst not request more, he prayed for peace in his own days.\f*
\c 40
\p
\v 1 Be comforted, be comforted my people, saith your God. \f + \fr 40:1 \ft The Prophet alludeth to the comfort of the Jews, when they should be delivered from captivity of Babylon: but principally prophesieth of man's delivery from sin by Christ.\f* \f + \fr 40:1 \ft The sixth part. Of the delivery from sin by Christ.\f*
\v 2 Speak to the heart of Jerusalem, and call to her: because her malice is accomplished, her iniquity is forgiven: she hath received of the hand of our Lord double for all her sins. \x + \xo 40:2 \xt Mat. 3. Mar. 1. Luc. 3. Ioan. 1.\x*
\v 3 The voice of one crying in the desert: Prepare the way of our Lord, make straight the paths of our God in the wilderness. \f + \fr 40:3 \ft An evident prophecy of S. John Baptist.\f*
\v 4 Every valley shall be exalted, and every mountain and little hill shall be humbled, and crooked things shall become straight, and rough ways, plain.
\v 5 And the glory of our Lord shall be revealed, and all flesh together shall see, the mouth of our Lord hath spoken.
\v 6 The voice of one saying: Cry. And I said: What shall I cry? All flesh is grass, and all the glory thereof as the flower of the field. \x + \xo 40:6 \xt Iac. 1. 1. Pet. 1\x*
\v 7 The grass is withered, and the flower is fallen, because the spirit of our Lord hath blown on it. Indeed the people is grass:
\v 8 the grass is withered, and the flower is fallen: but the word of our Lord abideth for ever.
\v 9 Upon an high mountain get thee up, thou that evangelizest to Sion: exalt the voice in strength, which evangelizest to Jerusalem: exalt it, fear not. Say to the cities of Juda: Behold your God: \f + \fr 40:9 \ft This is also manifest of Christ's preaching in the mountain: & of his Apostles, and Apostolical preachers.\f* \x + \xo 40:9 \xt Mat. 5.\x*
\v 10 behold our Lord God shall come in strength, & his arm shall have dominion: behold his reward is with him, and his work before him.
\v 11 As a shepherd shall he feed his flock: in his arm shall he gather together the lambs, and in his bosom shall he lift them up, and them with young himself shall carry. \x + \xo 40:11 \xt Ioan. 10.\x*
\v 12 Who hath measured the waters with his fist, and pondered the heavens with a span? Who hath poised with three fingers the huge greatness of the earth, & weighed the mountains in weight, and the little hills in balance? \f + \fr 40:12 \ft God's power and benevolence in creating & governing all this world, is a sign that he both can and will bestow these great benefits of grace upon all nations.\f*
\v 13 Who hath holpen the spirit of our Lord? Or who hath been his counseller, & shewed to him? \x + \xo 40:13 \xt Rom. 11. 1. Cor. 2.\x*
\v 14 With whom hath he taken counsel, and who hath instructed him, and taught him the path of justice, and taught him knowledge, and shewed him the way of prudence?
\v 15 Behold the Gentiles are as a drop of a bucket, and are reputed as the moment of a balance: behold the islands are as a little dust. \f + \fr 40:15 \ft * least dust, or atomus.\f*
\v 16 And Libanus shall not suffice to kindle the fire, and the beasts thereof shall not be sufficient for holocaust.
\v 17 All nations as if they were not, so are they before him, and they are reputed of him as nothing, and a vain thing.
\v 18 To whom then have you made God like? Or what image will you set to him? \x + \xo 40:18 \xt Act. 17.\x*
\v 19 Hath the artificer cast a sculptile? or hath the goldsmith figured it with gold, or the silversmith with plates of silver?
\v 20 Strong wood, and that which will not putrefy hath he chosen: the wise artificer seeketh how he may set up a sculptile which may not be moved.
\v 21 Why, do you not know: why, have you not heard? Why, hath it not been told you from the beginning? Have you not understood the foundations of the earth? \f + \fr 40:21 \ft From the beginning the law of nature, afterwards the law of Moyses taught that he which made the world is God.\f*
\v 22 He that sitteth upon the compass of the earth, and the inhabitants thereof are as locusts: he that stretcheth out the heavens as nothing, and spreadeth them as a tent to dwell in.
\v 23 He that maketh the searchers of secrets as if they were not, that hath made the judges of the earth as a vain thing: \f + \fr 40:23 \ft Wisest Philosophers know nothing, neither can consist but by him.\f*
\v 24 and indeed their stock was neither planted, nor sown, nor rooted in the earth: suddenly he hath blown upon them, and they have withered, and a whirlwind shall take them away as stubble.
\v 25 And to whom have ye likened me, and made me equal? Saith the holy one.
\v 26 Lift up your eyes on high, and see who hath created these things: he that bringeth out the host of them in number, and calleth them all by name: by the multitude of his force and strength, & power, not one of them was missing. \x + \xo 40:26 \xt Psa. 146.\x*
\v 27 Why sayest thou Jacob, and speakest thou Israel: My way is hid from our Lord, and my judgement is passed over of my God?
\v 28 Why knowest thou not, or hast thou not heard? Our Lord is God everlasting, which hath created the ends of the earth: he shall not fail, nor labour, neither is there searching out of his wisdom.
\v 29 Which giveth strength to the weary: and to them that are not, multiplieth force and strength.
\v 30 Children shall faint, and labour, and youngmen shall fall by infirmity.
\v 31 But they that hope in our Lord shall change their strength, they shall take wings as eagles, they shall run and not labour, they shall walk and not faint.
\c 41
\p
\v 1 Let the islands hold their peace before me, and the Gentiles change their strength: let them come near, & then speak, let us approach to judgement together. \f + \fr 41:1 \ft God's expostulation with Islands, & other Gentiles living in idolatry, which implieth a prophecy of their conversion to Christ, pertaineth amongst others very particularly to our great Britainy, the greatest & most renowned Island of Europe. See D. Bristow. Mot. 11.\f*
\v 2 Who hath raised the just from the East, hath called him that he should follow him? He shall give the Gentiles in his sight, & he shall obtain kings: he shall give them as it were dust to his sword, as stubble taken violently with the wind, to his bow.
\v 3 He shall pursue them, he shall pass in peace, there shall no path appear after his feet.
\v 4 Who hath wrought and done these things, calling the generations from the beginning? I the Lord, the first and the last I am. \x + \xo 41:4 \xt Apo. 1. & 22.\x*
\v 5 The islands have seen, and have been afraid, the ends of the earth have been astonied, they have approached, and come near.
\v 6 Every one shall help his neighbour, and shall say to his brother: Be strong.
\v 7 The coppersmith striking with the hammer encouraged him that forged at that time, saying: It is good for soldering: and he strengthened it with nails, that it should not be moved.
\v 8 And thou Israel my servant, Jacob whom I have chosen, the seed of Abraham my friend:
\v 9 in whom I have taken thee from the ends of the earth, and from the far parts thereof have called thee, and said to thee: Thou art my servant, I have chosen thee, & have not cast thee away.
\v 10 Fear not, because I am with thee: decline not, because I am thy God: I have strengthened thee, and have holpen thee, and the right hand of my just one hath sustained thee.
\v 11 Behold all that fight against thee shall be confounded and ashamed, they shall be as if they were not, and the men shall perish that gainsay thee.
\v 12 Thou shalt seek them, and shalt not find, the men thy rebels: they shall be as if they were not: and as consumption the men that war against thee.
\v 13 Because I am the Lord thy God, taking thy hand, and saying to thee: Fear not, I have holpen thee.
\v 14 Fear not thou worm of Jacob, ye that are dead of Israel: I have holpen thee, saith our Lord: and thy redeemer the holy one of Israel. \f + \fr 41:14 \ft You that are as abjects contemned, & as dead men in the world, fear not, because Christ hath care to protect, & to reward you.\f*
\v 15 I have made thee as a new threshing wain, having teeth like a saw: thou shalt thresh the mountains, and break them in pieces: and shalt make the little hills as dust.
\v 16 Thou shalt fan them, and the wind shall take them away, & the whirlwind shall disperse them: and thou shalt rejoice in the Lord, in the holy one of Israel thou shalt be joyful.
\v 17 The needy and the poor seek for waters, and there are none: their tongue hath been dry with thirst. I the Lord will hear them, I the God of Israel will not forsake them.
\v 18 I will open rivers in the high hills, and fountains in the midst of plain fields: I will make the desert into pools of waters, and the land not passable into rivers of waters.
\v 19 I will give into the wilderness the cedar, and the thorn, and the myrtle and the olive tree: I will set in the desert the fir tree, the elm, and the box tree together.
\v 20 That they may see, and know, and recount, and understand together, that the hand of the Lord hath done this, and the holy one of Israel hath created it.
\v 21 Make your judgement approach, saith the Lord: bring hither, if perhaps you have any thing, said the King of Jacob.
\v 22 Let them come, and tell us what things soever are to come: tell the former things what they have been: and we will set our heart, and shall know the later ends of them, and tell us the things that are to come. \f + \fr 41:22 \ft Only God, and those to whom he revealeth, can tell things to come, and therefore idols cannot foreshew what shall be, neither could tell beforehand things that are already come to pass.\f*
\v 23 Shew what things are to come hereafter, and we shall know that ye are gods. Do ye also good or evil, if you can: & let us speak & see together.
\v 24 Behold, you are of nothing, and your work of that which is not: he is abomination that hath chosen you.
\v 25 I have raised up from the North, and he shall come from the rising of the sun: he shall call upon my name, and shall bring the magistrates as mire, and as the plasterer treading clay.
\v 26 Who hath shewed from the beginning, that we may know: and from the beginning that we may say: Art thou just? There is neither that sheweth, nor telleth before, nor heareth your words.
\v 27 The first shall say to Sion: Lo I am present, and to Jerusalem: I will give an evangelist.
\v 28 And I saw, and neither of these was there any that would consult, and being asked would answer a word.
\v 29 Behold all are unjust, and their works vain: their idols are wind and vanity.
\c 42
\p
\v 1 Behold my servant, I will receive him: mine elect, my soul hath pleased it-self in him: I have given my spirit upon him, he shall bring forth judgement to the Gentiles. \f + \fr 42:1 \ft Christ according to his humanity is the servant of God, by whom all other servants are redeemed, none else being able to satisfy for themselves, much less for others.\f* \x + \xo 42:1 \xt Mat. 17.\x*
\v 2 He shall not cry, nor accept person, neither shall his voice be heard abroad. \x + \xo 42:2 \xt Mat. 12.\x*
\v 3 The bruised reed he shall not break, and smoking flax he shall not quench: he shall bring forth judgement in truth.
\v 4 He shall not be sad, nor turbulent, till he set judgement in the earth: and the islands shall expect his law.
\v 5 Thus saith the Lord God that created the heavens, and stretched them out: that established the earth, and the things that spring thereof: that giveth breath to the people, that is upon it, and spirit to them that tread thereupon.
\v 6 I the Lord have called thee in justice, and taken thy hand, & preserved thee. And I have given thee for a covenant of the people, for a light of the Gentiles.
\v 7 That thou mightest open the eyes of the blind, and bring forth the prisoner out of prison, and them that sit in darkness out of the prison house.
\v 8 I the Lord, this is my name: I will not give my glory to another, and my praise to graven things.
\v 9 The things that were first, lo they are come: new things also I do shew: before they come forth, I will make you hear them.
\v 10 Sing ye to the Lord a new song, his praise is from the ends of the earth: ye that go down to the sea, and you the fullness thereof: ye islands, and inhabitants of the same.
\v 11 Let the desert be exalted and the cities thereof: Cedar shall dwell in houses: ye inhabitants of the Rock, give praise, they shall cry from the top of the mountains.
\v 12 They shall give glory to the Lord, and shall declare his praise in the islands.
\v 13 The Lord shall go forth as a strong man, as a man of war shall he raise up zeal: he shall shout and cry: over his enemies he shall be strengthened.
\v 14 I have always held my peace, I have kept silence, I have been patient, I will speak as a travailing woman: I will dissipate, and swallow up together.
\v 15 I will make mountains and little hills desolate, and will make all their grass to wither: and I will turn rivers into islands, and will dry up the standing pools. \f + \fr 42:15 \ft Such haughty and covetous minds as expect their Messias to be a worldly and warlike conquerer, that will advance his followers to kingdoms or princedoms, and to abundance of temporal riches, shall be frustrate of their vain hopes. Whereas Christ our Saviour both by example and doctrine teacheth the contrary, willing his followers to learn of him to be poor in spirit, meek & humble in heart, and their reward shall be great in heaven, not in earth; they shall be happy not in external, but in eternal glory.\f*
\v 16 And I will lead the blind into the way, which they know not: and in the paths, which they have been ignorant of I will make them walk: I will make darkness before them to be light, and crooked things straight: these words have I done to them, and have not forsaken them.
\v 17 They are turned backward: let them be confounded with confusion, that trust in graven thing, that say to the framed thing, ye are our gods.
\v 18 Hear ye deaf, and ye blind behold to see.
\v 19 Who is blind, but my servant? And deaf, but he to whom I have sent my messengers? Who is blind, but he that is sold? And who is blind, but the servant of the Lord?
\v 20 Thou that seest many things, wilt thou not keep them? Thou that hast ears open, wilt thou not hear?
\v 21 And the Lord hath been willing to sanctify him, and to magnify the law, and extol it.
\v 22 But the same people is spoiled, & wasted: all are the snare of youngmen, and they are hid in the houses of prisons: they are made a prey, neither is there to deliver them: a spoil, neither is there that saith: Restore.
\v 23 Who is there among you that will hear this, attend and harken for things to come?
\v 24 Who hath given Jacob into spoil, and Israel to the wasters? Hath not our Lord himself, to whom we have sinned? And they would not walk in his ways, and they have not heard his law.
\v 25 And he hath poured out upon them, the indignation of his fury, & a strong battle, and hath burnt him round about, and he knew not: and set him on fire, and he understood not.
\c 43
\p
\v 1 And now thus saith our Lord that created thee, o Jacob, & formed thee, o Israel: Fear not, because I have redeemed thee, and called thee by the name: thou art mine. \f + \fr 43:1 \ft Christ calleth and endueth sinners with grace, without any precedent good work or desire in them, even as he createth of nothing.\f*
\v 2 When thou shalt pass through the waters, I will be with thee, and the floods shall not cover thee: when thou shalt walk in fire, thou shalt not be burnt, and the flame shall not burn in thee: \f + \fr 43:2 \ft In all tribulations & persecutions Christ protecteth his servants, not suffering them to be tempted further than they may resist if they will. Whereby the Church still remaineth incontaminate, and shall never be destroyed.\f*
\v 3 Because I am the Lord thy God the holy one of Israel thy saviour, I have given Ægypt thy propitiation, Æthiopia and Saba for thee.
\v 4 Since thou becamest honourable in mine eyes, and glorious: I have loved thee, & I will give men for thee, and peoples for thy soul.
\v 5 Fear not, because I am with thee: from the East will I bring thy seed, and from the West I will gather thee.
\v 6 I will say to the North: Give: and to the South: Hinder not: bring my sons from a far, and my daughters from the ends of the earth.
\v 7 And every one that invocateth my name, for my glory have I created him, formed him, and made him.
\v 8 Bring forth the blind people, and having eyes: the deaf, and he that hath ears.
\v 9 All the nations are assembled together, and the tribes are gathered: which of you can shew this & shall make us hear the former things? Let them give their witnesses, and be justified, and hear, and say: In very deed.
\v 10 You are my witnesses, saith our Lord, and my servants whom I have chosen: that you may know, and believe me, and understand that I myself am. Before me there hath no God been formed, & after me there shall not be.
\v 11 I am, I am the Lord, and there is no saviour beside me.
\v 12 I have shewed, and have saved: I have made it heard, and there hath been no strange one among you. You are my witnesses, saith our Lord, and I God.
\v 13 And from the beginning I myself, and there is not that can deliver out of my hand: I will work, and who shall turn it away?
\v 14 Thus saith the Lord your redeemer, the holy one of Israel: For your sake have I sent forth into Babylon, and have plucked down all the bars, & Chaldees glorying in their ships. \f + \fr 43:14 \ft God made Cyrus conqueror of Babylon, not for his own sake, but for Israel, that he might release their captivity. For God perpetually disposeth of Kingdoms for\f*
\v 15 I the Lord your holy one, that created Israel your king.
\v 16 Thus saith our Lord, that gave a way in the sea, and a path in the vehement waters.
\v 17 Which brought forth the chariot & the horse, the arm and the strong: they slept together, neither shall they rise again: they are broken as flax, and are extinct.
\v 18 Remember not former things, and look not on things of old. \x + \xo 43:18 \xt 2. Cor. 5. Apo. 21.\x*
\v 19 Behold I make new things, and now they shall spring forth, verily you shall know them: I will make a way in the desert, and rivers in the place not haunted.
\v 20 The beast of the field shall glorify me, the dragons and the ostriches: because I have given waters in the desert: rivers in the place not haunted, that I might give drink to my people, to mine elect.
\v 21 This people have I formed for myself, they shall tell my praise.
\v 22 Thou hast not invocated me, o Jacob, neither hast thou laboured in me, o Israel.
\v 23 Thou hast not offered me the ram of thine holocaust, and with thy victims thou hast not glorified me: I have not made thee to serve in oblation, nor put thee to pain in frankincense.
\v 24 Thou hast not bought me sweet cane for silver, and with the fat of thy victims thou hast not inebriated me. But thou hast made me to serve with thy sins, thou hast put me to pain with thine iniquities.
\v 25 I am, I am he that take clean away thine iniquities for mine own sake, and I will not remember thy sins.
\v 26 Bring me into remembrance, & let us be judged together: tell if thou have any thing, that thou mayst be justified.
\v 27 Thy first father sinned, and thy interpreters have transgressed against me. \f + \fr 43:27 \ft The sin of Adam contaminating all mankind was not purged by any:\f* \f + \fr 43:27 \ft All Patriarchs, Priests, Prophets, & all others sinning, till Christ the innocent lamb came to take away the sin of the world.\f*
\v 28 And I have profaned the holy princes, I have given Jacob to destruction, & Israel to reproach.
\c 44
\p
\v 1 And now hear, o Jacob my servant, and Israel whom I have chosen.
\v 2 Thus saith the Lord that made and formed thee, the helper from the womb: fear not o my servant Jacob, and thou most righteous whom I have chosen. \f + \fr 44:2 \ft God's election preventeth man's good endeavour for without grace none could return to God.\f*
\v 3 For I will pour out waters upon the thirsty ground, and streams upon the dry land: I will pour out my spirit upon thy seed, and my blessing upon thy stock. \x + \xo 44:3 \xt Iere. 30. & 40.\x*
\v 4 And they shall spring the herbs as willows beside the waters running by.
\v 5 This man shall say: I am our Lord's: and another man shall call in the name of Jacob, and this will write with his hand, To the Lord: and in the name of Israel he shall be resembled.
\v 6 Thus saith our Lord the King of Israel; and the redeemer thereof the Lord of hosts: I am the first, and I the last, and beside me there is no God. \f + \fr 44:6 \ft Idolaters are foolish in leaving God, who is eternal and to trust in idols that neither can shew what was from the beginning, nor prophesy things to come.\f* \x + \xo 44:6 \xt Apo. 1. & 22.\x*
\v 7 Who is like to me? Let him call and declare: and let him expound me the order, since I appointed the ancient people: the things to come, and that shall be hereafter let them shew unto them.
\v 8 Fear ye not, neither be ye troubled, from that time I have made thee to hear, and have declared: you are my witnesses. Is there a God beside me, and a maker, whom I have not known?
\v 9 All the makers of an idol are nothing, and their best beloved things shall not profit them. Themselves are their witnesses, that they do not see, nor understand, that they may be confounded. \f + \fr 44:9 \ft All that is here said of the vanity of idols & foolish impiety of idolaters, may be referred (saith S. Ierom in this\f*
\v 10 Who hath formed a god, and molten a sculptile profitable to nothing?
\v 11 Behold, all the partakers thereof shall be confounded: for the makers are of men: they shall all assemble, they shall stand and fear, and shall be confounded together.
\v 12 The iron-smith hath wrought with the file, with coals, & with hammers he hath formed it, & hath wrought in the arm of his strength: he shall hunger and faint, he shall not drink water, and shall become weary. \x + \xo 44:12 \xt Sap. 13.\x*
\v 13 The carpenter hath stretched out a rule, he hath formed it with a plain: he hath made it with corners, and hath fashioned it round with the compass: and he hath made the image of a man, as it were a beautiful man dwelling in a house.
\v 14 He hath cut down cedars, taken the elm tree, & the oak that stood among the trees of the forest: he hath planted the pine tree, which the rain nourished.
\v 15 And it was made a fire for men: he took of them, and was warmed: and kindled them, & baked bread: but of the rest he wrought a god, & adored: he made a sculptile, and bowed down before it.
\v 16 Half he burnt with fire, and of the half broiled he flesh & eat it: he sod pottage, and was filled, and was warmed, and said: Aha, I am warm, I have seen the fire.
\v 17 But the rest thereof he made a god, and a sculptile to himself, he boweth before it, and beseecheth, saying: Deliver me, because thou art my God.
\v 18 They have not known, nor understood: for they have forgotten, that their eyes could not see, and that they could not understand with their heart.
\v 19 They do not recount in their mind, nor know, nor feel, that they should say: Half thereof I have burnt with fire, and I have baked bread upon the coals thereof: I have broiled flesh, & have eaten, and of the rest thereof shall I make an idol? Shall I fall down before the stock of a tree?
\v 20 Part thereof is ashes; an unwise heart adored it, & he will not save his soul, nor say: Perhaps there is a lie in my right hand.
\v 21 Remember these things, o Jacob, and Israel, because thou art my servant. I have formed thee, thou art my servant, o Israel, forget me not.
\v 22 I have clean taken away thine iniquities as a cloud, & thy sins as a mist: return to me because I have redeemed thee.
\v 23 Praise ye, o heavens, because the Lord hath done mercy: make jubilation ye ends of the earth: ye mountains sound praise, thou forest & every tree thereof, because the Lord hath redeemed Jacob, and Israel shall be glorified.
\v 24 Thus saith our Lord thy redeemer, & thy maker, from the womb: I am the Lord, that make all things, that alone stretch out the heavens, that establish the earth, and none with me.
\v 25 That make the signs of diviners void, and turn the soothsayers into fury. That turn the wise backward, and that make their knowledge foolish.
\v 26 That raiseth up the word of his servant, and accomplisheth the counsel of his messengers, which say to Jerusalem: Thou shalt be inhabited; & to the cities of Juda: You shall be built, and I will raise up the deserts thereof. \f + \fr 44:26 \ft In all this prophecy of the Church of Christ the Prophet alludeth to the history of Jerusalem destroyed by the Chaldees, and re-edified by permission of Cyrus, & Darius, in the times of Aggeus, & Zacharias.\f*
\v 27 Which say to the depth: Be thou desolate, and thy rivers I will dry up.
\v 28 Who say to Cyrus: Thou art my pastor, and thou shalt accomplish all my will. Who say to Jerusalem: Thou shalt be built; and to the temple: Thou shalt be formed.
\c 45
\p
because he acknowledgeth not God. 8. Upon which \add occasion the Prophet foresheweth the coming of Christ; 14. in figure of whom he addeth more of Cyrus: 18. and avoucheth that there is but one true God.\add* \f + \fr 45:0 \ft The 7. part. The delivery of the Jews from Babylon by Cyrus King of Medes and Persians, now also of Assyrians.\f*
\v 1 Thus saith the Lord to my christ Cyrus, whose right hand I have taken to subdue the Gentiles before his face, and to turn the backs of kings, and to open the doors before him, and the gates shall not be shut. \f + \fr 45:1 \ft Because all Kings that reign among the Jews were anointed with oil, Cyrus is called Christ, though he was not ordained with this ceremony of anointing.\f*
\v 2 I will go before thee, and will humble the glorious of the earth: I will break the brazen gates, and will burst the iron bars.
\v 3 And I will give thee hidden treasures, and mysteries of secrets: that thou mayst know that I am the Lord, which call thy name, the God of Israel.
\v 4 For my servant Jacob, and Israel mine elect, and I have called thee by thy name: I have resembled thee, and thou hast not known me. \f + \fr 45:4 \ft S. Ierom noteth here out of Iosephus (l. 11. Antiq.) that Cyrus finding his name long before prophesied by Isaias, became very benevolous to the Jews, loving them as the familiar servants of God.\f* \f + \fr 45:4 \ft But though he knew and professed one God, & no other (1. Esd. 1.) yet he was not converted in all points of religion, neither served God according to that general knowledge he had, & so knew not God rightly.\f* \x + \xo 45:4 \xt 2. Par. 26.\x*
\v 5 I the Lord, & there is none else: beside me there is no God: I girded thee, and thou hast not known me:
\v 6 that they which are from the rising of the sun, and which are from the west may know, that there is none beside me, I the Lord, and there is none other,
\v 7 that form light, and create darkness, make peace, and create evil: I the Lord that do all these things.
\v 8 Drop dew ye heavens from above, and let the clouds rain the just: be the earth opened, & bud forth a saviour: & let justice spring up withal: I the Lord have created him. \f + \fr 45:8 \ft The Prophet in the former prophecy contemplating Christ as in a figure, now elevated more in spirit, prophesieth of Christ only, who built his Church upon a sure rock. Not of Cyrus, who being advanced by God, yet perfectly knew not God, v. 4. nor of Zorobabel, who did not release the people from captivity, but together with others was released, neither had the title of a King, but lived in subjection to other Kings. S. Ierom in hunc locum.\f*
\v 9 Woe to him that gainsayeth his maker, a sherd of the earthen pots: shall the clay say to him that fashioneth it: What makest thou, & thy work is without hands? \x + \xo 45:9 \xt Rom. 9. Jere. 18.\x*
\v 10 Woe to him that saith to his father: Why doest thou beget? And to the woman: Why doest thou travail?
\v 11 Thus saith our Lord the holy one of Israel, the maker thereof: Ask me things to come: concerning my children & the work of my hands command you me.
\v 12 I made the earth: & man upon the same I have created: my hands stretched forth the heavens, and I have commanded all their host.
\v 13 I have raised him up to justice, & will direct all his ways: he shall build my city, & dismiss my captivity: not for price, nor for gifts, saith our Lord the God of hosts.
\v 14 Thus saith our Lord: The labour of Ægypt, and the merchandise of Æthiopia, and of Sabaim the high men shall pass to thee, & shall be thine: they shall walk after thee, they shall go bound with manacles: & they shall adore thee, & shall beseech thee: Only in thee is God, and there is no God beside thee.
\v 15 Verily thou art God hidden, the God of Israel a saviour.
\v 16 They are all confounded, and ashamed: the forgers of errors are gone together into confusion.
\v 17 Israel is saved in our Lord with eternal salvation: you shall not be confounded, and you shall not be ashamed for ever and ever.
\v 18 Because thus saith our Lord that created the heavens, the very God that formed the earth, and made it, the very maker thereof: he did not create it in vain: to be inhabited he formed it. I the Lord, and there is none other.
\v 19 I have not spoken in secret, in a dark place of the earth: I have not said to the seed of Jacob: Seek me in vain. I the Lord that speak justice, that declare right things.
\v 20 Gather ye together, and come, and approach together ye that are saved of the Gentiles: they have been ignorant that lift up the wood of their graven work, and ask of a god that saveth not.
\v 21 Declare ye, and come, and consult together: who hath made this to be heard from the beginning, from that time foretold this? Have not I the Lord, and there is no God besides but I? A just God, and that saveth there is none beside me.
\v 22 Be converted to me, and you shall be saved all ye ends of the earth: because I am God, and there is none other.
\v 23 I have sworn by myself, the word of justice shall proceed out of my mouth, and shall not return, because every knee shall be bowed to me, and every tongue shall swear. \x + \xo 45:23 \xt Rom. 14. Phil. 2.\x*
\v 24 Therefore in our Lord, shall he say, are my justices and empire: they shall come to him, and all that resist him, shall be confounded.
\v 25 In our Lord shall all the seed of Israel be justified and praised.
\c 46
\p
\v 1 Bel is broken, Nabo is destroyed: their idols are made to beasts & cattle, your burdens of heavy weight even unto weariness. \f + \fr 46:1 \ft Bel or Belus, called also Saturnus, was of such estimation, that they offered to him in sacrifice not only men that were taken captives, but also their own sons. Nabo, otherwise called Dagon, was an especial idol amongst the Philistiims. 1. Reg. 5.\f*
\v 2 They have melted away, and are broken together: they could not save him that carried them, & their soul shall go into captivity.
\v 3 Hear me, o house of Jacob, all the remnant of the house of Israel, which are carried of my womb, are borne up of my matrice.
\v 4 Even unto old age I am the same, and unto hoar hairs I will carry: I have made, & I will bear: I will carry, and will save.
\v 5 Whereto have you resembled me, and made me equal, and compared me, and made me like?
\v 6 You that contribute gold out of the bag, and weigh silver with balance: hiring a goldsmith to make a god: and they fall down and adore. \x + \xo 46:6 \xt Rom. 6.\x*
\v 7 They bear him on their shoulders carrying, and setting him in his place, and he shall stand, and shall not move out of his place. Yea when they shall cry also unto him, he shall not hear: from tribulation he shall not save them.
\v 8 Remember this, and be confounded: return ye transgressors to the heart.
\v 9 Remember the former world, because I am God, and there is no God beside, neither is there the like to me.
\v 10 Which shew the last thing from the beginning, and from the beginning the things that as yet were not done, saying: My counsel shall stand, & all my will shall be done:
\v 11 Which call a bird from the east, and from a far country, the man of mine own will, and I have spoken, and will bring it: I have created, and will do it. \f + \fr 46:11 \ft Not Cyrus (saith S. Ierom) but Christ the Orient star, prophesied by Balaam, Num. 24. whom the Sages came to adore from the East. Mat. 2.\f*
\v 12 Hear me ye hard hearted, which are far from justice.
\v 13 I have made my justice near, it shall not be far off, and my salvation shall not tarry. I will give salvation in Sion, and my glory to Israel.
\c 47
\p
\v 1 Come down, sit in the dust o Virgin daughter of Babylon, sit on the ground: there is no throne for the daughter of the Chaldees, because thou shalt no more be called nice and tender. \f + \fr 47:1 \ft Babylon not hitherto overcome at last was brought to misery and destruction.\f*
\v 2 Take a mill, and grind meal: make bare thy turpitude, discover the shoulder, uncover the thighs, pass the rivers.
\v 3 Thine ignominy shall be discovered, and thy reproach shall be seen: I will take vengeance, and no man shall resist me. \x + \xo 47:3 \xt Nahum 3.\x*
\v 4 Our redeemer, the Lord of hosts is his name, the holy one of Israel.
\v 5 Sit holding thy peace, and enter into darkness, o daughter of the Chaldees: because thou shalt no more be called the lady of kingdoms.
\v 6 I was angry against my people, I have contaminated mine inheritance, and have given them into thy hand: thou hast not shewed mercies to them: upon the ancient thou hast made thy yoke exceeding heavy. \f + \fr 47:6 \ft God's people contaminating themselves with sin, were suffered to fall into ignominious captivity; but God giveth them grace of repentance, & then severely punisheth their unmerciful afflicters & persecuters.\f*
\v 7 And thou hast said: I will be a lady for ever: thou hast not put these things upon thy heart, neither hast thou remembered thy later end.
\v 8 And now hear these things thou that art delicate, and dwellest confidently, that sayest in thy heart: I am, and there is none else beside me: I shall not sit a widow, and I shall not know barrenness. \x + \xo 47:8 \xt Apoc. 8.\x*
\v 9 These two things shall come to thee suddenly in one day, barrenness and widowhood. All things are come upon thee, because of the multitude of thy sorceries, and for the vehement hardness of thine enchanters. \x + \xo 47:9 \xt Infra. 5.\x*
\v 10 And thou hast confidence in thy malice, and hast said: There is none that seeth me. Thy wisdom, and thy knowledge, this hath deceived thee. And thou hast said in thy heart: I am, and beside me there is none other.
\v 11 Evil shall come upon thee, and thou shalt not know the rising thereof: and calamity shall fall violently upon thee, which thou canst not expiate: misery shall come upon thee suddenly, which thou shalt not know.
\v 12 Stand with thine enchanters, and with the multitude of thy sorceries, in which thou hast travailed from thy youth, if perhaps it may profit thee any thing, or if thou mayst become stronger.
\v 13 Thou hast failed in the multitude of thy counsels: let the astrologers of the heaven stand and save thee, which did contemplate the stars, and count the months, that by them they might tell things that shall come to thee.
\v 14 Behold they are become as stubble, fire hath burnt them, they shall not deliver their soul from the hand of the flame: there are no coals, wherewith they may be warmed, nor fire, that they may sit thereat.
\v 15 So are the things become unto thee, in whatsoever thou hast travailed: thy merchants from thy youth, every one hath erred in his own way, there is none that can save thee.
\c 48
\p
\v 1 Hear ye these things o house of Jacob, which are called by the name of Israel, and are come out of the waters of Juda, which swear in the name of our Lord, and are mindful of the God of Israel not in truth, nor in justice. \f + \fr 48:1 \ft By waters in the Hebrew phrase is here understood the fountain, or spring, the Prophet speaking to those that were of the tribe of Juda: who especially challenged the preeminences and blessings of Israel the Patriarch, but had not his virtues of fortitude, and internal sight of God, signified by the name Israel.\f*
\v 2 For they are called of the holy city, and are established upon the God of Israel: the Lord of hosts is his name.
\v 3 The former things of old I have declared, & they proceeded out of my mouth, and I have made them to be heard: Suddenly I have wrought, and they came.
\v 4 For I knew that thou art stubborn, and thy neck is an iron sinew, and thy forehead of brass.
\v 5 Iforetold thee of old: before they came I told thee, lest perhaps thou shouldst say: My idols have done these things, & my sculptiles & moltens have commanded these things.
\v 6 See all the things which thou hast heard: but have you declared them? I have made thee know new things of old, and the things are kept which thou knowest not:
\v 7 now they are created, and not of old: and before the day, and thou heardest them not, lest perhaps thou mightest say: Behold I knew them.
\v 8 Thou hast neither heard, nor known, neither was thine ear opened of old. For I know that transgressing thou wilt transgress, and I have called thee a transgressor from the womb.
\v 9 For my name's sake I will make my fury far off: and for my praise I will bridle thee, that thou perish not. \f + \fr 48:9 \ft God spareth & conserveth his people, not for their merits but of his mercy, shewing his benignity that they may repent if they will.\f*
\v 10 Behold I have fined thee, but not as silver, I have chosen thee in the furnace of poverty.
\v 11 For myself, for myself will I do it, that I be not blasphemed: and I will not give my glory to another.
\v 12 Hear me, o Jacob, and thou Israel whom I call: I the same, I the first, & I the last.
\v 13 My hand also hath founded the earth, and my right hand hath measured the heavens: I shall call them, & they shall stand together.
\v 14 Assemble ye together all you, & hear: which of them hath shewed these things? The Lord hath loved him, he will do his will in Babylon, and his arm in the Chaldees.
\v 15 I, even I have spoken, and called him: I have brought him, and his way is directed.
\v 16 Come ye to me, and hear this: I have not spoken in secret from the beginning, from the time before it was done I was there, and now the Lord God hath sent me, and his spirit.
\v 17 Thus saith our Lord thy Redeemer, the holy one of Israel: I the Lord thy God that teach thee profitable things, that govern thee in the way that thou walkest.
\v 18 I would thou hadst attended to my commandments: thy peace had been as a flood, and thy justice as the waves of the sea.
\v 19 And thy seed had been as the sand, and the stock of thy womb as the gravel stones thereof: his name had not perished, neither had it been destroyed from before my face.
\v 20 Come forth out of Babylon, fly from the Chaldees, shew it forth in the voice of exultation: make this to be heard, and speak it out even to the ends of the earth. Say: Our Lord hath redeemed his servant Jacob. \x + \xo 48:20 \xt Iere. 21.\x*
\v 21 They thirsted not in the desert, when he brought them forth: water out of the rock he brought forth to them, and he clove the rocks, and there flowed waters. \x + \xo 48:21 \xt Exod. 1. Nu. 20.\x*
\v 22 There is no peace to the impious, saith our Lord. \f + \fr 48:22 \ft These promises of reconciliation to God, and of peace, pertain to the penitent, not to the obstinate in impiety.\f*
\c 49
\p
\v 1 Hear ye islands, and attend ye peoples from a far. The Lord hath called me from the womb, from my mother's belly he hath been mindful of my name. \f + \fr 49:1 \ft This word from afar, & the like doth convince (saith S. Ierom) that the Prophet speaketh of all nations to be converted to Christ. And as this Prophet hath already spoken much of Christ and his Church, so henceforth more especially he sheweth himself rather an Evangelist, or an Apostle, than only a Prophet: which S. Ierom testifieth of him. Epist. ad Paulin.\f*
\v 2 And he hath made my mouth as a sharp sword: in the shadow of his hand he hath protected me, & hath made me as a chosen arrow in his quiver he hath hidden me.
\v 3 And he said to me: Thou art my servant Israel, because in thee will I glory.
\v 4 And I said: I have laboured in vain, without cause, and in vain have I spent my strength: therefore my judgement is with the Lord, and my work with my God.
\v 5 And now saith the Lord, that formed me from the womb to be his servant, that I may reduce Jacob unto him, and Israel will not be gathered together: and I am glorified in the eyes of the Lord, and my God is made my strength.
\v 6 And he said: It is a small thing that thou shouldst be my servant to raise up the tribes of Jacob, and to convert the dregs of Israel. Behold, I have given thee to be the light of the Gentiles, that thou mayst be salvation even to the farthest part of the earth. \x + \xo 49:6 \xt Act. 13.\x*
\v 7 Thus saith our Lord the redeemer of Israel, the holy one thereof, to the contemptible soul, to the nation that is abhorred, to the servant of lords: kings shall see, & princes shall rise, & adore for our Lord's sake, because he is faithful, & for the holy one of Israel who hath chosen thee.
\v 8 Thus saith our Lord: In time acceptable I have heard thee, and in the day of salvation I have holpen thee: and I have kept thee, and given thee to be a covenant of the people, that thou mightest raise up the land, and possess the inheritances dissipated. \x + \xo 49:8 \xt 2. Cor. 6.\x*
\v 9 That thou mightest say to them, that are bound: Come forth, & to them that are in darkness: Be ye discovered. Upon the ways shall they feed, & their pastures shall be in all plains.
\v 10 They shall not hunger nor thirst, & heat and sun shall not strike them: because he that is merciful to them shall govern them, and all the fountains of waters shall give them drink. \x + \xo 49:10 \xt Apoc. 7.\x*
\v 11 And I will make all my mountains to be a way, & my paths shall be exalted.
\v 12 Behold these shall come from far, & behold they from the North and the sea, and these from the South country.
\v 13 Ye heavens praise, and earth rejoice, ye mountains give praise with jubilation, because our Lord hath comforted his people, and will have mercy on his poor ones.
\v 14 And Sion said: Our Lord hath forsaken me, & our Lord hath forgotten me. \f + \fr 49:14 \ft The Church of the old testament lamenteth that she seemeth to be forsaken, in respect of the many great benefits bestowed on the Church of Christ.\f*
\v 15 Why, can a woman forget her infant, that she will not have pity on the son of her womb? And if she should forget, yet will not I forget thee. \f + \fr 49:15 \ft But God answereth that he cannot, & will not forget, nor forsake his Church which indeed is all one in the old and new testament, only differing in state, and therefore that which he doth to her in the new testament, pertaineth to the whole Church in general of all times & all places.\f*
\v 16 Behold, I have written thee in my hands, thy walls are before mine eyes always.
\v 17 Thy builders are come: they that destroy thee and dissipate thee shall go out of thee.
\v 18 Lift up thine eyes round about, and see, all these are gathered together, they are come to thee: I live, saith our Lord, for thou shalt be clothed with all these as with an ornament, and as a bride thou shalt put them about thee. \x + \xo 49:18 \xt Isa. 60.\x*
\v 19 Because thy deserts, and thy solitary places, & the land of thy ruin, shall now be strait by reason of the inhabitants, & they shall be chased far away that swallowed thee up.
\v 20 As yet shall the children of thy barrenness say in thine ears: The place is strait for me, make me space to dwell.
\v 21 And thou shalt say in thy heart: Who hath begot me these? I am barren & not bearing, led into transmigration, & captive: & these who hath brought up? I destitute & alone: & these where were they?
\v 22 Thus saith our Lord God: behold I will lift up my hand to the Gentiles, & to the peoples I will exalt my sign. And they shall carry thy sons in their arms, and thy daughters upon their shoulders.
\v 23 And kings shall be thy nursing fathers, & queens thy nurses: with countenance cast down toward the ground they shall adore thee, & they shall lick up the dust of thy feet. And thou shalt know that I am the Lord, upon whom they shall not be confounded that expect him.
\v 24 Shall a prey be taken from the strong? Or can that which was caught of the mighty be saved?
\v 25 Because thus saith our Lord: Yea verily, even the captivity shall be taken away from the strong: and that which was taken by the mighty, shall be saved. But those that have judged thee, will I judge, and thy children I will save.
\v 26 And I will feed thine enemies with their own flesh: & as with new wine, so shall they be imbrued with their own blood: and all flesh shall know, that I am the Lord that save thee, & thy redeemer the mighty one of Jacob.
\c 50
\p
\v 1 Thus saith our Lord: What is this bill of the divorce of our mother, wherewith I have dismissed her? Or who is my creditor, to whom I sold you? Lo you are sold for your wicked deeds, I have dismist your mother. \f + \fr 50:1 \ft God divorced not the Synagogue from him of hardness of heart.\f* \f + \fr 50:1 \ft Neither delivered her for payment, as though he were in debt to any creditor.\f* \f + \fr 50:1 \ft But her own revolt, and iniquities separated her from Christ.\f*
\v 2 Because I came, and there was not a man: I called, and there was none that would hear. Why, is mine hand abridged and made a little one, that I cannot redeem? Or is there no strength in me to deliver? Behold, in my rebuke I will make the sea desert, I will turn the floods into dry land: the fishes shall rot without water, and shall die for thirst. \x + \xo 50:2 \xt Isa. 59. Num. 11.\x*
\v 3 I will clothe the heavens with darkness, and will make sackcloth their covering.
\v 4 The Lord hath given me a learned tongue, that I may know to stay him up that is weary, with a word: he stirreth up in the morning, in the morning he stirreth up mine ear, that I may hear him as a master. \f + \fr 50:4 \ft Skill of tongue how to speak, & discretion when & where, was given to Isaias, ch. 6. v. 6. Much more (saith S. Ierom) to Christ: who spake in his life, was silent in his passion, and now speaketh by his Apostles, and other pastors.\f*
\v 5 The Lord God hath opened mine ear, & I do not gainsay? I am not gone backward.
\v 6 I have given my body to the strikers, & my cheeks to the pluckers: I have not turned away my face from the rebukers & spitters. \x + \xo 50:6 \xt Mat. 26.\x*
\v 7 The Lord God is mine helper, therefore am I not confounded: therefore have I set my face, as a most hard rock, and I know that I shall not be confounded.
\v 8 He is near that justifieth me, who shall gainsay me? Let us stand together. Who is mine adversary? Let him come to me. \x + \xo 50:8 \xt Rom. 8.\x*
\v 9 Behold the Lord God my helper: who is he that shall condemn me? Lo they shall all be destroyed as a garment, the moth shall eat them.
\v 10 Which of you feareth our Lord, heareth the voice of his servant, who hath walked in darkness, and hath no light? Let him hope in the name of our Lord, & lean upon his God.
\v 11 Lo all you do kindle a fire, are compassed with flames, walk in the light of your fire, and in the flames which you have kindled: of my hand is this done to you, you shall sleep in sorrows.
\c 51
\p
persecution, nor be overcome: 23. but her enemies shall \add fail.\add*
\v 1 Hear me ye that follow that which is just, and that seek our Lord: attend to the rock whence you are hewn out, & to the cave of the lake from the which you are cut out. \f + \fr 51:1 \ft In the next verse the rock & cave are explicated to signify Abraham and Sara, who are proposed for examples to be imitated, being so noble progenitors of the Jews. S. Paul exhorteth his country men, and in them all Christians, the like in spiritual progenitors, that first plant Catholic Religion in any place saying: Remember your Prelates which have spoken the word of God to you: Heb. 13.\f*
\v 2 Attend to Abraham your father, and to Sara that bare you: because I called him alone, and blessed him, & multiplied him.
\v 3 Our Lord therefore will comfort Sion, and will comfort all the ruins thereof: and he will make her desert as delicacies, and her wilderness as the garden of our Lord. Joy and gladness shall be found in it, giving of thanks, and voice of praise.
\v 4 Attend unto me, o my people, and my tribe hear ye me: because a law shall proceed from me, and my judgement shall rest to be a light of the peoples.
\v 5 My just one is nigh at hand, my saviour is gone forth, and mine arms shall judge peoples: the islands shall expect me, & shall patiently wait for mine arm.
\v 6 Lift up your eyes into heaven, and look down to the earth beneath: because the heavens shall melt as smoke, and the earth shall be worn away as a garment, and like to these things shall the inhabitants thereof perish: but my salvation shall be for ever, and my justice shall not fail.
\v 7 Hear me ye that know that which is just, my people which have my law in their heart: fear ye not the reproach of men, and be not afraid of their blasphemies. \x + \xo 51:7 \xt Ps. 36.\x*
\v 8 For as a garment so shall the worm eat them: and as wool, so shall the moth devour them, but my salvation shall be for ever, and my justice unto generations of generations.
\v 9 Arise, arise, put on strength o arm of our Lord: arise as in the old days, in the generations of worlds. Hast not thou strucken the proud, & wounded the dragon? \f + \fr 51:9 \ft As God destroyed Pharao the proud dragon in the sea, which he dried up for his people to pass, so he will overthrow the devil, & deliver captives from sin & tyranny.\f*
\v 10 Hast not thou dried the sea, the water of the vehement, which madest the depth of the sea a way, that the delivered might pass. \x + \xo 51:10 \xt Exo. 14.\x*
\v 11 And now they that are redeemed of our Lord shall return, and shall come into Sion praying, and joy everlasting upon their heads, they shall possess joy and gladness, sorrow and mourning shall fly away.
\v 12 I, even I myself will comfort you: who art thou that thou shouldest be afraid of a mortal man, and of the son of man, which as grass so shall wither?
\v 13 And thou hast forgotten our Lord thy maker, which stretched out the heavens, and founded the earth: and thou hast been afraid continually all the day at the face of his fury, which afflicted thee, and had prepared to destroy: where is now the fury of the affliction?
\v 14 He shall quickly come going to open, and he shall not kill unto utter destruction, neither shall his bread fail.
\v 15 But I am the Lord thy God which trouble the sea, and the waves thereof do swell, the Lord of hosts is my name.
\v 16 I have put my words in thy mouth, and in the shadow of my hand I have protected thee, that thou mightest plant the heavens, and found the earth, & mightest say to Sion: Thou art my people. \x + \xo 51:16 \xt Isa. 49.\x*
\v 17 Be lifted up, be lifted up, arise Jerusalem, which hast drunken of the hand of our Lord the cup of his wrath: even to the bottom of the cup of drowsiness hast thou drunk, even to the dregs.
\v 18 There is none that can uphold her of all the children that she hath born: and there is none that taketh her by the hand of all the children, that she hath brought up.
\v 19 There are two things which have happened to thee: who shall be sorry for thee? Spoil, and destruction, and famine, and the sword, who shall comfort thee? \f + \fr 51:19 \ft Spoil & destruction shall happen by famine & sword.\f* \x + \xo 51:19 \xt Isa. 47.\x*
\v 20 Thy children are thrown forth, they have slept in the head of all ways, as the oryx that is snared: full of the indignation of our Lord, of the rebuke of thy God.
\v 21 Therefore hear this poor little one, and drunken not of wine.
\v 22 Thus saith thy dominatour our Lord, and thy God, who hath fought for his people: Behold I have taken out of thy hand the cup of drowsiness, the bottom of the cup of mine indignation, thou shalt not add to drink it any more.
\v 23 And I will put it in their hand, that have humbled thee, and have said to thy soul: Bow down, that we may pass over: and thou hast laid thy body as the ground, and as a way to them that pass over?
\c 52
\p
\v 1 Arise, arise, put on thy strength o Sion, put on the garments of thy glory o Jerusalem the city of the holy one: because the uncircumcised, and unclean shall add no more to pass by thee.
\v 2 Be shaken out of the dust, arise, sit up Jerusalem: loose the bonds of thy neck, o captive daughter of Sion.
\v 3 Because thus saith our Lord: You were sold for nought, and without silver you shall be redeemed. \f + \fr 52:3 \ft The Jews had not wronged the Babylonians, neither had mankind sinned against the devil, but both had offended God.\f* \f + \fr 52:3 \ft Who of his bounty payed man's ransom: which no other man was able to pay.\f*
\v 4 Because thus saith our Lord God: My people went down into Ægypt at the beginning to be a sojourner there: and Assur without any cause did oppress them. \x + \xo 52:4 \xt Gen. 46.\x*
\v 5 And now what have I here? Saith our Lord: because my people is taken away for nought. Their rulers do unjustly, saith our Lord, and continually all the day my name is blasphemed. \x + \xo 52:5 \xt Rom. 2. Ezec. 36.\x*
\v 6 For this cause shall my people know my name in that day: because I myself that spake, lo am present.
\v 7 How beautiful upon the mountains are the feet of him that evangelizeth & preacheth peace: of him that telleth good, preaching health, that saith to Sion: Thy God shall reign.
\v 8 The voice of thy watchmen, they have lifted up their voice, they shall praise together: because eye to eye they shall see when our Lord shall convert Sion.
\v 9 Rejoice, & praise together ye deserts of Jerusalem: because our Lord hath comforted his people: he hath redeemed Jerusalem.
\v 10 Our Lord hath prepared his holy arm in the sight of all the Gentiles: and all the ends of the earth shall see the salvation of our God.
\v 11 Depart, depart, go ye out from thence, touch not a polluted thing: go out of the midst of her, be cleansed ye that carry the vessels of our Lord. \f + \fr 52:11 \ft Communication with infidels in spiritual things is in no case lawful, as S. Paul sheweth by this text. 2. Cor. 6. v. 17.\f*
\v 12 Because you shall not go out in tumult, neither with flight shall you make haste: for our Lord will go before you, and the God of Israel will gather you together.
\v 13 Behold my servant shall understand, he shall be exalted, and shall be lifted up, and shall be exceeding high.
\v 14 As many have been astonished upon thee, so shall his look among men be inglorious, and his form among the sons of men.
\v 15 He shall sprinkle many nations, kings shall shut their mouth upon him: because they to whom it was not told of him, have seen: and they that heard not have beheld.
\c 53
\p
\v 1 Who hath believed our hearing? And the arm of our Lord to whom is it revealed? \f + \fr 53:1 \ft That many hearing the truth preached do not believe it, is by their obstinate freewill, because they do not obey the Gospel. Ro. 10. v. 16. when their understanding directeth them that it is not disagreeable to reason.\f*
\v 2 And he shall come up as a young spring before him, and as a root from a thirsty ground: there is no beauty in him, nor comeliness, and we have seen him, and there was no sightliness, and we were desirous of him.
\v 3 Despised, and most abject of men, a man of sorrows, and knowing infirmity: and his look as it were hid and despised, whereupon neither have we esteemed him.
\v 4 He surely hath born our infirmities, and our sorrows he hath carried: and we have thought him as it were a leper, & strucken of God, and humbled.
\v 5 But he was wounded for our iniquities, he was broken for our sins: the discipline of our peace upon him, and with the wail of his stripe we are healed.
\v 6 All we have strayed as sheep, every one hath declined into his own way: and our Lord hath put upon him the iniquity of all us.
\v 7 He was offered because himself would, and opened not his mouth: as a sheep to slaughter shall he be led, and as a lamb before his shearer, he shall be dumb, & shall not open his mouth:
\v 8 from distress and from judgement he was taken up: who shall declare his generation? Because he is cut out of the land of the living, for the wickedness of my people have I strucken him.
\v 9 And he shall give the impious for his burial, and the rich for his death: because he hath not done iniquity, neither was there guile in his mouth. \f + \fr 53:9 \ft Our Saviour died and was buried where the wicked were commonly punished:\f* \f + \fr 53:9 \ft Yet was buried richly & honourably by Ioseph of Aremathia & Nicodemus.\f*
\v 10 And our Lord would break him in infirmity. If he shall put away his soul for sin, he shall see seed of long age, and the will of our Lord shall be directed in his hand.
\v 11 For that his soul hath laboured, he shall see and be filled: in his knowledge the same my just servant shall justify many, and he shall bear their iniquities.
\v 12 Therefore will I distribute unto him very many, and he shall divide the spoils of the strong, for that he hath delivered his soul unto death, and was reputed with the wicked: and he hath borne the sins of many, and hath prayed for the transgressors.
\c 54
\p
\v 1 Praise o barren woman which bearest not: sing praise, and make joyful noise, which didst not bear: because many are the children of the desolate, more than of her that hath a husband, saith our Lord. \f + \fr 54:1 \ft In the old testament Gentiles were barren bringing no fruit to God, but in the new testament they are fruitful, & the Jews are barren, till the latter end of the world, when they also shall be fruitful again.\f* \x + \xo 54:1 \xt Gal. 4.\x*
\v 2 Enlarge the place of thy tent, and stretch out the skins of thy tabernacles, spare not: make long thy cords, and fasten thy nails.
\v 3 For thou shalt penetrate to the right hand, and to the left: and thy seed shall inherit the Gentiles, & shall inhabit the desolate cities.
\v 4 Fear not, because thou shall not be confounded, nor blush: for thou shalt not be ashamed, because thou shalt forget the confusion of thy youth, and the reproach of thy widowhood thou shalt remember no more.
\v 5 Because he shall rule over thee that made thee, the Lord of hosts is his name: & thy redeemer the holy one of Israel, shall be called the God of all the earth. \x + \xo 54:5 \xt Luc. 1.\x*
\v 6 For as a woman forsaken & mourning in spirit hath our Lord called thee, & as a wife cast off from her youth, hath thy God said:
\v 7 For a moment, a little while have I forsaken thee, & in great mercies will I gather thee.
\v 8 In a moment of indignation have I hid my face a little while from thee, & in mercy everlasting have I had mercy on thee, said thy redeemer our Lord.
\v 9 As in the days of Noe is this thing to me, to whom I sware, that I would no more bring in the waters of Noe upon the earth: so have I sworn not to be angry with thee, and not to rebuke thee. \f + \fr 54:9 \ft As it is assured that the world shall never be drowned again with water, so it is, that the Church of Christ shall never be suppressed.\f* \x + \xo 54:9 \xt Gen. 9.\x*
\v 10 For the mountains shall be moved, & the little hills shall tremble; but my mercy shall not depart from thee, & the covenant of my peace shall not be moved, said our Lord thy miseratour. \f + \fr 54:10 \ft Another assurance, that mountains & hills shall rather be moved, yea some mountains shall be removed, but the Church shall be always firm and perpetual.\f*
\v 11 Poor little one shaken with tempest, without all comfort, behold I will lay thy stones in order, & will found thee in sapphires,
\v 12 & I will put the jasper stone for thy munitions: & thy gates into graven stones, all thy borders into stones worthy to be desired.
\v 13 All thy children taught of our Lord: & a multitude of peace to thy children. \x + \xo 54:13 \xt Ioan 6. v. 45.\x*
\v 14 And in justice thou shalt be founded: depart far from calumny, because thou shalt not fear: and from dread, because it shall not approach to thee.
\v 15 Behold, the borderer shall come, which was not with me, thy stranger sometime shall be joined to thee.
\v 16 Behold, I have created the smith that bloweth the coals in the fire, & bringeth forth a vessel for his work, & I created the killer to destroy.
\v 17 Every vessel that is made against thee, shall not prosper: and every tongue resisting thee in judgement, thou shalt judge. This is the inheritance of the servants of our Lord, and their justice with me, saith our Lord.
\c 55
\p
\v 1 All ye that thirst come to the waters: and you that have no silver, make haste, buy, & eat: come, buy without silver, and without any exchange wine and milk. \f + \fr 55:1 \ft Grace is offered to all, but those only are justified, and replenished with more grace and spiritual gifts, that cooperate, doing that which in them lieth, desiring & thirsting justice, for such (saith our Saviour) shall have their fill. Mat. 5. v. 6.\f* \x + \xo 55:1 \xt Apo. 22.\x*
\v 2 Why bestow you silver not for bread, & your labour not for satiety? Hearing hear ye me, and eat that which is good, and your soul shall be delighted in fatness.
\v 3 Incline your ear, & come to me: hear, and your soul shall live, and I will make an everlasting covenant with you, the faithful mercies of David. \x + \xo 55:3 \xt Act. 13.\x*
\v 4 Behold I have given him for a witness to the peoples, for a Prince and master to the Gentiles.
\v 5 Behold thou shalt call the nation, which thou knowest not: and the nations that knew not thee shall run to thee, because of the Lord thy God, and the holy one of Israel: because he hath glorified thee.
\v 6 Seek ye our Lord whilst he may be found, invocate him, whilst he is near.
\v 7 Let the impious forsake his way, and the unjust man his cogitations, and return to our Lord, and he will have mercy on him: and to our God, because he is bountiful to forgive. \f + \fr 55:7 \ft The beginning of God's service is to forsake the way of wickedness.\f*
\v 8 For my cogitations are not your cogitations: nor your ways my ways, saith our Lord.
\v 9 For as the heavens are exalted above the earth, so are my ways exalted above your ways, & my cogitations above your cogitations. \f + \fr 55:9 \ft The ways of God's service, and of serving this world, are so opposite and contrary, that it is unpossible to walk in them both at once. No man can serve these two masters, God and this world. We must therefore so use this world, that we may serve God, and inherit heaven.\f*
\v 10 And as the shower cometh down, and the snow from heaven, and returneth no more thither, but inebriateth the earth, and watereth it, and maketh it to spring, and giveth seed to the sower, and bread to him that eateth:
\v 11 so shall my word be, which shall proceed from my mouth: it shall not return to me void, but it shall do what things soever I would, and shall prosper in these things for which I sent it.
\v 12 Because you shall go forth in joy, and in peace shall you be conducted, the mountains and the little hills shall sing praise before you, and all the woods of the country shall clap the hand.
\v 13 For the shrub, shall come up the fir tree, and for the nettle, shall grow the myrtle tree: and our Lord shall be named for an everlasting sign, that shall not be taken away.
\c 56
\p
\v 1 Thus saith our Lord: keep ye judgement, and do justice: because my salvation is near to come, and my justice to be revealed. \f + \fr 56:1 \ft Judgement is a right resolution to do God's will, and justice is the perfect performance thereof, as before is noted, cha. 32.\f* \x + \xo 56:1 \xt Sap. 1.\x*
\v 2 Blessed is the man that doth this thing, and the son of man that shall apprehend this, keeping the Sabbath that he pollute it not, keeping his hands that he do no evil.
\v 3 And let not the son of the stranger, that cleaveth to our Lord, say: By separation the Lord will divide me from his people.
\v 4 And let not the eunuch say: Behold I am a dry tree. Because thus saith our Lord to the eunuchs: They that shall keep my Sabbaths, and shall choose the things that I would, and shall hold my covenant. \f + \fr 56:4 \ft Under the name of Sabbath is understood the observation of all the law.\f* \f + \fr 56:4 \ft Those that of free election choose good things not commanded, deserve greater reward.\f*
\v 5 I will give unto them in my house, and within my walls a place, and a name better than sons and daughters, an everlasting name will I give them, which shall not perish.
\v 6 And the children of the stranger that cleave to the Lord, to worship him, & to love his name, to be his servants: every one that keepeth the Sabbath not to pollute it, and that holdeth my covenant.
\v 7 I will bring them into my holy mount, & will make them joyful in the house of my prayer: their holocausts, and their victims shall please me upon mine altar: because my house shall be called the house of prayer to all peoples. \x + \xo 56:7 \xt Mat. 21. Mat. 11. Luc. 19.\x*
\v 8 Saith our Lord God that gathereth the dispersed of Israel: As yet will I gather unto it, the gathered together thereof.
\v 9 All ye beasts of the field come to devour, all ye beasts of the forest. \f + \fr 56:9 \ft The Prophet foreseeing in spirit the careless negligence of some Pastors, of just zeal & charity inveigheth against them: warning them of their grievous punishment.\f*
\v 10 His watchmen all blind have been ignorant: dumb dogs not able to bark, seeing vain things, sleeping and loving dreams.
\v 11 And most impudent dogs, they have known no satiety: the pastors themselves have been ignorant of understanding: all have declined into their own way, every one to his own avarice, from the highest even to the last. \x + \xo 56:11 \xt Iere. 6. & 8. Sap. 2.\x*
\v 12 Come, let us take wine, and be filled with drunkenness, and it shall be as today, so also tomorrow, and much more.
\c 57
\p
\v 1 The just perisheth, and there is none that considereth in his heart, & men of mercy are gathered away, because there is none that understandeth; for at the face of malice, is the just gathered away. \f + \fr 57:1 \ft Just men dying seem to the wicked to perish.\f* \f + \fr 57:1 \ft But they are gathered to the happy society of other blessed souls.\f* \f + \fr 57:1 \ft And commonly God so taketh away the just, when he will punish the wicked people, that they may not in this world see the general calamity of others.\f*
\v 2 Let peace come, let him rest in his bed that hath walked in his direction.
\v 3 But come you hither ye children of the witch, the seed of the adulterer, and of the harlot.
\v 4 Upon whom have you jested? Upon whom have you opened your mouth awide, and thrust out the tongue? Are not you wicked children, a lying seed?
\v 5 Which take comfort in the gods under every thick green tree, immolating your little ones in the torrents, under the high rocks?
\v 6 In the parts of the torrent is thy part, this is thy lot: and thou hast poured out libament to them, thou hast offered sacrifice, shall I not take indignation of these things?
\v 7 Upon an high and lofty mountain thou hast laid thy bed, and hast gone up thither to immolate hosts.
\v 8 And behind the door, and behind the post thou hast set thy memorial: because thou hast discovered thyself near me, and hast received an adulterer, thou hast enlarged thy bed, and made a covenant with them: thou hast loved their couch with open hand.
\v 9 And thou hast adorned thyself with royal ointment, and hast multiplied the gay paintings. Thou didst send thy legates far off, & wast humbled even to hell.
\v 10 In the multitude of thy way thou hast laboured; thou saidst not: I will rest: thou hast found life of thine own hand, therefore thou hast not asked.
\v 11 For whom, with careful reverence, hast thou feared, whereas thou hast lied, & hast not been mindful of me, nor thought on me in thy heart? Because I am holding my peace, and as it were not seeing, and thou hast forgotten me.
\v 12 I will declare thy justice, and thy works shall not profit thee.
\v 13 When thou shalt cry, let thy gathered together deliver thee, and the wind shall take them all away, a soft blast shall bear them away: But he that hath confidence in me, shall inherit the land, & shall possess my holy mount.
\v 14 And I will say: Make a way, give passage, turn out of the path, take away stumbling blocks out of the way of my people. \x + \xo 57:14 \xt Isa. 62. v. 10.\x*
\v 15 Because thus saith the High & Eminent, that inhabiteth eternity: and his name is holy, dwelling in the high, and holy place, and with a contrite & humble spirit: that he may revive the spirit of the humble, and revive the heart of the contrite.
\v 16 For I will not contend for ever, neither will I be wrath unto the end: because the spirit shall proceed from my face, and breathings I will make. \f + \fr 57:16 \ft To the humble & contrite penitents God sheweth all benignity, and granteth wished good things: as prosperous winds to sea-faring travelers, & the like.\f*
\v 17 For the iniquity of his avarice I was angry, and have strucken him: I have hid my face from thee, and have taken indignation: and he hath gone wandering in the way of his own heart.
\v 18 Isaw his ways, and have healed him, and reduced him, and have restored consolations unto him, and to them that mourn for him.
\v 19 I have created the fruit of the lips peace, peace to him that is far off, & that is near, saith our Lord, and I have healed him.
\v 20 But the impious are as it were the raging sea, which cannot be quiet, and the waves thereof overflow unto conculcation and mire.
\v 21 There is no peace to the impious, saith our Lord God. \f + \fr 57:21 \ft Those that persist obstinate can have no remission.\f* \x + \xo 57:21 \xt Isa. 48. v. 22.\x*
\c 58
\p
\v 1 Cry, cease not, as a trumpet exalt thy voice, and tell my people their wicked doings, and the house of Jacob their sins. \f + \fr 58:1 \ft Many sinners are so fast asleep in their wickedness, that they cannot, or rather will not hear ordinary admonitions: to such therefore God's Preachers must cry, and not cease to cry, as with a loud trumpet exalt their voice, opportunely, importunely with all patience, & longamity, till they make the deaf to hear, to believe the truth, and the dumb to speak, that is, to profess virtue in word & deed. Mar. 7.\f*
\v 2 For me indeed they seek from day to day, and they will know my ways, as a nation that hath done justice, and hath not forsaken the judgement of their God: they ask of me the judgements of justice: they will approach to God.
\v 3 Why have we fasted, and thou hast not regarded: have we humbled our souls, and thou hast not known? Behold in the day of your fast your own will is found, and you exact of all your debters.
\v 4 Behold you fast to debates and contentions, and strike with the fist impiously. Do not fast as until this day, that your cry may be heard on high.
\v 5 Is this such a fast, as I have chosen: for a man by the day to afflict his soul? Is this it, to wind his head about like a circle, and to spread sack-cloth and ashes? Wilt thou call this a fast, and a day acceptable to the Lord? \x + \xo 58:5 \xt Zach. 7.\x*
\v 6 Is not this rather the fast that I have chosen? Dissolve the bands of impiety, loose the bundles that overload, dismiss them free that are broken, and break in sunder every burden. \f + \fr 58:6 \ft Cultus Dei. Luc. 2. v. 37. Dissolve the bands of impiety, loose the bundles that overload, dismiss them free that are broken, and break in sunder every burden.\f*
\v 7 Break thy bread to the hungry & the needy, & harborless bring in into thy house: when thou shalt see the naked cover him, and despise not thy flesh. \x + \xo 58:7 \xt Eze. 18. Mat. 25.\x*
\v 8 Then shall thy light break forth as the morning, and thy health shall sooner arise, & thy justice shall go before thy face, and the glory of our Lord shall embrace thee.
\v 9 Then shalt thou invocate, and our Lord will hear: thou shalt cry, and he will say: Lo here I am. If thou wilt take away the chain out of the midst of thee, & cease to stretch out the finger, & to speak that which profiteth not.
\v 10 When thou shalt pour out thy soul to the hungry, and shalt fill the afflicted soul, thy light shall arise up in darkness, & thy darkness shall be as the noon day.
\v 11 And our Lord will give thee rest always, & will fill thy soul with brightness, and deliver thy bones, and thou shalt be as a watered garden, and as a fountain of waters, whose waters shall not fail.
\v 12 And the deserts of the worlds shall be builded in thee, thou shalt raise up the foundations of generation and generation: and thou shalt be called the builder of the hedges, turning the paths into rest. \x + \xo 58:12 \xt Isa. 61.\x*
\v 13 If thou turn away thy foot from the Sabbath, from doing thy will in my holy day, and call the Sabbath delicate, and the holy of our Lord glorious, and glorify him, whilst thou doest not thine own ways, & thy will be not found, to speak a word:
\v 14 Then shalt thou be delighted upon the Lord, & I will lift thee up above the heights of the earth, & will feed thee with the inheritance of Jacob thy father. For the mouth of the Lord hath spoken.
\c 59
\p
\v 1 Behold the hand of our Lord is not abridged that he cannot save, neither is his ear made heavy that it cannot hear. \x + \xo 59:1 \xt Num. 11. Isa. 40.\x*
\v 2 But your iniquities have divided between you and your God, and your sins have hid his face from you that he would not hear. \f + \fr 59:2 \ft No defect is in God's power nor will, that he delivereth not the faithful from afflictions, but their sins are the impediment; for which he punisheth them, that they may repent, & then he will deliver them, v. 20.\f*
\v 3 For your hands are polluted with blood and your fingers with iniquity: your lips have spoken lie, and your tongue speaketh iniquity.
\v 4 There is none that doth invocate justice, neither is there any that judgeth truly: but they trust in things of nothing, and speak vanities: they have conceived labour, and brought forth iniquity. \x + \xo 59:4 \xt Iob. 15.\x*
\v 5 They have broken the eggs of asps, & have woven the spider's webs: he that shall eat of their eggs, shall die: and that which is nourished, shall be hatched into a cockatrice.
\v 6 Their webs shall not be for clothing, neither shall they be covered with their works: their works are unprofitable works, and the work of iniquity is in their hands.
\v 7 Their feet run to evil, & hasten to shed innocent blood: their cogitations are unprofitable cogitations: waste & destruction are in their ways. \x + \xo 59:7 \xt Prov. 1. Rom. 1.\x*
\v 8 They have not known the way of peace, and there is no judgement in their steps: their paths are become crooked to them: every one that treadeth in them, knoweth not peace.
\v 9 For this cause is judgement far from us, & justice shall not apprehend us. We expected light, and behold darkness: brightness, & we have walked in darkness.
\v 10 We have groped as blind men for the wall, and as without eyes have feeled: we have stumbled at noon day as in darkness, in dark places as the dead.
\v 11 We all shall roar as bears, and as mourning doves we shall lament. We have expected judgement, and there is none: salvation, and it is far from us.
\v 12 For our iniquities are multiplied before thee and our sins have answered to us: because our wicked doings are with us, & our iniquities we have known,
\v 13 to sin and lie against our Lord: and we were turned away so that we went not after our God, that we spake calumny and transgression: we conceived, and spake from the heart words of lying.
\v 14 And judgement was turned backward, and justice stood far off: because truth hath fallen down in the street, and equity could not enter in.
\v 15 And truth grew into oblivion: and he that departed from evil, lay open to the prey: and our Lord saw, and it appeared evil in his eyes, because there is no judgement.
\v 16 And he saw that there is not a man: & he was astonished, because there is none to oppose himself: and his own arm saved to himself, and his justice it-self confirmed him. \f + \fr 59:16 \ft No pure man being able to redeem, and deliver mankind from captivity of sin, God became man to accomplish this work.\f*
\v 17 He is clothed with justice as with a breastplate, and is an helmet of salvation on his head: he is clothed with garments of revenge, and is covered as with a mantle of zeal. \x + \xo 59:17 \xt Ephes. 6. 1. Thes. 5.\x*
\v 18 As unto revenge as it were unto retribution of indignation to his adversaries, and recompense to his enemies: he will repay the like to the islands.
\v 19 And they of the West shall fear the name of our Lord: and they of the rising of the sun, his glory: when he shall come as a violent stream, which the spirit of our Lord driveth:
\v 20 and there shall come a redeemer to Sion, and to them, that return from iniquity in Jacob, saith our Lord. \x + \xo 59:20 \xt Rom. 11.\x*
\v 21 This is my covenant with them, saith our Lord: My spirit that is in thee, and my words that I have put in thy mouth, shall not depart out of thy mouth, and out of the mouth of thy seed, & out of the mouth of thy seed's seed, saith our Lord, from this present and for ever. \f + \fr 59:21 \ft The Church hath still the spirit of truth, and therefore can never err.\f*
\c 60
\p
\v 1 Arise, be illuminated Jerusalem: because thy light is come, & the glory of our Lord is risen upon thee: \f + \fr 60:1 \ft God preventing with grace, every one must cooperate by gratefully accepting this benefit, and so dispose himself to justification.\f*
\v 2 Because lo darkness shall cover the earth, & a mist the peoples: but upon thee shall our Lord arise, and his glory shall be seen upon thee. \f + \fr 60:2 \ft Only those that come into the Church receive the light of true faith, all others are in darkness.\f*
\v 3 And the Gentiles shall walk in thy light, and kings in the brightness of thy rising. \x + \xo 60:3 \xt Isa. 49.\x*
\v 4 Lift up thine eyes round about & see, all these are gathered together, they are come to thee: thy sons shall come from a far, & thy daughters shall rise from the side.
\v 5 Then shalt thou see, & abound, & thy heart shall marvel and be enlarged, when the multitude of the sea shall be converted to thee, the strength of Gentiles shall come to thee.
\v 6 The inundation of camels shall cover thee, the dromedaries of Madian and Epha: all of Saba shall come, bringing gold and frankincense: and shewing forth praise to our Lord. \f + \fr 60:6 \ft This prophecy began to be fulfilled when the 3. Sages came on swift beasts to adore Christ, and offered gifts. Mat. 2.\f*
\v 7 All the cattle of Cedar shall be gathered together unto thee, the rams of Nabaioth shall minister to thee: they shall be offered upon my placable altar, and I will glorify the house of my majesty.
\v 8 Who are these, that fly as clouds, and as doves to their windows?
\v 9 For the islands expect me, and the ships of the sea in the beginning, that I may bring thy sons from a far: their silver, & their gold with them, to the name of the Lord thy God, and to the holy one of Israel, because he hath glorified thee. \f + \fr 60:9 \ft This is fulfilled in great Brittany, Ireland, & other islands, as Tertullian, Origen, & S. Beda prove against the Jews: and S. Chrysostom against the Gentiles.\f*
\v 10 And the children of strangers shall build thy walls, and their kings shall minister to thee: for in mine indignation have I strucken thee, and in my reconciliation have I had mercy upon thee.
\v 11 And thy gates shall be open continually: day and night they shall not be shut, that the strength of the Gentiles may be brought to thee, and their kings may be brought. \f + \fr 60:11 \ft This was accomplished when the Roman Emperors, & other Monarchs & nations received the faith of Christ.\f* \x + \xo 60:11 \xt Apoc. 21. v. 25.\x*
\v 12 For the nation & the kingdom that shall not serve thee, shall perish: & the Gentiles shall be wasted with desolation.
\v 13 The glory of Libanus shall come to thee, the fir-tree, & box-tree, and pine-tree together, to adorn the place of my sanctification, and the place of my feet I will glorify. \f + \fr 60:13 \ft S. Ierom compelled (as he saith) to leave the historical sense, because it is not convenient to say, The walls & foundation of Jerusalem were adorned with precious stones, and the temple, which should be most glorious, was made of wood; expoundeth this place of excellent men. The holy most eloquent man Cyprian the Martyr, and the Confessor of our time Hilarius do they not seem to thee the high trees that have built the Church of God?\f*
\v 14 And the children of them that humbled thee, shall come crouching to thee, and all that detracted from thee shall adore the steps of thy feet, and shall call thee the city of the Lord, Sion of the holy one of Israel.
\v 15 For that thou wast forsaken, and hated, and there was none that passed by thee, I will make thee to be the pride of worlds, a joy unto generation & generation:
\v 16 & thou shalt suck the milk of the Gentiles, & thou shalt be nursed with the teat of kings: & thou shalt know that I am the Lord that save thee, and thy Redeemer the strong one of Jacob.
\v 17 For brass I will bring gold, and for iron I will bring silver: and for wood brass, and for stones iron: and I will make thy visitation peace, and thine overseers justice.
\v 18 Iniquity shall no more be heard in thy land, waste and destruction in thy borders, and salvation shall occupy thy walls, & praise thy gates. \x + \xo 60:18 \xt Apoc. 22. v. 23.\x*
\v 19 Thou shalt have the sun no more to shine by day, neither shall the brightness of the moon lighten thee: but the Lord shall be unto thee for an everlasting light, and thy God for thy glory. \x + \xo 60:19 \xt Apoc. 22. v. 5.\x*
\v 20 Thy sun shall go down no more, and thy moon shall not be diminished: because the Lord shall be unto thee for an everlasting light, & the days of thy mourning shall be ended.
\v 21 And thy people all just, for ever shall inherit the land, the bud of my planting, the work of mine hand to glorify.
\v 22 The least shall be into a thousand, and the little one into a most strong nation: I the Lord in the time thereof will suddenly do it.
\c 61
\p
\v 1 The spirit of the Lord upon me, because the Lord hath anointed me: to preach to the mild he sent me, that I should heal the contrite of heart, and preach indulgence to the captives, and deliverance to them that are shut up. \f + \fr 61:1 \ft Our Saviour was not, neither needed to be visibly anointed, as Aaron, David, & others were; but invisibly by God, with oil of gladness, above all others. Ps. 44. v. 8. with the Holy Ghost, and with power. Act. 10. v. 39. of whose fullness all others receive. Ioan. 1. v. 16.\f* \x + \xo 61:1 \xt Luc. 4. v. 18.\x*
\v 2 That I should preach the placable year to the Lord, & the day of vengeance of our God: that I might comfort all that mourn;
\v 3 that I might appoint to the mourners of Sion, & give them a crown for ashes, the oil of joy for mourning, a mantle of praise for the spirit of sorrowfulness: and they shall be called in it the strong of justice, planting of the Lord to glorify.
\v 4 And they shall build the deserts from the beginning of the world, and shall erect the old ruins; and shall repair the desolate cities, that were dissipated in generation and generation.
\v 5 And aliens shall stand, and feed your cattle: and the children shall be your husbandmen, and dressers of the vines.
\v 6 And you shall be called the Priests of the Lord: to you it shall be said: The ministers of our God: you shall eat the strength of the Gentiles, and in their glory you shall be proud.
\v 7 For your double confusion & shame, they shall praise their part: for this cause shall they receive double in their land, everlasting joy shall be to them. \f + \fr 61:7 \ft It was a grief and sorrow to the Apostles & first Preachers of Christ's Gospel, that both the Jews departed from God, & Gentiles still followed idolatry, but shortly after, many were converted.\f* \f + \fr 61:7 \ft And preferred their own happy lot before all other Jews & Gentiles.\f*
\v 8 Because I am the Lord that love judgement, & hate robbery in holocaust: and I will give their work in truth, and make a perpetual covenant with them.
\v 9 And they shall know their seed in the Gentiles, and their bud in the midst of peoples, all that shall see them, shall know them, that these are the seed which the Lord hath blessed.
\v 10 Rejoicing I will rejoice in our Lord, and my soul shall be joyful in my God: because he hath clothed me with the garments of salvation: and with the garment of justice he hath compassed me, as a bridegroom decked with a crown, and as a bride adorned with her jewels.
\v 11 For as the earth bringeth forth her spring, and as the garden shooteth forth his seed: so shall our Lord God make justice to spring forth, and praise before all the Gentiles.
\c 62
\p
\v 1 For Sion I will not hold my peace, and for Jerusalem, I will not rest, till her just one come forth as brightness, & her Saviour be kindled as a lamp. \f + \fr 62:1 \ft True Preachers and Pastors cease not from preaching the truth, for any threats, terror, or torment. But say with this Prophet: For Sion (that is, for the good of the Church) I will not cease &c. & with S. Paul. The word of God is not tied. 2. Tim. 2.\f*
\v 2 And the Gentiles shall see thy just one, and all kings thy noble one: and thou shalt be called by a new name, which the mouth of our Lord shall name.
\v 3 And thou shalt be a crown of glory in the hand of our Lord, & the diadem of a kingdom in the hand of thy God.
\v 4 Thou shalt no more be called, Forsaken: & thy land shall no more be called, Desolate: But thou shalt be called, My will in her, and thy land inhabited, because it hath well pleased our Lord in thee: & thy land shall be inhabited.
\v 5 For the young man shall dwell with the virgin, and thy children shall dwell in thee. And the bridegroom shall rejoice upon the bride, & thy God shall rejoice upon thee.
\v 6 Upon thy walls, Jerusalem, I have appointed watch-men, all the day, and all the night, for ever they shall not hold their peace. You that remember our Lord, hold not your peace, \f + \fr 62:6 \ft The Church of Christ is perpetually visible in her watch-men, the Pastors & Governers thereof.\f*
\v 7 & give not silence to him, until he establish, and until he make Jerusalem the praise in the earth.
\v 8 Our Lord hath sworn by his right hand, and by the arm of his strength: If I shall give thy wheat any more to be meat for thine enemies: and if the strange children shall drink thy wine, wherein thou hast laboured.
\v 9 Because they that shall gather it together, shall eat it, and shall praise the Lord: and they that carry it together, shall drink it in my holy courts.
\v 10 Pass ye, pass ye through the gates, prepare a way for the people, make the journey plain, & pick up the stones, & lift up the sign to the peoples.
\v 11 Behold our Lord hath made heard in the ends of the earth, tell the daughter of Sion: Behold thy Saviour cometh: behold his reward is with him, and his work before him. \x + \xo 62:11 \xt Mat 21. Zach. 9.\x*
\v 12 And they shall call them, The holy people, the redeemed of our Lord. But thou shalt be called, A city sought for, and not Forsaken.
\c 63
\p
\v 1 Who is this that cometh from Edom, with dyed garments from Bosra, this beautiful one in his robe, going in the multitude of his strength? I that speak justice, and am a defender to save. \f + \fr 63:1 \ft S. Dionyse, Hierar. cælest. c. 7. supposeth this to be the question of the highest order to Angels, admiring Christ's beauty to be so excellent, notwithstanding that he is imbrued with blood ascending from Edom (which signifieth terrestrial ) from Bosra (a walled city overthrown) that is, from Jerusalem into heaven, with triumph after a bloody victory.\f*
\v 2 Why then is thy clothing red, and thy garments as theirs that tread in the wine-press? \x + \xo 63:2 \xt Apoc. 19. v. 13.\x*
\v 3 I have trodden the press alone, and of the Gentiles there is not a man with me: I have trodden them in my fury, and have trodden them down in my wrath: & their blood is sprinkled upon my garments, & I have stained all my raiment.
\v 4 For the day of revenge is in my heart, the year of my redemption is come.
\v 5 I looked about, & there was no helper: I sought, and there was none to aid: and mine arm hath saved, and mine indignation it-self hath holpen me.
\v 6 And I have trodden down the peoples in my fury, and have inebriated them in mine indignation, and have drawn their strength down to the ground.
\v 7 I will remember the mercies of our Lord, the praise of our Lord for all things, that our Lord hath rendered to us, and for the multitude of the good things to the house of Israel, which he hath given them according to his indulgence, and according to the multitude of his mercies.
\v 8 And he said: But yet is my people, children that deny not: and he is become their saviour.
\v 9 In all their tribulation he was not troubled, and the Angel of his face saved them: in his love, and in his indulgence he redeemed them, and bare them, and lifted them up all the days of the world. \f + \fr 63:9 \ft The Angel guardian of the Church, which standeth before the face of God; Christ testifying that also the particular guardians do always see the face of his Father. Mat. 18.\f*
\v 10 But they provoked to wrath, and afflicted the spirit of his holy one: and he was turned to be their enemy, and he conquered them.
\v 11 And he remembered the days of the world of Moyses, and of his people: Where is he that brought them out of the sea, with the Pastors of his flock? Where is he that put in the midst of him the spirit of his holy one? \x + \xo 63:11 \xt Exo. 14.\x*
\v 12 He that brought out Moyses to the right hand by the arm of his majesty: that divided the waters before them, that he might make to himself an everlasting name.
\v 13 He that brought them out through the depths, as an horse in the desert that stumbled not.
\v 14 As the beast that goeth down in the plain field, the spirit of our Lord was their conductor: so didst thou bring thy people that thou mightest make thee a name of glory.
\v 15 Attend from heaven, and look from thy holy habitation, & of thy glory: where is thy zeal, and thy strength, the multitude of thy bowels, and of thy mercies? They have held back themselves toward me. \x + \xo 63:15 \xt Deu. 26. Bar. 2.\x*
\v 16 For thou art our father, and Abraham hath not known us, and Israel hath been ignorant of us: thou, o Lord, art our father, our Redeemer, from the beginning is thy name.
\v 17 Why hast thou made us err, o Lord, from thy ways: hast thou hardened our heart, that we feared not thee? Return for thy servants, the tribes of thine inheritance. \f + \fr 63:17 \ft God is never the cause of error or hardness of heart: but by indulgence not punishing, sinners harden their own hearts. so S. Ierom.\f*
\v 18 As nothing have they possessed thy holy people: our enemies have trodden down thy sanctification.
\v 19 We are become as in the beginning, when thou didst not rule over us, neither was thy name invocated upon us.
\c 64
\p
\v 1 Would God thou wouldest break the heavens asunder, and wouldst descend: at thy presence the mountains should melt away. \f + \fr 64:1 \ft The good people, with Priests and Prophets of the old Testament most fervently desired Christ's coming.\f*
\v 2 As the burning of fire would they melt, the waters would burn with fire, that thy name might be made known to thine enemies: at thy presence the nations should be troubled.
\v 3 When thou shalt do marvelous things, we shall not sustain: thou art descended, and at thy presence the mountains are melted.
\v 4 From the beginning of the world they have not heard, nor received with the ears: the eye hath not seen, o God, beside thee, what things thou hast prepared for them that expect thee. \x + \xo 64:4 \xt 1. Cor. 2.\x*
\v 5 Thou hast met him that rejoiceth, and doth justice: in thy ways they shall remember thee: behold thou art angry, and we have sinned: we have been always in them, and we shall be saved. \f + \fr 64:5 \ft And, signifieth for, as Gen. 14. v. 8. And the English Bibles translate for, in this place, though the Hebrew text hath vau, that is, and. But we with S. Ierom and other ancient Fathers follow the authentical Latin: which hath, et in this place, & enim in the other.\f* \f + \fr 64:5 \ft Likewise the same particle and signifieth yet, as if he had said: yet we shall be saved.\f*
\v 6 And all we are become as one unclean, and all our justices as the cloth of a menstrued woman: and we have all fallen as a leaf, and our iniquities as the wind have taken us away.
\v 7 There is none that invocateth thy name: that riseth up, and holdeth thee, thou hast hid thy face from us, and hast dashed us in the hand of our iniquity.
\v 8 And now Lord thou art our father, & we clay: and thou art our maker, and all we the works of thy hands.
\v 9 Be not angry, o Lord, enough, and remember no more our iniquity: lo regard, all we are thy people. \x + \xo 64:9 \xt Psal. 78.\x*
\v 10 The city of thy holy one is made desert, Sion is made desert, Jerusalem is become desolate.
\v 11 The house of our sanctification, and of our glory, where our fathers praised thee, is turned into the burning of fire, and all our things worthy to be desired are turned into ruins.
\v 12 Wilt thou upon these things contain thyself, o Lord, wilt thou hold thy peace, and afflict us vehemently?
\c 65
\p
\v 1 They have sought me that before asked not, they have found that sought me not, I said: Behold me, behold me, to a Gentility that did not invocate my name. \f + \fr 65:1 \ft This cannot be meant of the Jews, but necessarily of the Gentiles.\f* \x + \xo 65:1 \xt Ro. 10.\x*
\v 2 I have spread forth mine hands all the day to an incredulous people, which goeth in a way not good after their own cogitations. \f + \fr 65:2 \ft But this is evidently spoken of the Jews: and so S. Paul testifieth of both these places. Rom. 10. v. 20. 21.\f*
\v 3 Apeople that provoke me to anger before my face always: that immolate in gardens, and sacrifice upon bricks.
\v 4 That dwell in sepulchres, and sleep in temples of idols: that eat swine's flesh, and profane potage in their vessels.
\v 5 That say: Depart from me, approach not to me, because thou art unclean: these shall be smoke in my fury, a fire burning all the day.
\v 6 Behold it is written before me: I will not hold my peace, but I will render and repay into their bosom
\v 7 your iniquities, and the iniquities of your fathers together, saith our Lord, that have sacrificed upon the mountains, and upon the little hills have reproached me, & I will remeasure their first work in their bosom.
\v 8 Thus saith our Lord: As if a berry be found in a cluster, and it be said: Destroy it not, because it is a blessing: so will I do for my servants' sake, that I destroy not the whole.
\v 9 And I will bring forth seed out of Jacob, & out of Juda a possessor of my mountains: & mine elect shall inherit it, and my servants shall inhabit there.
\v 10 And the champion countries shall be into folds of flocks, and the valley of Achor for the couch of herds, unto my people that have sought after me.
\v 11 And you, that have forsaken the Lord, that have forgotten my holy mount, that set a table to Fortune, and offer libaments upon it.
\v 12 I will number you in the sword, and you shall all fall by slaughter: because I called, and you have not answered: I spake, and you have not heard, and you did evil in mine eyes: and you have chosen the things, that I would not. \f + \fr 65:12 \ft Nothing can be more plainly uttered than is here the doctrine of man's freewill.\f* \x + \xo 65:12 \xt Prov. 1. Iere. 7.\x*
\v 13 For this cause thus saith our Lord God: Behold my servants shall eat, and you shall be hungry: behold my servants shall drink, and you shall be thirsty. \f + \fr 65:13 \ft Likewise of reward & punishment of good and evil works.\f*
\v 14 Behold my servants shall rejoice, and you shall be confounded: behold my servants shall praise for joyfulness of heart: and you shall cry for sorrow of heart, and for contrition of spirit you shall howl.
\v 15 And you shall leave your name for an oath to mine elect: and the Lord God shall kill thee, and will call his servants by another name. \f + \fr 65:15 \ft The name of Jews shall be execrable.\f* \f + \fr 65:15 \ft And God's servants shall be called Christians.\f* \f + \fr 65:15 \ft * Oath of execration.\f*
\v 16 In which he that is blessed upon the earth, shall be blessed in God, Amen: & he that sweareth in the earth, shall swear by God Amen: because the former distresses are forgotten, & because they are hid from mine eyes.
\v 17 For behold I create new heavens, & a new earth: & the former things shall not be in memory, & they shall not ascend upon the heart. \f + \fr 65:17 \ft After the general Resurrection the heavens and earth shall be altered in qualities, not in substance.\f* \x + \xo 65:17 \xt Apo. 21.\x*
\v 18 But you shall be glad & rejoice for ever in these things, which I create: because lo I create Jerusalem exultation, and the people thereof joy.
\v 19 And I will rejoice in Jerusalem, and be glad in my people, and there shall no more be heard in it the voice of weeping, and the voice of crying.
\v 20 There shall no more be a child of days, & an old man that shall not fill up his days, because the child of an hundred years shall die, and the sinner of an hundred years shall be accurst.
\v 21 And they shall build cities, and inhabit: and they shall plant vineyards, and eat the fruits thereof.
\v 22 They shall not build, and another shall dwell: they shall not plant, & another shall eat: for according to the days of the tree, shall be the days of my people, and they shall make old the works of their hands.
\v 23 Mine elect shall not labour in vain, nor engender in conturbation: because it is the seed of the blessed of the Lord, and their posterity with them.
\v 24 And it shall be, before they call, I will hear: as they are yet speaking, I will hear. \x + \xo 65:24 \xt Psal. 31.\x*
\v 25 The wolf and the lamb shall feed together, the lion and the oxe shall eat straw: & to the serpent dust shall be his bread: they shall not hurt, nor kill in all my holy mountain, saith our Lord. \f + \fr 65:25 \ft The greatest and proudest Gentiles being converted to Christ, do humble themselves to the simple manners of Christians, to penance, fasting, praying, and all works of mortification.\f*
\c 66
\p
\v 1 Thus saith our Lord: Heaven is my seat, and the earth my foot stool: what is this house that you will build to me? And what is this place of my rest? \f + \fr 66:1 \ft Aprophecy that the Temple shall cease:\f* \x + \xo 66:1 \xt Act. 7. v. 49.\x*
\v 2 My hand hath made all these things, & all these things have been done, saith our Lord. But to whom shall I have respect, but to the poor little one, & the contrite of spirit, and him that trembleth at my words?
\v 3 He that immolateth an oxe, is as he that should slay a man: he that killeth a sheep in sacrifice, as he that should brain a dog: he that offereth oblation, as he that should offer swine's blood: he that remembereth frankincense, as he that should bless an idol. All these things have they chosen in their ways, and in their abominations their soul is delighted. \f + \fr 66:3 \ft and sacrifices of the old Testament shall become unlawful.\f*
\v 4 Wherefore I also will choose their delusions: and the things that they feared, I will bring to them: because I called, and there was none that would answer: I have spoken, and they heard not: & they have done evil in mine eyes, and have chosen the things that I would not. \x + \xo 66:4 \xt Prov. 24. Iere. 7. v. 13.\x*
\v 5 Hear the word of our Lord, ye that tremble at his word: your brethren that hate you, and reject you for my name sake, have said: Let the Lord be glorified, & we shall see in your joy: but they shall be confounded.
\v 6 Avoice of people from the city, a voice from the temple, the voice of our Lord repaying retribution to his enemies. \f + \fr 66:6 \ft Iosephus expoundeth this of the Angel's voice uttered in the temple before the destruction, saying: Migremus hinc: Let us depart from hence. S. Ierome confirmeth the same by the words of the Psalm. 54. I saw contradiction in the city.\f*
\v 7 Before she travailed, she brought forth, before her time came to be delivered, she brought forth a man child.
\v 8 Who ever heard such a thing? & who hath seen the like to this? Why, shall the earth travail in one day? Or shall a nation be brought forth together, because Sion hath travailed, & brought forth her children?
\v 9 Shall not I that make others to bring forth children, myself bring forth, saith the Lord? Shall I, that give generation to others, be barren, saith the Lord thy God? \f + \fr 66:9 \ft God giveth natural power to all living creatures of generation: but himself bringeth forth children of his Church.\f*
\v 10 Rejoice with Jerusalem, & be joyful in her all ye that love her: be glad with her in gladness all ye, that mourn upon her,
\v 11 that you may suck, & be filled of the breast of her consolation: that you may milk, & flow with delights in all manner of her glory.
\v 12 Because thus saith our Lord: Behold I will decline upon her as it were a flood of peace, and as a torrent overflowing the glory of the Gentiles, which you shall suck: at the breasts, you shall be carried, & upon the knees they shall speak you fair.
\v 13 As if the mother would speak one fair, so will I comfort you, & in Jerusalem you shall be comforted.
\v 14 You shall see, & your heart shall rejoice, and your bones shall spring as an herb, and the hand of our Lord shall be known to his servants, & he shall be wrath with his enemies.
\v 15 Because lo our Lord will come in fire, & his chariots as a whirlwind, to render his fury in indignation, & his rebuking in flame of fire: \f + \fr 66:15 \ft Immediately before Christ come to judge, this whole world shall be destroyed by fire.\f*
\v 16 because our Lord shall judge in fire, & in his sword to all flesh, and the slain of our Lord shall be multiplied,
\v 17 they that were sanctified, & thought themselves clean in the gardens behind the gate within, they that did eat swine's flesh, and abomination, and the mouse: they shall be confounded, saith our Lord.
\v 18 But I know their works, and their cogitations: I come that I may gather together, with all nations and tongues: and they shall come and shall see my glory.
\v 19 And I will put a sign in them, and I will send of them, that shall be saved, to the Gentiles into the sea, into Afrike, & Lydia, them that hold the arrow: into Italy, and Greece; to the islands far off, to them that have not heard of me, and have not seen my glory. And they shall shew forth my glory to the Gentiles: \f + \fr 66:19 \ft Christ ascending to his Father left the sign of (Thau Ezech. 9.) the cross, unto us, or put it in our foreheads, that we may freely say: the light of thy countenance is signed upon us. S. Ierom in hunc locum.\f*
\v 20 and they shall bring all your brethren of all nations a gift to our Lord, upon horses, and in chariots, & in horse-litters, & on mules, and in coaches, to my holy mountain Jerusalem, saith our Lord, as if the children of Israel should bring in a gift in a clean vessel into the house of our Lord. \f + \fr 66:20 \ft Men of all nations shall be brought into the Church by the ministry of particular Angels. S. Iero. ibid.\f*
\v 21 And I will take of them to be Priests, & Levites, saith our Lord.
\v 22 Because as new heavens, and a new earth, which I make to stand before me, saith our Lord: so shall your seed stand, and your name. \x + \xo 66:22 \xt Apo. 21.\x*
\v 23 And there shall be month after month, and sabbath after sabbath: all flesh shall come to adore before my face, saith our Lord. \f + \fr 66:23 \ft General resurrection of all men.\f*
\v 24 And they shall go out, and see the carcasses of the men, that have transgressed against me: their worm shall not die, and their fire shall not be quenched: and they shall be even unto satiety of sight to all flesh. \x + \xo 66:24 \xt Mar. 9. v. 44.\x*
